{"title_page": "Pat Carroll", "text_new": "{{short description|American actress}}\n{{other people}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name = Pat Carroll\n| image = Pat Carroll 1972.JPG\n| caption = Carroll in 1972\n| birth_name = Patricia Ann Carroll\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1927|5|5}}\n| birth_place = [[Shreveport, Louisiana]], U.S.\n| other_names = Pat Ann Carroll<br />Patricia Carroll\n| occupation = Actress, voice actress, singer\n| years_active = 1947\u2013present\n| notable_works = Voice of [[Ursula (The Little Mermaid)|Ursula the Sea Witch]] in Disney's ''[[The Little Mermaid (1989 film)|The Little Mermaid]]'' (1989)\n| spouse = {{marriage|Lee Karsian|1955|1976|end=divorced}}\n| domestic_partner = \n| children = 3, including [[Tara Karsian]]\n| television = ''[[The Danny Thomas Show|Make Room for Daddy]]'', ''[[Laverne & Shirley]]'', ''[[ER (TV series)|ER]]'' \n}}\n'''Patricia Ann Carroll''' (born May 5, 1927) is an American actress, voice actress, and singer. She is known for voicing [[Ursula (Disney)|Ursula]] in ''[[The Little Mermaid (1989 film)|The Little Mermaid]]'' as well as having a long acting career, including appearances in [[CBS]]'s ''[[The Danny Thomas Show]]'', [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]]'s ''[[Laverne & Shirley]]'', [[NBC]]'s ''[[ER (TV series)|ER]]'', other guest-starring and series-regular roles on American television as well as voice-acting in several cartoon series. Carroll is an [[Emmy Award|Emmy]], [[Drama Desk Award|Drama Desk]] and [[Grammy Award|Grammy]] Award winner and a [[Tony Award]] nominee.\n\n==Early life==\nCarroll was born in [[Shreveport, Louisiana]], on May 5, 1927, to Maurice Clifton Carroll and Kathryn Angela (n\u00e9e Meagher)<ref name = \"Film Reference\">{{cite web|title=Pat Carroll Biography (1927-)|url=http://www.filmreference.com/film/33/Pat-Carroll.html|publisher=FilmReference.Com/City-Data.Com|accessdate=May 26, 2013}}</ref>  Her family moved to [[Los Angeles]] when Pat was five years old and she soon began acting in local productions. She graduated from [[Immaculate Heart High School (Los Angeles)|Immaculate Heart High School]] and attended [[Catholic University of America]] after enlisting in the [[United States Army]] as a civilian actress technician.<ref name=\"BU\">{{cite web|title=Pat Carroll|url=http://www.bu.edu/phpbin/archives-cc/app/details.php?id=7536|publisher=Howard Gotlieb Archival Research Center Boston University|accessdate=May 26, 2013}}{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nIn 1956, Carroll won an [[Emmy Award]] for her work on ''[[Caesar's Hour]]'' and was a regular on the sitcom ''[[Make Room for Daddy]]'' from 1961 to 1964. She guest starred in the drama [[anthology series]] ''[[The DuPont Show with June Allyson]]''. Carroll also appeared on many [[variety show]]s of the 1950s, 1960s and 1970s, such as ''[[The Red Buttons Show]]'', ''[[The Danny Kaye Show]]'', ''[[The Red Skelton Show]]'', and ''[[The Carol Burnett Show]]''. In 1965 she co-starred as \"Prunella\", one of the wicked stepsisters in the 1965 production of [[Rodgers and Hammerstein]]'s musical version of ''[[Cinderella (Rodgers and Hammerstein musical)|Cinderella]]''.\n\nIn the late 1970s Carroll's successful one woman show on [[Gertrude Stein]], ''Gertrude Stein, Gertrude Stein, Gertrude Stein'' (by playwright Marty Martin), won several major theater awards;<ref>{{cite news|last=Casselberry Manuel|first=Diane|title=Pat Carroll; Gertrude Stein was never a bore|url=http://www.csmonitor.com/1981/0108/010861.html|accessdate=May 26, 2013|newspaper=[[The Christian Science Monitor]]|date=January 8, 1981}}</ref> her recorded version won a 1980 [[Grammy Award]] for Best Spoken Word, Documentary or Drama.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.grammy.com/nominees/search?artist=pat+carroll&field_nominee_work_value=Gertrude+Stein%2C+Gertrude+Stein%2C+Gertrude+Stein&year=1980&genre=All|title=1980 Best Spoken Word, Documentary Or Drama|publisher=Grammy.Org/The Recording Academy|accessdate=May 26, 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn early 1976, Carroll was cast as Lily, the mother of Shirley Feeney (played by [[Cindy Williams]]) in the episode \"Mother Knows Worst\" on the hit ''[[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]]'' [[situation comedy]], ''[[Laverne & Shirley]]''.<ref name = \"JimHill\">{{cite web|last=Hill|first=Jim|title=Why (For) Pat Carroll wasn't actually Disney's first choice to voice Ursula in \"The Little Mermaid\"|url=http://jimhillmedia.com/editor_in_chief1/b/jim_hill/archive/2007/06/15/why-for-pat-carroll-wasn-t-actually-disney-s-first-choice-to-voice-ursula-in-the-little-mermaid.aspx#.UaJqmhzIBgI|publisher=JimHillMedia|accessdate=May 26, 2013}}</ref> She portrayed Pearl Markowitz, the mother of [[Adam Arkin]]{{'}}s character Lenny Markowitz, in the 1977 [[CBS]] situation comedy ''[[Busting Loose (TV series)|Busting Loose]]''. Her frequent television roles in the 1980s included newspaper owner Hope Stinson on the syndicated ''The Ted Knight Show'' (the former ''[[Too Close for Comfort]]'') during its final season in 1986; and that of Gussie Holt, the mother of [[Suzanne Somers]]' lead character in the syndicated sitcom ''[[She's the Sheriff]]'' (1987\u20131989).\n\nSince the late 1980s, Carroll has had a great deal of voice-over work on animated programs<ref name = \"JimHill\"/> such as ''[[A Pup Named Scooby-Doo]]'', ''[[Galaxy High]]'', ''[[Foofur]]'' and ''[[A Goofy Movie]]''. On TV's ''[[Pound Puppies (1986 TV series)|Pound Puppies]]'', she voiced [[Katrina Stoneheart]]. On two ''[[Garfield]]'' television specials (''[[A Garfield Christmas]]'' and ''[[Garfield's Thanksgiving]]''), she portrayed [[Jon Arbuckle|Jon]]'s feisty Grandmother.  She also voiced the  character of Granny in the 2005 re-release of [[Hayao Miyazaki]]'s ''[[My Neighbor Totoro]]''.<ref name = \"Film Reference\"/>\n\nIn 1989, Carroll portrayed the sea witch Ursula in Disney's ''[[The Little Mermaid (1989 film)|The Little Mermaid]]'' and sang \"[[Poor Unfortunate Souls]]\".<ref name = \"JimHill\"/> In interviews, Carroll has referred to the role as one of the favorites of her career.<ref>{{YouTube|sUwOeOiMC3I}}</ref> She has since reprised the role in other forms of media, including the ''[[Kingdom Hearts]]'' series of video games,<ref name = \"Film Reference\"/> the spinoff television series, and in various [[Disney theme parks]] attractions and shows.\n\nCarroll also appeared on a variety of game shows including ''[[Celebrity Sweepstakes]],'' ''[[You Don't Say]]'', ''[[To Tell the Truth]]'', ''[[Match Game 73]]'', ''[[Password]]'' and ''[[I've Got a Secret]]''.<ref name = \"Film Reference\"/>\n\nA member of [[the Actors Studio]], she has also had a successful career in the theater, appearing in numerous plays including productions of ''[[Our Town]]'' and Sophocles' ''[[Electra (Sophocles)|Electra]]''.<ref>{{cite news|authorlink1=Robert Simonson| last=Simonson| first=Robert| title=Stephen Spinella Joins Claire Bloom & Pat Carroll in NJ Electra Sept. 15| url=http://www.playbill.com/news/article/40761-Stephen-Spinella-Joins-Claire-Bloom-Pat-Carroll-in-NJ-Electra-Sept-15| archive-url=https://archive.is/20130630204824/http://www.playbill.com/news/article/40761-Stephen-Spinella-Joins-Claire-Bloom-Pat-Carroll-in-NJ-Electra-Sept-15|url-status=dead| archive-date=June 30, 2013| journal=[[Playbill]]| accessdate=May 26, 2013| author2=David Lefkowitz| date=September 4, 1998}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| title=A Conversation With Pat Carroll at the High Falls Film Festival, May 14, 2009| url=http://thefilmpanelnotetaker.com/a-conversation-with-pat-carroll-at-the-high-falls-film-festival-may-14-2009| publisher=The Film Panel Notetaker| accessdate=May 26, 2013| date=May 21, 2009| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140513104242/http://thefilmpanelnotetaker.com/a-conversation-with-pat-carroll-at-the-high-falls-film-festival-may-14-2009|archivedate=May 13, 2014}}</ref>  In 1990, she starred in ''[[The Merry Wives of Windsor]]'' at the [[Shakespeare Theatre Company|Shakespeare Theatre at the Folger]] in the role of [[Sir John Falstaff]], a balding knight with whiskers.<ref name = \"Rich\">{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/1990/05/30/theater/review-theater-pat-carroll-as-falstaff-in-merry-wives-at-folger.html| title=Review/Theater; Pat Carroll as Falstaff in 'Merry Wives' at Folger| last=Rich| first=Frank |date=May 30, 1990| work=The New York Times| accessdate=20 January 2011}}</ref>\n\nWhen drama critic [[Frank Rich]] of ''[[The New York Times]]'' reviewed her performance he wrote, \"Her performance is a triumph from start to finish, and, I think, a particularly brave and moving one, with implications that go beyond this one production. Ms. Carroll and Mr. Kahn help revivify the argument that the right actresses can perform some of the great classic roles traditionally denied to women and make them their own. It's not a new argument, to be sure; female Hamlets stretch back into history. But what separates Ms. Carroll's Falstaff from some other similar casting experiments of late is that her performance exists to investigate a character rather than merely as ideological window dressing for a gimmicky production.\"<ref name = \"Rich\"/>\n\n==Personal life==\nCarroll married Lee Karsian in 1955 and they had three children<ref name = \"BU\"/> - two daughters, Kerry and [[Tara Karsian]] and a son, Sean.<ref name = \"Film Reference\"/>  In 1991 Carroll received an honorary doctorate from [[Siena College]] in [[Albany, New York]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Honorary Degrees - Past Recipients|url=http://www.siena.edu/pages/5696.asp|publisher=Siena College|accessdate=May 26, 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120604033444/http://www.siena.edu/pages/5696.asp|archivedate=June 4, 2012}}</ref> Carroll is a practicing [[Roman Catholic]] citing that her religious views help her to determine what projects to accept.<ref>{{cite web| title=Pat Carroll| url=http://www.behindthevoiceactors.com/Pat-Carroll/| publisher=Behind the Voice Actors| accessdate=July 13, 2018}}</ref> She is a [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]].\n\n==Filmography==\n\n===Film===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\" | Year\n!style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\" | Title\n!style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\" | Role\n!style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\" | Notes\n\n|-\n| 1967\n|''[[The Ballad of Josie]]'' \n| Elizabeth\n|\n|-\n| 1968\n|''[[With Six You Get Eggroll]]'' \n| Maxine Scott\n|\n|-\n| 1984\n| ''[[Racing with the Moon]]'' \n| Mrs. Spangler \n| \n|-\n| 1985\n| ''[[The Trip to Bountiful]]'' \n| Rosella \n| \n|-\n| 1988\n| ''[[My Neighbor Totoro]]'' \n| Granny \n|Voice, 2005 Disney redub \n|-\n| 1989 \n| ''[[The Little Mermaid (1989 film)|The Little Mermaid]]'' \n| [[Ursula (Disney)|Ursula]] \n|Voice\n|-\n| rowspan=2|2000\n| ''[[Songcatcher]]'' \n| Viney Butler\n|\n|-\n| ''[[The Little Mermaid II: Return to the Sea]]''\n| Morgana\n|Voice\n|-\n| 2001 \n| ''[[Mickey's Magical Christmas: Snowed in at the House of Mouse]]'' \n| [[Ursula (The Little Mermaid)|Ursula]] \n|Voice\n|-\n| 2002 \n| ''[[Mickey's House of Villains]]'' \n| [[Ursula (The Little Mermaid)|Ursula]] \n|Voice\n|-\n| rowspan=2|2007\n| ''[[Freedom Writers]]'' \n| [[Miep Gies]]\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Nancy Drew (2007 film)|Nancy Drew]]'' \n| Landlady<ref name = \"Film Reference\"/>\n|\n|-\n| 2014\n| ''[[BFFs]]''\n| Joan\n|\n|}\n\n===Television===\n{{div col|colwidth=22em}}\n* ''[[The Red Buttons Show]]'' (1952\u20131953)\n* ''The Saturday Night Revue'' (1953)\n* ''[[Make Room for Daddy]]'' (1953) - Bunny Halper\n* ''[[The Pepsi-Cola Playhouse]]'' (1954)\n* ''[[Studio 57]]'' (1954) - Sue\n* ''[[Caesar's Hour]]'' (1954) - Alice Brewster\n* ''[[Producers' Showcase]]'' (1955) - Gym teacher\n* ''[[Kraft Television Theatre]]'' (1955)\n* ''[[The Jimmy Durante Show]]'' (1955)\n* ''[[The Steve Allen Show]]'' (1958)\n* ''[[Hobby Lobby (TV series)|Hobby Lobby]]'' (1959)\n* ''[[General Electric Theater]]'' (1959) - Frances Dowd\n* ''[[The DuPont Show with June Allyson]]'' (1959) - Cherry\n* ''[[The Ann Sothern Show]]'' (1961) - Pandora\n* ''[[The Investigators (American TV series)|The Investigators]]'' (1961)\n* ''[[The United States Steel Hour]]'' (1961)\n* ''[[The Red Skelton Show]]'' (1962)\n* ''[[Cinderella (Rodgers and Hammerstein musical)|Cinderella]]'' (1965) - Prunella\n* ''[[Please Don't Eat the Daisies]]'' (1966) - Carol Baker\n* ''[[The Carol Burnett Show]]'' (1971) \u2014 Herself; Two appearances in 1971 (Season 4, Episodes 16 and 23) \n* ''[[The Mary Tyler Moore Show]]'' (1971) - Loretta Kuhne\n* ''[[The Interns (TV series)|The Interns]]'' (1971) - Maria\n* ''[[Love, American Style]]'' (1970\u20131971)\n* ''[[Getting Together]]''  (1971-1972) - Rita Simon\n* ''[[Police Story (1973 TV series)|Police Story]]'' (1974) - Mrs. Bannister\n* ''[[Nakia (TV series)|Nakia]]'' (1974) - Belle Jones in episode \"A Matter of Choice\"\n* ''[[Laverne & Shirley]]'' (1976) - Mrs. Feeney\n* ''[[Good Heavens]]'' (1976) - Harriet\n* ''[[Busting Loose (TV series)|Busting Loose]]'' (1977) - Pearl Markowitz\n* ''[[Police Woman (TV series)|Police Woman]]'' (1977) - Miriam Stein\n* ''[[The Love Boat]]'' (1978)\n* ''[[Legends of the Superheroes]]'' (1979) - Esther Hall\n* ''[[Trapper John, M.D.]]'' (1985) - Aunt Mo\n* ''[[Crazy Like a Fox (TV series)|Crazy Like a Fox]]'' (1985)\n* ''[[Yogi's Treasure Hunt]]'' (1985) - Additional Voices\n* ''[[Pound Puppies (1986 TV series)|Pound Puppies]]'' (1986) - Katrina Stoneheart\n* ''[[Galaxy High School]]'' (1986) - Ms. Biddy McBrain\n* ''[[Foofur]]'' (1986\u20131987) -  Hazel\n* ''[[Too Close for Comfort]]'' (1986) - Mrs. Hope Stinson\n* ''[[A Garfield Christmas]]'' (1987) - Grandma\n* ''[[She's the Sheriff]]'' (1987\u20131989) - Gussie Holt\n* ''[[Superman (1988 TV series)|Superman]]'' (1988) - Queen Hippolyta\n* ''[[A Pup Named Scooby-Doo]]'' (1989) - Paula P. Casso\n* ''[[Garfield's Thanksgiving]]'' (1989) - Grandma\n* ''[[Chip 'n Dale Rescue Rangers]]'' (1990) - Koo-Koo\n* ''[[Designing Women]]'' (1993) - Mrs. Beecham\n* ''[[The Little Mermaid (TV series)|The Little Mermaid]]'' (1993\u20131994) - [[Ursula (The Little Mermaid)|Ursula]]\n* ''The Royale'' (1996)\n* ''[[Songcatcher]]'' (2000) - Viney Butler\n* ''[[House of Mouse]]'' (2001\u20132002) - Ursula (voice, 5 episodes)\n* ''[[ER (TV series)|ER]]'' (2005) - Rebecca Chadwick (3 episodes)<ref name = \"Film Reference\"/>\n* ''[[Tangled: The Series]]'' (2017-2018) - Old Lady Crowley (short:\"Make me smile\" and episodes:\"One Angry Princess\", \"Max's Enemy\", \"Secret of the Sun Drop\" .) \n{{div col end}}\n\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-break}}\n\n===Video games===\n* ''[[Kingdom Hearts (video game)|Kingdom Hearts]]'' (2002) - Ursula (voice)\n* ''[[Kingdom Hearts: Chain of Memories]]'' (2004) - Ursula (voice)<ref name = \"Film Reference\"/>\n* ''[[Kingdom Hearts II]]'' (2005) - Ursula (voice)\n* ''[[Kingdom Hearts 3D: Dream Drop Distance]]'' (2012) - Ursula (voice)\n* ''[[Kingdom Hearts 1.5 HD Remix]]'' (2013) - Ursula (voice)\n* ''[[Kingdom Hearts 2.5 HD Remix]]'' (2014) - Ursula (voice)\n\n{{col-end}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* Young, Jordan R. (1989). ''Acting Solo: The Art of One-Person Shows''. Beverly Hills: Past Times Publishing Co.  \nLucas, Eddie (2011) Livingroom Legends: Chats with TV's Famous Faces : Interview With Pat Carroll.  http://louisxivgames.com/pat-carroll-actress.pdf\n\n==External links==\n{{wikiquote|Pat Carroll}}\n{{Commons category|Pat Carroll}}\n* {{IMDb name|0140946|Pat Carroll}}\n* {{IBDB name}}\n* {{Tcmdb name}}\n* {{amg name|11329|Pat Carroll}}\n* {{YouTube|a4BhZxRUXaY|Pat Carroll performs a live script reading of The Little Mermaid}}\n\n{{Navboxes\n| title = Awards for Pat Carroll\n| list =\n{{DramaDesk PlayOutstandingActress 1975-2000}}\n{{EmmyAward ComedySupportingActress 1950-1975}}\n{{Grammy Award for Best Spoken Word Album 1980s}}\n}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Carroll, Pat}}\n[[Category:1927 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Actresses from Louisiana]]\n[[Category:American film actresses]]\n[[Category:American television actresses]]\n[[Category:American voice actresses]]\n[[Category:American video game actresses]]\n[[Category:Drama Desk Award winners]]\n[[Category:Outstanding Performance by a Supporting Actress in a Comedy Series Primetime Emmy Award winners]]\n[[Category:Grammy Award winners]]\n[[Category:Actresses from Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Actors from Shreveport, Louisiana]]\n[[Category:Catholic University of America alumni]]\n[[Category:Immaculate Heart College alumni]]\n[[Category:American Roman Catholics]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Immaculate Heart High School, Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:20th-century American actresses]]\n[[Category:21st-century American actresses]]\n[[Category:California Republicans]]\n[[Category:Louisiana Republicans]]\n[[Category:Catholics from Louisiana]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American actress}}\n{{other people}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name = Pat Carroll\n| image = Pat Carroll 1972.JPG\n| caption = Carroll in 1972\n| birth_name = Patricia Ann Carroll\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1927|5|5}}\n| birth_place = [[Shreveport, Louisiana]], U.S.\n| other_names = Pat Ann Carroll<br />Patricia Carroll\n| occupation = Actress, voice actress, singer\n| years_active = 1947\u2013present\n| notable_works = Voice of [[Ursula (The Little Mermaid)|Ursula the Sea Witch]] in Disney's ''[[The Little Mermaid (1989 film)|The Little Mermaid]]'' (1989)\n| spouse = {{marriage|Lee Karsian|1955|1976|end=divorced}}\n| domestic_partner = \n| children = 3, including [[Tara Karsian]]\n| television = ''[[Make Room for Daddy]]'', ''[[Laverne & Shirley]]'', ''[[ER (TV series)|ER]]'' \n}}\n'''Patricia Ann Carroll''' (born May 5, 1927) is an American actress, voice actress, and singer. She is known for voicing [[Ursula (Disney)|Ursula]] in ''[[The Little Mermaid (1989 film)|The Little Mermaid]]'' as well as having a long acting career, including appearances in [[CBS]]'s ''[[The Danny Thomas Show]]'', [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]]'s ''[[Laverne & Shirley]]'', [[NBC]]'s ''[[ER (TV series)|ER]]'', other guest-starring and series-regular roles on American television as well as voice-acting in several cartoon series. Carroll is an [[Emmy Award|Emmy]], [[Drama Desk Award|Drama Desk]] and [[Grammy Award|Grammy]] Award winner and a [[Tony Award]] nominee.\n\n==Early life==\nCarroll was born in [[Shreveport, Louisiana]], on May 5, 1927, to Maurice Clifton Carroll and Kathryn Angela (n\u00e9e Meagher)<ref name = \"Film Reference\">{{cite web|title=Pat Carroll Biography (1927-)|url=http://www.filmreference.com/film/33/Pat-Carroll.html|publisher=FilmReference.Com/City-Data.Com|accessdate=May 26, 2013}}</ref>  Her family moved to [[Los Angeles]] when Pat was five years old and she soon began acting in local productions. She graduated from [[Immaculate Heart High School (Los Angeles)|Immaculate Heart High School]] and attended [[Catholic University of America]] after enlisting in the [[United States Army]] as a civilian actress technician.<ref name=\"BU\">{{cite web|title=Pat Carroll|url=http://www.bu.edu/phpbin/archives-cc/app/details.php?id=7536|publisher=Howard Gotlieb Archival Research Center Boston University|accessdate=May 26, 2013}}{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nIn 1956, Carroll won an [[Emmy Award]] for her work on ''[[Caesar's Hour]]'' and was a regular on the sitcom ''[[Make Room for Daddy]]'' from 1961 to 1964. She guest starred in the drama [[anthology series]] ''[[The DuPont Show with June Allyson]]''. Carroll also appeared on many [[variety show]]s of the 1950s, 1960s and 1970s, such as ''[[The Red Buttons Show]]'', ''[[The Danny Kaye Show]]'', ''[[The Red Skelton Show]]'', and ''[[The Carol Burnett Show]]''. In 1965 she co-starred as \"Prunella\", one of the wicked stepsisters in the 1965 production of [[Rodgers and Hammerstein]]'s musical version of ''[[Cinderella (Rodgers and Hammerstein musical)|Cinderella]]''.\n\nIn the late 1970s Carroll's successful one woman show on [[Gertrude Stein]], ''Gertrude Stein, Gertrude Stein, Gertrude Stein'' (by playwright Marty Martin), won several major theater awards;<ref>{{cite news|last=Casselberry Manuel|first=Diane|title=Pat Carroll; Gertrude Stein was never a bore|url=http://www.csmonitor.com/1981/0108/010861.html|accessdate=May 26, 2013|newspaper=[[The Christian Science Monitor]]|date=January 8, 1981}}</ref> her recorded version won a 1980 [[Grammy Award]] for Best Spoken Word, Documentary or Drama.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.grammy.com/nominees/search?artist=pat+carroll&field_nominee_work_value=Gertrude+Stein%2C+Gertrude+Stein%2C+Gertrude+Stein&year=1980&genre=All|title=1980 Best Spoken Word, Documentary Or Drama|publisher=Grammy.Org/The Recording Academy|accessdate=May 26, 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn early 1976, Carroll was cast as Lily, the mother of Shirley Feeney (played by [[Cindy Williams]]) in the episode \"Mother Knows Worst\" on the hit ''[[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]]'' [[situation comedy]], ''[[Laverne & Shirley]]''.<ref name = \"JimHill\">{{cite web|last=Hill|first=Jim|title=Why (For) Pat Carroll wasn't actually Disney's first choice to voice Ursula in \"The Little Mermaid\"|url=http://jimhillmedia.com/editor_in_chief1/b/jim_hill/archive/2007/06/15/why-for-pat-carroll-wasn-t-actually-disney-s-first-choice-to-voice-ursula-in-the-little-mermaid.aspx#.UaJqmhzIBgI|publisher=JimHillMedia|accessdate=May 26, 2013}}</ref> She portrayed Pearl Markowitz, the mother of [[Adam Arkin]]{{'}}s character Lenny Markowitz, in the 1977 [[CBS]] situation comedy ''[[Busting Loose (TV series)|Busting Loose]]''. Her frequent television roles in the 1980s included newspaper owner Hope Stinson on the syndicated ''The Ted Knight Show'' (the former ''[[Too Close for Comfort]]'') during its final season in 1986; and that of Gussie Holt, the mother of [[Suzanne Somers]]' lead character in the syndicated sitcom ''[[She's the Sheriff]]'' (1987\u20131989).\n\nSince the late 1980s, Carroll has had a great deal of voice-over work on animated programs<ref name = \"JimHill\"/> such as ''[[A Pup Named Scooby-Doo]]'', ''[[Galaxy High]]'', ''[[Foofur]]'' and ''[[A Goofy Movie]]''. On TV's ''[[Pound Puppies (1986 TV series)|Pound Puppies]]'', she voiced [[Katrina Stoneheart]]. On two ''[[Garfield]]'' television specials (''[[A Garfield Christmas]]'' and ''[[Garfield's Thanksgiving]]''), she portrayed [[Jon Arbuckle|Jon]]'s feisty Grandmother.  She also voiced the  character of Granny in the 2005 re-release of [[Hayao Miyazaki]]'s ''[[My Neighbor Totoro]]''.<ref name = \"Film Reference\"/>\n\nIn 1989, Carroll portrayed the sea witch Ursula in Disney's ''[[The Little Mermaid (1989 film)|The Little Mermaid]]'' and sang \"[[Poor Unfortunate Souls]]\".<ref name = \"JimHill\"/> In interviews, Carroll has referred to the role as one of the favorites of her career.<ref>{{YouTube|sUwOeOiMC3I}}</ref> She has since reprised the role in other forms of media, including the ''[[Kingdom Hearts]]'' series of video games,<ref name = \"Film Reference\"/> the spinoff television series, and in various [[Disney theme parks]] attractions and shows.\n\nCarroll also appeared on a variety of game shows including ''[[Celebrity Sweepstakes]],'' ''[[You Don't Say]]'', ''[[To Tell the Truth]]'', ''[[Match Game 73]]'', ''[[Password]]'' and ''[[I've Got a Secret]]''.<ref name = \"Film Reference\"/>\n\nA member of [[the Actors Studio]], she has also had a successful career in the theater, appearing in numerous plays including productions of ''[[Our Town]]'' and Sophocles' ''[[Electra (Sophocles)|Electra]]''.<ref>{{cite news|authorlink1=Robert Simonson| last=Simonson| first=Robert| title=Stephen Spinella Joins Claire Bloom & Pat Carroll in NJ Electra Sept. 15| url=http://www.playbill.com/news/article/40761-Stephen-Spinella-Joins-Claire-Bloom-Pat-Carroll-in-NJ-Electra-Sept-15| archive-url=https://archive.is/20130630204824/http://www.playbill.com/news/article/40761-Stephen-Spinella-Joins-Claire-Bloom-Pat-Carroll-in-NJ-Electra-Sept-15|url-status=dead| archive-date=June 30, 2013| journal=[[Playbill]]| accessdate=May 26, 2013| author2=David Lefkowitz| date=September 4, 1998}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| title=A Conversation With Pat Carroll at the High Falls Film Festival, May 14, 2009| url=http://thefilmpanelnotetaker.com/a-conversation-with-pat-carroll-at-the-high-falls-film-festival-may-14-2009| publisher=The Film Panel Notetaker| accessdate=May 26, 2013| date=May 21, 2009| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140513104242/http://thefilmpanelnotetaker.com/a-conversation-with-pat-carroll-at-the-high-falls-film-festival-may-14-2009|archivedate=May 13, 2014}}</ref>  In 1990, she starred in ''[[The Merry Wives of Windsor]]'' at the [[Shakespeare Theatre Company|Shakespeare Theatre at the Folger]] in the role of [[Sir John Falstaff]], a balding knight with whiskers.<ref name = \"Rich\">{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/1990/05/30/theater/review-theater-pat-carroll-as-falstaff-in-merry-wives-at-folger.html| title=Review/Theater; Pat Carroll as Falstaff in 'Merry Wives' at Folger| last=Rich| first=Frank |date=May 30, 1990| work=The New York Times| accessdate=20 January 2011}}</ref>\n\nWhen drama critic [[Frank Rich]] of ''[[The New York Times]]'' reviewed her performance he wrote, \"Her performance is a triumph from start to finish, and, I think, a particularly brave and moving one, with implications that go beyond this one production. Ms. Carroll and Mr. Kahn help revivify the argument that the right actresses can perform some of the great classic roles traditionally denied to women and make them their own. It's not a new argument, to be sure; female Hamlets stretch back into history. But what separates Ms. Carroll's Falstaff from some other similar casting experiments of late is that her performance exists to investigate a character rather than merely as ideological window dressing for a gimmicky production.\"<ref name = \"Rich\"/>\n\n==Personal life==\nCarroll married Lee Karsian in 1955 and they had three children<ref name = \"BU\"/> - two daughters, Kerry and [[Tara Karsian]] and a son, Sean.<ref name = \"Film Reference\"/>  In 1991 Carroll received an honorary doctorate from [[Siena College]] in [[Albany, New York]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Honorary Degrees - Past Recipients|url=http://www.siena.edu/pages/5696.asp|publisher=Siena College|accessdate=May 26, 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120604033444/http://www.siena.edu/pages/5696.asp|archivedate=June 4, 2012}}</ref> Carroll is a practicing [[Roman Catholic]] citing that her religious views help her to determine what projects to accept.<ref>{{cite web| title=Pat Carroll| url=http://www.behindthevoiceactors.com/Pat-Carroll/| publisher=Behind the Voice Actors| accessdate=July 13, 2018}}</ref> She is a [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]].\n\n==Filmography==\n\n===Film===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\" | Year\n!style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\" | Title\n!style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\" | Role\n!style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\" | Notes\n\n|-\n| 1967\n|''[[The Ballad of Josie]]'' \n| Elizabeth\n|\n|-\n| 1968\n|''[[With Six You Get Eggroll]]'' \n| Maxine Scott\n|\n|-\n| 1984\n| ''[[Racing with the Moon]]'' \n| Mrs. Spangler \n| \n|-\n| 1985\n| ''[[The Trip to Bountiful]]'' \n| Rosella \n| \n|-\n| 1988\n| ''[[My Neighbor Totoro]]'' \n| Granny \n|Voice, 2005 Disney redub \n|-\n| 1989 \n| ''[[The Little Mermaid (1989 film)|The Little Mermaid]]'' \n| [[Ursula (Disney)|Ursula]] \n|Voice\n|-\n| rowspan=2|2000\n| ''[[Songcatcher]]'' \n| Viney Butler\n|\n|-\n| ''[[The Little Mermaid II: Return to the Sea]]''\n| Morgana\n|Voice\n|-\n| 2001 \n| ''[[Mickey's Magical Christmas: Snowed in at the House of Mouse]]'' \n| [[Ursula 