 Richard. ''Breaking the Ice: The Racial Integration of Southwest Conference Football'' (McFarland, 1987).\n* Romero, Francine Sanders. \"'There are only white champions': The rise and demise of segregated boxing in Texas.\" ''Southwestern Historical Quarterly'' 108.1 (2004): 26-41. [https://www.jstor.org/stable/30239493 online]\n* Sacks, Marcy S. ''Joe Louis: Sports and Race in Twentieth-Century America'' (Routledge, 2018).\n* Spivey, Donald. \"The black athlete in big-time intercollegiate sports, 1941-1968.\" ''Phylon''  44.2 (1983): 116-125. [http://www.pages.drexel.edu/~rosenl/sports%20Folder/The%20Black%20Athlete%20in%20Big-Time%20Intercollegiate%20Sports%2041-68.pdf online]\n* White, Derrick E. \"From desegregation to integration: Race, football, and\" Dixie\" at the University of Florida.\" ''Florida Historical Quarterly'' 88.4 (2010): 469-496. [http://www.academia.edu/download/38229162/Florida_Historical_Quarterly_2010_White-1.pdf online]\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikiquote}}\n{{Commons category}}\n* [https://archive.is/20021004051643/http://www.jimcrowhistory.org/history/history.htm The History of Jim Crow], Ronald L. F. Davis \u2013 A series of essays on the history of Jim Crow. {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/*/http://www.jimcrowhistory.org/history/history.htm |date=* }}\n** [https://web.archive.org/web/20070601223741/http://www.jimcrowhistory.org/history/creating2.htm Creating Jim Crow] \u2013 Origins of the term and system of laws. \n** [https://web.archive.org/web/20040203140654/http://www.jimcrowhistory.org/resources/lessonplans/hs_es_etiquette.htm Racial Etiquette: The Racial Customs and Rules of Racial Behavior in Jim Crow America] \u2013 The basics of Jim Crow etiquette. \n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20050407215126/http://www.robinwashington.com/jimcrow/1_home.html \"You Don't Have to Ride Jim Crow!\"] PBS documentary on first Freedom Ride, in 1947. \n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20060212050132/http://afroamhistory.about.com/cs/jimcrowlaws/a/jimcrowlaws.htm List of laws enacted in various states]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20040618111006/http://www.ferris.edu/news/jimcrow/what.htm Ferris University page] about Jim Crow\n* [http://www.ushmm.org/museum/exhibit/focus/antisemitism/voices/transcript/?content=20090423''Voices on Antisemitism'' Interview with David Pilgrim, founder of Jim Crow Museum] from the US Holocaust Memorial Museum\n* [https://www.pbs.org/jazz/time/time_jim_crow.htm Jim Crow Era, History in the Key of Jazz], [[Gerald Early]], Washington University, St. Louis, Missouri (esp. see section \"Jim Crow is Born\")\n*{{cite web |url=http://www.nps.gov/malu/forteachers/jim_crow_laws.htm |title=Jim Crow Laws |publisher=[[National Park Service]] |accessdate=November 17, 2010 }} Examples of Jim Crow laws\n*[http://stars.library.ucf.edu/ahistoryofcentralfloridapodcast/43/ Jim Crow Signs] at [http://stars.library.ucf.edu/ahistoryofcentralfloridapodcast/ A History of Central Florida Podcast]\n\n{{Jim Crow Era|state=collapsed}}\n{{African American topics|state=collapsed}}\n{{Native American topics|collapsed}}\n{{Racism topics|state=collapsed}}\n{{Segregation by type|state=collapsed}}\n{{US history|state=collapsed}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Jim Crow}}\n[[Category:African-American history]]\n[[Category:Anti-black racism in the United States]]\n[[Category:Debt bondage]]\n[[Category:Discrimination in the United States]]\n[[Category:History of African-American civil rights]]\n[[Category:History of racial segregation in the United States]]\n[[Category:Jim Crow]]\n[[Category:Legal history of the United States]]\n[[Category:Native American history]]\n[[Category:Politics and race in the United States]]\n[[Category:Race legislation in the United States]]\n[[Category:Political terminology of the United States]]\n[[Category:Reconstruction Era]]\n[[Category:United States repealed legislation]]\n[[Category:White supremacy in the United States]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: Furthermore \u2192 Furthermore,, 1954-1965 \u2192 1954\u20131965, high profile \u2192 high-profile, 453-477 \u2192 453\u2013477 (5)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jim_Crow_laws"}
{"title_page": "Ankit Fadia", "text_new": "{{short description|Indian author and speaker}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=October 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2013}}\n\n{{Infobox writer <!-- For more information see [[:Template:Infobox Writer/doc]]. -->\n| image = File:Ankitfadia3.jpg\n| image_size = \n| birth_date = {{Birth year and age|1985}}<ref \nname=\"birthyear\" />\n| birth_place = [[Ahemdabad]], India\n| occupation = [[Public Speaking|Speaker]], [[Ethical hacker]]\n| nationality = [[India]]n\n| education = \n| alma_mater = D Public School\n| genre = Technology, entertainer\n| notableworks = ''[[FASTER: 100 Ways To Improve Your Digital life]]''<br />''SOCIAL: 50 Ways To Improve Your Professional Life''\n| website = {{URL|www.ankitfadia.in}}\n| residence = [[Mumbai]], India\n| name = Ankit Fadia\n}}\n'''Ankit Fadia''' (born 24 May 1985)<ref name=\"birthyear\">{{cite web |title=FADIA, Ankit 1985- |url= http://www.worldcat.org/identities/lccn-no2001-81317 |publisher= [[WorldCat]] |accessdate= 2012-09-21}}</ref> is an Indian author, speaker, television host, and self-proclaimed ethical hacker  of computer systems, whose skills and ethics have been debated. His work mostly involves OS and networking based tips and tricks, proxy websites and making people think that he is a hacker'''.<ref name=\"Times of India\">{{cite web |url= http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/kolkata/How-to-live-appily-ever-after/articleshow/40713468.cms |title='How to live... 'appily' ever after' |publisher= Times of India |date= |accessdate= 2014-09-18}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url = http://www.thehindu.com/sci-tech/article48684.ece |title= Inside account |author= Priyadarshini Pandey |accessdate= 2013-02-26 |date= 14 November 2009 | newspaper = The Hindu | location=Chennai, India}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url = http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/delhi-times/Ankit-Fadia-Everything-official-about-him/articleshow/414502089.cms |access-date = 6 December 2006| title = Ankit Fadia: Everything official about him| publisher= [[The Times of India]] |date= 3 September 2001}}</ref>'''\n\nIn 2008 he started a television show on [[MTV India]] called \"''[[MTV What the Hack!|What The Hack]]''\", which he co-hosted with Jos\u00e9 Covaco. In this show Fadia gave tips on how to make good use of the Internet and answered people's technology-related questions.<ref name=\"Dnaindia.com\">{{cite web |url= http://www.dnaindia.com/money/report_from-this-diwali-mtv-will-be-more-than-just-music_1298240 |title= From this Diwali, MTV will be more than just music - Money - DNA |publisher= Dnaindia.com |date=12 October 2009 |accessdate= 2012-01-08}}</ref> In 2013, Ankit Fadia started a [[YouTube]] show ''Geek On the Loose'', in collaboration with PING networks, where he shared technology-related tips and tricks. The show has got more than 750,000+ views on YouTube.<ref name=\"Geek On the Loose\">{{cite web |url= https://www.youtube.com/user/geekontheloose/about |publisher= YouTube |title= Geek On the Loose}}</ref>\n\nHe has been accused of [[plagiarism]] in his work.<ref>{{Cite web |title= Errata: Ankit Fadia - \"Unofficial Guide to Ethical Hacking\" 32% Plagiarized |url= http://attrition.org/errata/charlatan/ankit_fadia/unofficial.html |website = attrition.org |accessdate= 2015-09-19}}</ref> His claims of hacking feats have since been trashed by many [[Computer magazine|magazines]].<ref>{{Cite web |title= Ethical hacker Ankit Fadia is a fake |url= http://www.sunday-guardian.com/investigation/ethical-hacker-ankit-fadia-is-a-fake| publisher=Sunday Guardian |accessdate= 2015-09-19}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |author=Shunol Doke |title= Ankit Fadia's website hacked again \u2013 Tech2 |url= http://tech.firstpost.com/news-analysis/ankit-fadias-website-hacked-again-41559.html |date=18 Sep 2012 |accessdate= 2016-03-29}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title= Forbes India Magazine - Ankit Fadia Revealed |url= http://forbesindia.com/article/beyond-business/ankit-fadia-revealed/34793/0 |website= forbesindia.com |accessdate= 2015-09-19}}</ref> \n\nAt the age of 10, his parents gifted him a computer and he says he started taking an interest in hacking after a year of playing video games when he read a newspaper article on the subject.<ref name=\"rediff_kashmiri_2002\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rediff.com/search/2002/apr/18ankit.htm |title=Rediff Guide to the Net: Features: 16-year-old hacker Ankit Fadia outsmarts Kashmiri separatists |publisher=Rediff.com|date=18 April 2002 |accessdate=2013-02-26}}</ref><ref name=\"Success Decoded\">{{cite web|url=http://www.telegraphindia.com/1140112/jsp/graphiti/17757828.jsp |title=Success Decoded |publisher=The Telegraph |date= |accessdate=2014-09-21}}</ref> He soon started a website [https://web.archive.org/web/20020802033500/http://hackingtruths.box.sk/ hackingtruths.box.sk] where he wrote hacking [[Tutorial|tutorials]], which acquired many readers and encouraged him to write a book.<ref name=\"rediff_kashmiri_2002\"/>.<ref name=\"BBC_2002\">{{cite news | date = 17 April 2002 | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/1934874.stm | title = Indian hacker turns cyber cop | publisher = BBC News | accessdate = 2013-02-26}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url = http://www.thehindubusinessline.com/2003/04/19/stories/2003041901390700.htm | date = 19 April 2003 | title = E2 labs to combat cyber crime in Hyderabad | publisher = The Hindu Business Line | accessdate = 2006-12-19 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url = http://www.tribuneindia.com/2003/20030413/cth1.htm | date = 13 April 2003 | author=Manoj Kumar | title = Teen hacker who is sought after by FBI | publisher = The Tribune, Chandigarh | accessdate = 2006-08-19 }}</ref> <ref name=\"Success Decoded\" />\n== Career ==\nHe wrote more books on computer security, ''and'' spoke at several seminars across schools and colleges in India.<ref>{{cite news | url = http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-features/tp-metroplus/article497533.ece | title = Caught in the web | author = K. Jeshi | newspaper = The Hindu | date = 3 July 2010 | accessdate = 2013-03-01 | location=Chennai, India}}</ref> In addition, he started providing his own computer security courses, including the \"Ankit Fadia Certified Ethical Hacker\" programme in alliance with [shashank].<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.telegraphindia.com/1070204/asp/calcutta/story_7327984.asp |title=The inheritance of food | newspaper = The Telegraph |date= 4 February 2007 |accessdate=2013-03-01 |location=Calcutta, India}}</ref>\n\nIn 2009, Fadia stated that he was working in New York as an Internet security expert for \"prestigious companies\".<ref name=\"TH_hack_2009\">{{cite news | url = http://www.hindu.com/mp/2009/11/16/stories/2009111650950300.htm | title = How the hack he does it! | date = 16 November 2009 | accessdate = 2013-03-01 | newspaper = The Hindu | location=Chennai, India}}</ref> Fadia also [[celebrity branding|endorsed]] the Flying Machine jeans brand of [[Arvind Mills]].<ref>{{cite news | url = http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2010-10-21/news/27587443_1_youth-icon-brand-ambassador-mtv-india | title = Flying Machine endorsement: Ethical Hacker Fadia replaces Abhishek Bacchan | date = 21 October 2012 | accessdate = 2013-03-01 | newspaper = [[The Economic Times]] | author = Ratna Bhushan }}</ref>.<ref name=\"sunday_guardian_2012\">{{cite news | url = http://www.sunday-guardian.com/investigation/ethical-hacker-ankit-fadia-is-a-fake | title = Ethical hacker Ankit Fadia is a fake | date = 19 February 2012 | accessdate = 2013-02-26 | newspaper = The Sunday Guardian | author = Shubhankar Adhikari }}</ref><ref name=\"SMH_2003\">{{cite news  | title=Hacktivism through the eyes of an infiltrator  | url=http://www.smh.com.au/articles/2003/08/04/1059849331034.html  | author=Suelette Dreyfus  | date = 5 August 2003  | accessdate = 2013-02-26 | work=The Sydney Morning Herald}}</ref>\n==Television and web shows==\n\n* MTV What The Hack\n\nIn October 2009 [[MTV India]] announced the launch of Fadia's new TV show on MTV called ''[[MTV What the Hack!]]', where Fadia gave tips on how to make use of the Internet, and answered people's questions.<ref name=\"Dnaindia.com\"/> Internet users could email their problems to MTV India and Fadia gave them a solution on the show.<ref name=\"MTV India\">{{cite web|url=|title=VJs, Music, Videos, Blogs, Games, Wallpapers, Interviews, Performances, Shows, Fun and more|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=MTV India|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091121015512/http://www.mtvindia.com/news/news.php?id=3419|archivedate=21 November 2009|df=dmy}}</ref>\n\n* Unzipped By Dell\n\nIn 2012, [[Dell]] India partnered with Ankit Fadia to create a series of nearly 50 videos, each of 1 minute duration to show tips and tricks for the use of computers and mobile phones. These videos were shown on the Dell India Facebook page with an average of one video per week. People also had the opportunity to ask tech queries of Fadia on topics like photography, video making, music composing, navigation assistance, gaming, messaging and others.<ref name=\"India Infoline News Service\">{{cite web|url=http://www.indiainfoline.com/article/news/dell-india-in-association-with-ankit-fadia-presents-unzipped-by-dell-and-ankit-fadia-5555289971_1.html |title=Dell India in association with Ankit Fadia presents &quot;Unzipped: By Dell and Ankit Fadia |publisher=India Infoline News Service |date= |accessdate=2012-09-21}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://efytimes.com/e1/95718/Dell-India-In-Association-With-Ankit-Fadia-Presents-Unzipped-By-Dell-And-Ankit-Fadia |title=Dell India in association with Ankit Fadia presents &quot;Unzipped: By Dell and Ankit Fadia |publisher=EFYTimes.com |accessdate=2012-09-21 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150205230534/http://efytimes.com/e1/95718/Dell-India-In-Association-With-Ankit-Fadia-Presents-Unzipped-By-Dell-And-Ankit-Fadia |archive-date=5 February 2015 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/UnzippedbyDell |title=Unzipped by Dell Facebook Page |publisher=Facebook|date= |accessdate=2012-09-21}}</ref>\n\n* Geek On The Loose\n\nIn 2013, Ankit Fadia started a YouTube show Geek On the Loose in collaboration with PING networks where he shared technology-related tips, tricks and apps.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newindianexpress.com/cities/chennai/Short-cuts-for-the-tech-savvy/2013/07/18/article1688412.ece |title=Short-cuts for the tech savvy |publisher=The New Indian Express |date= |accessdate=2012-09-21}}</ref>  The show was based on situations mentioned in his book FASTER: 100 Ways To Improve Your Digital Life.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/lifestyle/books/ankit-fadia-aims-at-stretching-technology-limits/article1-1108564.aspx |title=Ankit Fadia aims at stretching technology limits |publisher=The Hindustan Times |date= |accessdate=2012-09-21}}</ref> The show has got more than 750,000+ views on YouTube.<ref name=\"Geek On the Loose\"/>\n\n== Awards and Recognitions ==\n* IT Youth Award from the Singapore Computer Society (2005) <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.scs.org.sg/news_centre/Press%20Release%202012/Press%20Release_IT%20Leader%20Awards%202012.pdf |title=Media Release IT Leader Awards 2012 |publisher=Singapore Computer Society |accessdate=2014-09-23}}</ref>\n* Global Ambassador for Cyber Security (National Telecom Awards 2011, Government of India)<ref>[http://www.cmaievents.com/awardees2011.php The CMAI 5th National Awards]. Cmaievents.com (2011-06-08). Retrieved on 2013-08-02.</ref>\n* Global Shaper, World Economic Forum <ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.globalshapers.org/shapers/ankit-fadia |title=Ankit Fadia{{!}}World Economic Forum: Global Shapers |publisher=World Economic Forum |accessdate=2014-09-23 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150205121332/http://www.globalshapers.org/shapers/ankit-fadia |archive-date=5 February 2015 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n*  [[DEF CON|DEF CON 20]] Security [[Charlatan]] of the year.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://scroll.in/article/758921/ankit-fadias-biggest-hack-getting-modi-government-to-make-him-a-brand-ambassador|title=Ankit Fadia's biggest hack: Getting Modi government to make him a brand ambassador|last=Daniyal|first=Shoaib|website=Scroll.in|language=en-US|access-date=2019-02-26}}</ref><ref name=\"youtube.com\">{{cite av media|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=GIzvTwFwaYI&t=33m3s|title=DEFCON 20: DC RECOGNIZE Awards|date=16 November 2012|accessdate=28 September 2015|work=YouTube}}</ref><ref>[http://pib.nic.in/newsite/PrintRelease.aspx?relid=128306 Clarification on Appointment of Brand Ambassadors]. Ministry of Communications & Information Technology, 29 September 2015.</ref> (This is not a positive endorsement)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Fadia, Ankit}}\n[[Category:1985 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Indian technology writers]]\n[[Category:Delhi Public School alumni]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Indian author and speaker}}\n{{Multiple issues|\n{{Cleanup rewrite|date=February 2020}}\n{{Lead too long|date=February 2020}}\n{{Confusing|date=February 2020}}\n}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=October 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2013}}\n\n{{Infobox writer <!-- For more information see [[:Template:Infobox Writer/doc]]. -->\n| image = \n| image_size = \n| caption = Ankit Fadia at the launch of himself\n| birth_date = {{Birth year and age|1985}}<ref \nname=\"birthyear\" />\n| birth_place = [[Ahemdabad]], India\n| occupation = Author & speaker\n| nationality = [[India]]n\n| education = \n| alma_mater = D Public School\n| genre = Technology, entertainer\n| notableworks = ''[[FASTER: 100 Ways To Improve Your Digital life]]''<br />''SOCIAL: 50 Ways To Improve Your Professional Life''\n| website = {{URL|www.ankitfadia.in}}\n| residence = [[Mumbai]], India\n| name = Ankit Fadia\n}}\n'''Ankit Fadia''' (born 24 May 1985)<ref name=\"birthyear\">{{cite web |title=FADIA, Ankit 1985- |url= http://www.worldcat.org/identities/lccn-no2001-81317 |publisher= [[WorldCat]] |accessdate= 2012-09-21}}</ref> is an Indian author, speaker, television host, and self-proclaimed \"BLACK HAT hacker\" of computer systems, whose skills and ethics have been debated. His work mostly involves OS and networking based tips and tricks, proxy websites and making people think that he is a hacker'''.<ref name=\"Times of India\">{{cite web |url= http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/kolkata/How-to-live-appily-ever-after/articleshow/40713468.cms |title='How to live... 'appily' ever after' |publisher= Times of India |date= |accessdate= 2014-09-18}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url = http://www.thehindu.com/sci-tech/article48684.ece |title= Inside account |author= Priyadarshini Pandey |accessdate= 2013-02-26 |date= 14 November 2009 | newspaper = The Hindu | location=Chennai, India}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url = http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/delhi-times/Ankit-Fadia-Everything-official-about-him/articleshow/414502089.cms |access-date = 6 December 2006| title = Ankit Fadia: Everything official about him| publisher= [[The Times of India]] |date= 3 September 2001}}</ref>'''\n\nIn 2008 he started a television show on [[MTV India]] called \"''[[MTV What the Hack!|What The Hack]]''\", which he co-hosted with Jos\u00e9 Covaco. In this show Fadia gave tips on how to make good use of the Internet and answered people's technology-related questions.<ref name=\"Dnaindia.com\">{{cite web |url= http://www.dnaindia.com/money/report_from-this-diwali-mtv-will-be-more-than-just-music_1298240 |title= From this Diwali, MTV will be more than just music - Money - DNA |publisher= Dnaindia.com |date=12 October 2009 |accessdate= 2012-01-08}}</ref> In 2013, Ankit Fadia started a [[YouTube]] show ''Geek On the Loose'', in collaboration with PING networks, where he shared technology-related tips and tricks. The show has got more than 750,000+ views on YouTube.<ref name=\"Geek On the Loose\">{{cite web |url= https://www.youtube.com/user/geekontheloose/about |publisher= YouTube |title= Geek On the Loose}}</ref> \n\nA number of his claims regarding his achievements have been disputed by others within the security industry, and he was mocked with a \"Security [[Charlatan]] of the Year\" award at [[DEF CON]] 20 in 2012.<ref name=\"youtube.com\" /> [[Attrition (website)|Attrition.org]] also reviewed his alleged credentials and included him on their [http://attrition.org/errata/charlatan/ Security Charlatans list],<ref name=\":0\" /> calling into question the veracity of his marketing statements. He has been accused of [[plagiarism]] in his work.<ref>{{Cite web |title= Errata: Ankit Fadia - \"Unofficial Guide to Ethical Hacking\" 32% Plagiarized |url= http://attrition.org/errata/charlatan/ankit_fadia/unofficial.html |website = attrition.org |accessdate= 2015-09-19}}</ref> His claims of hacking feats have since been trashed by many [[Computer magazine|magazines]].<ref>{{Cite web |title= Ethical hacker Ankit Fadia is a fake |url= http://www.sunday-guardian.com/investigation/ethical-hacker-ankit-fadia-is-a-fake| publisher=Sunday Guardian |accessdate= 2015-09-19}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |author=Shunol Doke |title= Ankit Fadia's website hacked again \u2013 Tech2 |url= http://tech.firstpost.com/news-analysis/ankit-fadias-website-hacked-again-41559.html |date=18 Sep 2012 |accessdate= 2016-03-29}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title= Forbes India Magazine - Ankit Fadia Revealed |url= http://forbesindia.com/article/beyond-business/ankit-fadia-revealed/34793/0 |website= forbesindia.com |accessdate= 2015-09-19}}</ref>\n\nAt the age of 10, his parents gifted him a computer and he says he started taking an interest in hacking after a year of playing video games when he read a newspaper article on the subject.<ref name=\"rediff_kashmiri_2002\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rediff.com/search/2002/apr/18ankit.htm |title=Rediff Guide to the Net: Features: 16-year-old hacker Ankit Fadia outsmarts Kashmiri separatists |publisher=Rediff.com|date=18 April 2002 |accessdate=2013-02-26}}</ref><ref name=\"Success Decoded\">{{cite web|url=http://www.telegraphindia.com/1140112/jsp/graphiti/17757828.jsp |title=Success Decoded |publisher=The Telegraph |date= |accessdate=2014-09-21}}</ref> He soon started a website [https://web.archive.org/web/20020802033500/http://hackingtruths.box.sk/ hackingtruths.box.sk] where he wrote hacking [[Tutorial|tutorials]], which acquired many readers and encouraged him to write a book.<ref name=\"rediff_kashmiri_2002\"/>.<ref name=\"BBC_2002\">{{cite news | date = 17 April 2002 | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/1934874.stm | title = Indian hacker turns cyber cop | publisher = BBC News | accessdate = 2013-02-26}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url = http://www.thehindubusinessline.com/2003/04/19/stories/2003041901390700.htm | date = 19 April 2003 | title = E2 labs to combat cyber crime in Hyderabad | publisher = The Hindu Business Line | accessdate = 2006-12-19 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url = http://www.tribuneindia.com/2003/20030413/cth1.htm | date = 13 April 2003 | author=Manoj Kumar | title = Teen hacker who is sought after by FBI | publisher = The Tribune, Chandigarh | accessdate = 2006-08-19 }}</ref> The book received favorable responses in India, made Fadia popular in the country, and turned his hobby into a full-time profession.<ref name=\"Success Decoded\" /> However, he was also accused of [[plagiarism]].<ref name=\"sunday_guardian_2012\"/>\n\n== Career ==\nHe wrote more books on computer security, ''and'' spoke at several seminars across schools and colleges in India.<ref>{{cite news | url = http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-features/tp-metroplus/article497533.ece | title = Caught in the web | author = K. Jeshi | newspaper = The Hindu | date = 3 July 2010 | accessdate = 2013-03-01 | location=Chennai, India}}</ref> In addition, he started providing his own computer security courses, including the \"Ankit Fadia Certified Ethical Hacker\" programme in alliance with [shashank].<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.telegraphindia.com/1070204/asp/calcutta/story_7327984.asp |title=The inheritance of food | newspaper = The Telegraph |date= 4 February 2007 |accessdate=2013-03-01 |location=Calcutta, India}}</ref>\n\nIn 2009, Fadia stated that he was working in New York as an Internet security expert for \"prestigious companies\".<ref name=\"TH_hack_2009\">{{cite news | url = http://www.hindu.com/mp/2009/11/16/stories/2009111650950300.htm | title = How the hack he does it! | date = 16 November 2009 | accessdate = 2013-03-01 | newspaper = The Hindu | location=Chennai, India}}</ref> Fadia also [[celebrity branding|endorsed]] the Flying Machine jeans brand of [[Arvind Mills]].<ref>{{cite news | url = http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2010-10-21/news/27587443_1_youth-icon-brand-ambassador-mtv-india | title = Flying Machine endorsement: Ethical Hacker Fadia replaces Abhishek Bacchan | date = 21 October 2012 | accessdate = 2013-03-01 | newspaper = [[The Economic Times]] | author = Ratna Bhushan }}</ref>\n\nFadia was dismissed by security and cryptography enthusiasts as a 'faker' making tall claims, who attributed his success to the [ tech-illiterate] media.<ref name=\"sunday_guardian_2012\">{{cite news | url = http://www.sunday-guardian.com/investigation/ethical-hacker-ankit-fadia-is-a-fake | title = Ethical hacker Ankit Fadia is a fake | date = 19 February 2012 | accessdate = 2013-02-26 | newspaper = The Sunday Guardian | author = Shubhankar Adhikari }}</ref> A security professional, who uses the handle @FakeAnkitFadia on Twitter, told ''The Sunday Guardian'', \"The first book that Fadia 'wrote' at the age of 14, ''The Unofficial Guide to Ethical Hacking'', was a little over 32% [ plagiarised] from other security publications and websites.\"<ref name=\"SMH_2003\">{{cite news  | title=Hacktivism through the eyes of an infiltrator  | url=http://www.smh.com.au/articles/2003/08/04/1059849331034.html  | author=Suelette Dreyfus  | date = 5 August 2003  | accessdate = 2013-02-26 | work=The Sydney Morning Herald}}</ref> Fadia has dismissed the critics who question his credibility as an expert, saying \"If I had been fake, my growth would have stopped 10 years ago\".<ref>{{cite news|title=A clean hacker|author=Rana Siddiqui Zaman|first=|date=22 January 2010|newspaper=The Hindu|location=Chennai, India}}</ref>\n\n== Hacking claims and controversies ==\nIn 2002, Fadia claimed that at the age of 17, he had defaced the website of an Indian magazine,<ref name=\"BBC_2002\"/> Subsequently, he named the magazine as the Indian edition of [[CHIP (magazine)|CHIP magazine]], and stated that the editor had offered him a job when informed about the defacement.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.thehindu.com/sci-tech/inside-account/article48684.ece | title=Inside Account | author = Priyadarshini Paitandy | date=14 September 2009 | accessdate = 2013-03-01 | location=Chennai, India | work=The Hindu}}</ref> In 2012, the Forbes India executive editor Charles Assisi (who was editor of CHIP India at the time of the supposed incident), denied that such an incident ever took place after verifying with his predecessor and successor at the magazine as well.<ref>{{cite web|title=Ankit Fadia Revealed|url=http://forbesindia.com/article/beyond-business/ankit-fadia-revealed/34793/0|accessdate=2013-02-21}}</ref>\n\nIn a 2002 interview published on [[rediff.com]], and online Hacking with Mashup(Sourav) from Bongaon, Kolkata, he stated that at the age of 16, he foiled an attempt by the [[Insurgency in Jammu and Kashmir|Kashmiri separatist]] hackers to [[website defacement|deface]] an Indian website.<ref name=\"rediff_kashmiri_2002\"/> He stated he gathered information about the attackers, [[eavesdropping|eavesdropped]] on their [[online chat]] using one of their identities, and then mailed the transcript to a US spy organisation that had hired him.<ref name=\"thestar_2005\">{{cite news | url = http://thestar.com.my/news/story.asp?file=/2005/2/27/nation/10276403&sec=nation | title = Teen helping adults fight 'bad guys' | author = M. Krishnamoorthy | newspaper = [[The Star (Malaysia)|The Star]] | date = 27 February 2005 | accessdate = 2013-02-26 }}</ref> He did not divulge the name of the organization he worked for, citing security reasons.<ref name=\"BBC_2002\"/> The Pakistani hacker group Anti-India Crew (AIC) questioned Fadia's claims: along with WFD, the AIC hacked the Indian government website epfindia.gov.in, dedicating it to Fadia, mocking his capabilities.<ref>{{cite news | url= http://hindu.com/2002/04/28/stories/2002042800921000.htm | title=This hacker has a different message | author=K. Srinivas Reddy | publisher=The Hindu | date=28 April 2002 | accessdate=2013-02-26 | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081221233959/http://www.hinduonnet.com/thehindu/2002/04/28/stories/2002042800921000.htm | archivedate=21 December 2008  | url-status=live | location=Chennai, India}}</ref> AIC also announced that it would be defacing the website of the [[Central Board of Excise and Customs|CBEC]] (www.cbec.gov.in) within the next two days, and challenged Fadia to prevent it by patching the vulnerability.<ref name=\"TheHindu_CBEC\">{{cite news | url=http://hindu.com/2002/04/30/stories/2002043002271300.htm | title=Hacker threat to CBEC website | author=K. Srinivas Reddy | publisher=The Hindu | date=30 April 2002 | accessdate=2013-02-26 | archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20081221234004/http://www.hinduonnet.com/thehindu/2002/04/30/stories/2002043002271300.htm | archivedate=21 December 2008  | url-status=live | location=Chennai, India}}</ref>\n\nIn 2003, he claimed to have infiltrated a group of hackers and stated that the Pakistani intelligence agencies were paying \"[[Westerners]]\" to [[Website defacement|deface]] Indian websites with anti-India or pro-Pakistan content.<ref name=\"SMH_2003\"/>\n\nFadia's own website has been hacked multiple times.<ref name=\"sunday_guardian_2012\"/> In 2009, he blamed the defacement on a vulnerability in the servers of his [[webhost]] net4india. Independent security experts contested his claim, stating that the problem was a loophole in his own website's code, His website was hacked by an Indian [[hacker]] Himanshu Sharma, where he accepted the challenge from Ankit Fadia.<ref>{{cite web|title=Is Ankit Fadia selling Viagra? |url=http://www.mid-day.com/news/2009/dec/081209-ankit-fadia-hacker-hacked.htm |author=MiD DAY |date=8 December 2009 |accessdate=2013-02-26 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091213004836/http://www.mid-day.com/news/2009/dec/081209-ankit-fadia-hacker-hacked.htm |archivedate=13 December 2009  |url-status=live}}</ref> In 2012, his website was defaced twice by hackers. In the first instance, the hackers rubbished his claims and stated that he was fooling people.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://news.softpedia.com/news/Ankit-Fadia-s-Website-Suspended-After-Being-Defaced-by-Ganster-291673.shtml | title=Ankit Fadia's site Suspended After Being Hacked by Ganster | publisher = Softpedia | author = Eduard Kovacs | date = 12 September 2012 | accessdate = 2013-02-26 }}</ref> Another hacker compromised it in response to a challenge that was issued by Fadia on the ''Tech Toyz'' show on CNBC-TV18.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=a93qi17GqMU&feature=player_embedded|title=Tech Toyz Hacking Special Episode Part III|date=10 August 2011}}</ref>{{Synthesis inline|date=March 2013}}\n\nIn 2012, [[DEF CON]] awarded him with the \"Security Charlatan of the Year\" award<ref name=\"youtube.com\">{{cite av media|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=GIzvTwFwaYI&t=33m3s|title=DEFCON 20: DC RECOGNIZE Awards|date=16 November 2012|work=YouTube|accessdate=28 September 2015}}</ref> citing him to be a fraudster and his presentations outdated. The website [http://attrition.org/errata/charlatan/ankit_fadia/ attrition.org] mentions him as a security charlatan<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|title = attrition.org Errata - Charlatans|url = http://attrition.org/errata/charlatan/|website = attrition.org|accessdate = 2015-09-19}}</ref> and accuses him of plagiarism in his work\n\n==Television and web shows==\n\n* MTV What The Hack\n\nIn October 2009 [[MTV India]] announced the launch of Fadia's new TV show on MTV called ''[[MTV What the Hack!]]', where Fadia gave tips on how to make use of the Internet, and answered people's questions.<ref name=\"Dnaindia.com\"/> Internet users could email their problems to MTV India and Fadia gave them a solution on the show.<ref name=\"MTV India\">{{cite web|url=|title=VJs, Music, Videos, Blogs, Games, Wallpapers, Interviews, Performances, Shows, Fun and more|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=MTV India|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091121015512/http://www.mtvindia.com/news/news.php?id=3419|archivedate=21 November 2009|df=dmy}}</ref>\n\n* Unzipped By Dell\n\nIn 2012, [[Dell]] India partnered with Ankit Fadia to create a series of nearly 50 videos, each of 1 minute duration to show tips and tricks for the use of computers and mobile phones. These videos were shown on the Dell India Facebook page with an average of one video per week. People also had the opportunity to ask tech queries of Fadia on topics like photography, video making, music composing, navigation assistance, gaming, messaging and others.<ref name=\"India Infoline News Service\">{{cite web|url=http://www.indiainfoline.com/article/news/dell-india-in-association-with-ankit-fadia-presents-unzipped-by-dell-and-ankit-fadia-5555289971_1.html |title=Dell India in association with Ankit Fadia presents &quot;Unzipped: By Dell and Ankit Fadia |publisher=India Infoline News Service |date= |accessdate=2012-09-21}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://efytimes.com/e1/95718/Dell-India-In-Association-With-Ankit-Fadia-Presents-Unzipped-By-Dell-And-Ankit-Fadia |title=Dell India in association with Ankit Fadia presents &quot;Unzipped: By Dell and Ankit Fadia |publisher=EFYTimes.com |accessdate=2012-09-21 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150205230534/http://efytimes.com/e1/95718/Dell-India-In-Association-With-Ankit-Fadia-Presents-Unzipped-By-Dell-And-Ankit-Fadia |archive-date=5 February 2015 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/UnzippedbyDell |title=Unzipped by Dell Facebook Page |publisher=Facebook|date= |accessdate=2012-09-21}}</ref>\n\n* Geek On The Loose\n\nIn 2013, Ankit Fadia started a YouTube show Geek On the Loose in collaboration with PING networks where he shared technology-related tips, tricks and apps.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newindianexpress.com/cities/chennai/Short-cuts-for-the-tech-savvy/2013/07/18/article1688412.ece |title=Short-cuts for the tech savvy |publisher=The New Indian Express |date= |accessdate=2012-09-21}}</ref>  The show was based on situations mentioned in his book FASTER: 100 Ways To Improve Your Digital Life.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/lifestyle/books/ankit-fadia-aims-at-stretching-technology-limits/article1-1108564.aspx |title=Ankit Fadia aims at stretching technology limits |publisher=The Hindustan Times |date= |accessdate=2012-09-21}}</ref> The show has got more than 750,000+ views on YouTube.<ref name=\"Geek On the Loose\"/>\n\n== Awards and Recognitions ==\n* IT Youth Award from the Singapore Computer Society (2005) <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.scs.org.sg/news_centre/Press%20Release%202012/Press%20Release_IT%20Leader%20Awards%202012.pdf |title=Media Release IT Leader Awards 2012 |publisher=Singapore Computer Society |accessdate=2014-09-23}}</ref>\n* Global Ambassador for Cyber Security (National Telecom Awards 2011, Government of India)<ref>[http://www.cmaievents.com/awardees2011.php The CMAI 5th National Awards]. Cmaievents.com (2011-06-08). Retrieved on 2013-08-02.</ref>\n* Global Shaper, World Economic Forum <ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.globalshapers.org/shapers/ankit-fadia |title=Ankit Fadia{{!}}World Economic Forum: Global Shapers |publisher=World Economic Forum |accessdate=2014-09-23 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150205121332/http://www.globalshapers.org/shapers/ankit-fadia |archive-date=5 February 2015 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n*  [[DEF CON|DEF CON 20]] Security [[Charlatan]] of the year.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://scroll.in/article/758921/ankit-fadias-biggest-hack-getting-modi-government-to-make-him-a-brand-ambassador|title=Ankit Fadia's biggest hack: Getting Modi government to make him a brand ambassador|last=Daniyal|first=Shoaib|website=Scroll.in|language=en-US|access-date=2019-02-26}}</ref><ref name=\"youtube.com\"/><ref>[http://pib.nic.in/newsite/PrintRelease.aspx?relid=128306 Clarification on Appointment of Brand Ambassadors]. Ministry of Communications & Information Technology, 29 September 2015.</ref> (This is not a positive endorsement)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Fadia, Ankit}}\n[[Category:1985 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Indian technology writers]]\n[[Category:Delhi Public School alumni]]\n", "name_user": "AshishSharma112", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(Original image add / Formatting completed)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ankit_Fadia"}
{"title_page": "The Little Mermaid (1989 film)", "text_new": "{{good article}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2015}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name                  = The Little Mermaid\n| image                 = The Little Mermaid (Official 1989 Film Poster).png\n| alt                   = \n| caption               = Original theatrical release poster by [[John Alvin]]\n| director              = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Ron Clements]]\n* [[John Musker]]\n}}\n| producer              = {{Plainlist|\n* John Musker\n* [[Howard Ashman]]\n}}\n| writer                = {{Plainlist|\n* Ron Clements\n* John Musker\n}}\n| based on              = {{Based on|''[[The Little Mermaid]]''|[[Hans Christian Andersen]]}}\n| starring              = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Ren\u00e9 Auberjonois]]\n* [[Christopher Daniel Barnes]]\n* [[Jodi Benson]]\n* [[Pat Carroll]]\n* [[Paddi Edwards]]\n* [[Buddy Hackett]]\n* Jason Marin\n* [[Kenneth Mars]]\n* [[Edie McClurg]]\n* [[Will Ryan]]\n* [[Ben Wright (English actor)|Ben Wright]]\n* [[Samuel E. Wright]]\n}}\n| music                 = [[Alan Menken]]\n| editing               = Mark Hester\n| production companies  = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Walt Disney Pictures]]\n* [[Walt Disney Animation Studios|Walt Disney Feature Animation]]\n* [[Silver Screen Partners|Silver Screen Partners IV]]\n}}\n| distributor           = [[Walt Disney Studios Motion Pictures|Buena Vista Pictures]]\n| released              = {{Film date|1989|11|17}}\n| runtime               = 83 minutes<!--Theatrical runtime: 82:32--><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbfc.co.uk/releases/little-mermaid-film|title=''THE LITTLE MERMAID'' (U)|work=[[British Board of Film Classification]]|date=December 28, 1989|access-date=April 2, 2016}}</ref>\n| country               = United States\n| language              = English\n| budget                = $40 million<ref name=disneywar>Stewart, James B. (2005). ''[[DisneyWar]]'', p. 104. {{ISBN|0-684-80993-1}}. [[Simon & Schuster]]. Retrieved June 4, 2007.</ref>\n| gross                 = {{US$|233 million|long=no}}<ref name=\"DisneyWW\"/>\n}}\n'''''The Little Mermaid''''' is a 1989 American [[animation|animated]] [[musical film|musical]] [[romantic fantasy film]] produced by [[Walt Disney Animation Studios|Walt Disney Feature Animation]] and [[Walt Disney Pictures]]. The 28th [[List of Walt Disney Animation Studios films|Disney animated feature film]] and the first film in [[The Little Mermaid (franchise)|''The Little Mermaid'' franchise]], it is loosely based on the Danish [[fairy tale]] [[The Little Mermaid|of the same name]] by [[Hans Christian Andersen]]. The film tells the story of a [[mermaid]] Princess named [[Ariel (The Little Mermaid)|Ariel]] who dreams of becoming human and falls in love with a human prince named [[List of Disney's The Little Mermaid characters#Prince Eric|Eric]]. Written and directed by [[Ron Clements]] and [[John Musker]], with music by [[Alan Menken]] and [[Howard Ashman]] (who also served as co-producer alongside John Musker), and art direction by [[Michael Peraza|Michael Peraza Jr.]] and Donald A. Towns, the film features the voices of [[Jodi Benson]], [[Christopher Daniel Barnes]], [[Pat Carroll (actress)|Pat Carroll]], [[Samuel E. Wright]], Jason Marin, [[Kenneth Mars]], [[Buddy Hackett]], and [[Ren\u00e9 Auberjonois]].\n\n''The Little Mermaid'' was released to theaters on November 17, 1989 to critical acclaim, earning praise for the animation, music, and plot. It was also a commercial success, garnering $84 million at the domestic box office during its initial release,<ref>{{cite web|title=The Little Mermaid (1989) \u2013 Box Office Summary|url=https://boxofficemojo.com/movies/?page=releases&id=littlemermaid.htm|website=[[Box Office Mojo]]}}</ref> and {{US$|233 million|long=no}} in total lifetime gross worldwide.<ref name=\"DisneyWW\"/> After the success of the 1986 [[Walt Disney Pictures|Disney]] animated film ''[[The Great Mouse Detective]]''<ref>https://www.mouseplanet.com/9534/How_Basil_Saved_Disney_Feature_Animation_Part_One</ref><ref>https://www.mouseplanet.com/9549/How_Basil_Saved_Disney_Feature_Animation_Part_Two</ref> and the 1988 Disney/[[Amblin Entertainment|Amblin]] live-action/animated film ''[[Who Framed Roger Rabbit]]'', ''The Little Mermaid'' is given credit for breathing life back into the art of Disney animated feature films after a string of critical or commercial failures produced by Disney that dated back to the early 1970s. It also marked the start of the era known as the [[Disney Renaissance]].<ref name=\"Pallant1\">{{cite book|last1=Pallant|first1=Chris|title=Demystifying Disney: A History of Disney Feature Animation|date=2011|publisher=Continuum Publishing|location=New York|isbn=9781441150462|page=89|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=zOCoAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA89|access-date=January 13, 2017}}</ref> The film won two Academy Awards for [[Academy Award for Best Original Score|Best Original Score]] and [[Academy Award for Best Original Song|Best Original Song]] (\"[[Under the Sea]]\").\n\nThe film's success lead to a [[The Little Mermaid (musical)|stage adaptation]] with a book by [[Doug Wright]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Q&A With Grey Gardens Playwright Doug Wright\u2014New York Magazine|url=https://nymag.com/arts/theater/profiles/16075|publisher=Newyorkmetro.com|first=Boris|last=Kachka|date=February 26, 2006|access-date=July 15, 2009}}</ref> and additional songs by [[Alan Menken]] and new lyricist [[Glenn Slater]] opened in Denver in July 2007 and began performances on [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] January 10, 2008<ref>{{cite web|title=Playbill Features: STAGE TO SCREENS: Chatting with Grey Gardens and Little Mermaid Librettist Doug Wright|url=https://www.playbill.com/features/article/stage-to-screens-chatting-with-grey-gardens-and-little-mermaid-librettist-d-130245|work=Playbill|date=January 6, 2006|access-date=July 15, 2009|author=Michael Buckley}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=The Little Mermaid to Celebrate First Broadway Anniversary January 10|url=https://www.playbill.com/news/article/the-little-mermaid-to-celebrate-first-broadway-anniversary-jan.-10-156713|date=January 8, 2009|author=Andrew Gans|work=Playbill|access-date=October 22, 2010}}</ref> starring [[Sierra Boggess]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.playbill.com/article/from-little-mermaid-to-phantom-of-the-opera-sierra-boggess-6-most-memorable-nights-onstage|title=From Little Mermaid to Phantom of the Opera, Sierra Boggess\u2019 6 Most Memorable Nights Onstage|first=Andrew|last=Gans|date=November 3, 2017|publisher=Playbill.com|location=New York City}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.broadway.com/buzz/96308/sierra-boggess-cast-as-ariel-in-disneys-the-little-mermaid/|title=Sierra Boggess Cast as Ariel in Disney's The Little Mermaid|publisher=Broadway.com|location=New York City}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ibdb.com/broadway-production/the-little-mermaid-456222|title=The Little Mermaid on Internet Broadway Database|publisher=The Broadway League|location=New York City}}</ref> Other derived works and material inspired by the movie, include a live-action film adaptation, directed by [[Rob Marshall]], currently in development, and a 2019 [[The Little Mermaid Live!|live musical presentation]] of the film airing on [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] as part of ''[[The Wonderful World of Disney]]''.\n\n==Plot==\n<!-- Per WP:FILMPLOT, plot summaries for feature film articles should be between 400 and 700 words in length. -->\n[[Ariel (The Little Mermaid)|Ariel]] is a 16-year-old mermaid Princess in the kingdom of Atlantica, in the Atlantic Ocean. She is fascinated by the human world above. She ventures out with her best friend [[List of Disney's The Little Mermaid characters#Flounder|Flounder]] to collect human artifacts in her [[grotto]] and often goes to the surface of the ocean to visit [[List of Disney's The Little Mermaid characters#Scuttle|Scuttle]], a seagull who offers inaccurate knowledge of human culture. She swims back to Atlantica and is watched by two eels named [[List of Disney's The Little Mermaid characters#Flotsam and Jetsam|Flotsam and Jetsam]] under orders from [[Ursula (The Little Mermaid)|Ursula]] the sea witch. Ariel ignores the warnings of her father [[List of Disney's The Little Mermaid characters#King Triton|King Triton]], the ruler of Atlantica, and [[List of The Little Mermaid characters#Sebastian|Sebastian]], a crab who serves as Triton's adviser and court composer, that contact with humans is forbidden.\n\nOne night, Ariel, Flounder, and an unwilling Sebastian travel to the surface to watch a celebration for [[List of Disney's The Little Mermaid characters#Prince Eric|Prince Eric]]'s birthday on a ship. Ariel instantly falls in love with Eric. Shortly afterward, a violent storm arrives, which wrecks the ship and tosses Eric overboard. Ariel rescues him and brings him to shore. She sings to him but leaves just as he regains consciousness to avoid being discovered. Fascinated by the memory of her voice, Eric vows to find the girl who saved and sang to him; Ariel vows to find a way to join him in his world. Noticing a change in Ariel's behavior, Triton questions Sebastian and learns of her love for Eric. Triton confronts Ariel in her grotto and destroys the artifacts she collected with his trident. After Triton leaves, Ariel begins weeping. Flotsam and Jetsam convince her to visit Ursula.\n\nUrsula makes a deal with Ariel to transform her into a human for three days in exchange for Ariel's voice, which Ursula puts in a nautilus shell. Within these three days, Ariel must receive the \"kiss of true love\" from Eric to remain a human permanently. Otherwise, she will transform back into a mermaid and belong to Ursula. Ariel accepts and is given human legs and taken to the surface by Flounder and Sebastian. Unbeknownst to Ariel, Ursula, who harbors a secret vendetta against King Triton, plans to use her as a bargaining chip and take over the kingdom. Eric finds Ariel on the beach and takes her to his castle, unaware that she is the one who had rescued him earlier. Ariel spends time with Eric, and at the end of the second day, they almost kiss but are thwarted by Flotsam and Jetsam. Angered at Ariel's near success, Ursula disguises herself as a beautiful young woman named Vanessa and appears onshore singing with Ariel's voice. Eric recognizes the song and, in her disguise, Ursula casts a hypnotic enchantment on Eric to make him forget about Ariel and marry Vanessa instead.\n\nThe next day, Ariel discovers that Eric will be married to Vanessa. Scuttle discovers Vanessa's true identity and informs Ariel, who immediately pursues the wedding barge. While Sebastian informs Triton, Scuttle disrupts the wedding with the help of various sea animals. Through all of the commotion the nautilus shell around Ursula's neck breaks, which restores Ariel's voice back to her and breaks Ursula's enchantment over Eric. Realizing that Ariel is the girl who saved his life, Eric rushes to kiss her, but the sun sets and Ariel transforms back into a mermaid. Ursula then reveals herself and kidnaps Ariel. Triton confronts Ursula and demands Ariel's release. However, the deal is inviolable; Triton makes a new deal to take Ariel's place as Ursula's servant by giving up his trident in order to save his daughter. Ariel is released as Triton transforms into a [[Polyp (zoology)|polyp]] and loses his authority over Atlantica. Ursula declares herself the new ruler, but before she can use the trident, Ariel confronts Ursula and attacks her, and Eric intervenes with a harpoon and hurts Ursula. Ursula attempts to kill Eric, but Ariel intervenes and causes Ursula to inadvertently kill Flotsam and Jetsam. As Ariel hurries to join Eric, the enraged Ursula uses the trident to grow to a monstrous size.\n\nAriel and Eric reunite on the surface just before Ursula grows past and towers over them. She then gains full control of the entire ocean, creating a storm and bringing sunken ships to the surface. As Ursula is about to destroy Ariel with the trident, Eric steers a wrecked ship and kills Ursula by impaling her with its splintered [[bowsprit]]. With Ursula dead, Triton and the other polyps in Ursula's garden revert to their original forms. Realizing that Ariel loves Eric, Triton changes her from a mermaid into a human permanently and approves her marriage to Eric. At the wedding, Ariel and Eric marry on a ship and depart.\n\n==Voice cast==\n{{Main|List of The Little Mermaid characters}}\n* [[Jodi Benson]] as [[Ariel (The Little Mermaid)|Princess Ariel]], the 16-year-old mermaid princess of Atlantica who is fascinated with humans, especially Prince Eric.<ref name=\"DisneyChar\">{{cite book|last=Grant|first=John|title=Encyclopedia of Walt Disney's Animated Characters (Third Edition)|publisher=Hyperion|year=1998|pages=344\u2013345|isbn=0-7868-6336-6}}</ref>\n:* Benson also voices Vanessa, Ursula's human alter ego\n* [[Christopher Daniel Barnes]] as [[List of The Little Mermaid characters#Prince Eric|Prince Eric]], a human prince saved by Ariel and is determined to find and marry her.<ref name=\"nytimes1\">{{cite news|last=|first=|date=July 14, 2014|title=The-Little-Mermaid \u2013 Cast, Crew, Director and Awards|url=https://www.nytimes.com/movies/movie/29563/The-Little-Mermaid/cast/|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|access-date=July 1, 2018|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140715022533/https://www.nytimes.com/movies/movie/29563/The-Little-Mermaid/cast|archive-date=July 15, 2014}}</ref>\n* [[Pat Carroll]] as [[Ursula (The Little Mermaid)|Ursula]], a sea witch who stole Ariel's voice and is determined to ruin her attempts to get Eric to love her.<ref name=\"nytimes1\" />\n* [[Samuel E. Wright]] as [[List of The Little Mermaid characters#Sebastian|Sebastian]], a worrisome Jamaican [[crab]] who serves as King Triton's advisor and court composer.<ref name=\"nytimes1\" />\n* Jason Marin as [[List of The Little Mermaid characters#Flounder|Flounder]], Ariel's [[fish]] best friend.<ref name=\"nytimes1\" />\n* [[Kenneth Mars]] as [[List of The Little Mermaid characters#King Triton|King Triton]], Ariel's father and the ruler of Atlantica who despises humans.<ref name=\"nytimes1\" />\n* [[Buddy Hackett]] as Scuttle, a dimwitted [[seagull]] who shares Ariel's fascination with humans and teaches her about \"human stuff\".<ref name=\"nytimes1\" />\n* [[Paddi Edwards]] as Flotsam and Jetsam, Ursula's symbiotic and insidious pet [[eel]]s.<ref name=\"nytimes1\" />\n* [[Ben Wright (English actor)|Ben Wright]] as Grimsby, Eric's loyal [[valet]].<ref name=\"nytimes1\" />\n* [[Edie McClurg]] as Carlotta, Eric's maid.<ref name=\"nytimes1\" />\n* [[Kimmy Robertson]] as Andrina, Arista, Adella and Alana, four of Ariel's sisters.<ref name=\"nytimes1\" />\n* [[Caroline Vasicek]] as Aquata and Attina, two more of Ariel's sisters.<ref name=\"nytimes1\" />\n* [[Will Ryan]] as Harold, a [[seahorse]] and Triton's herald.<ref name=\"nytimes1\" />\n* [[Ren\u00e9 Auberjonois]] as Chef Louis, Eric's mad chef who attempts to cook Sebastian, but fails.<ref name=\"nytimes1\" />\n\n==Production==\n===Story development===\n[[File:Georges de La Tour - Magdalen of Night Light - WGA12337.jpg|thumb|[[Georges de La Tour]]'s painting ''[[Magdalene with the Smoking Flame]]'' (1640) is shown in the film.]]\n''The Little Mermaid'' was originally planned as part of one of [[Walt Disney]]'s earliest feature films, a proposed [[Anthology film|package film]] featuring vignettes of [[Hans Christian Andersen]] tales.<ref name=\"commentaryTLM\" /> Development started soon after ''[[Snow White and the Seven Dwarfs (1937 film)|Snow White and the Seven Dwarfs]]'' in the late 1930s, but was delayed due to various circumstances.<ref>{{cite web|title=Disney's animated zombies: How classic stories are lost in reinvention|url=http://www.salon.com/2014/05/02/disneys_animated_zombies_how_classic_stories_are_lost_in_reinvention/|work=salon.com}}</ref>\n\nIn 1985, [[Ron Clements]] became interested in a film adaptation of ''The Little Mermaid'' while he was serving as a director on ''[[The Great Mouse Detective]]'' (1986) alongside [[John Musker]].<ref name=\"80srewindmermaid\">{{cite web|title=Making Of... The Little Mermaid Behind The Scenes|url=https://www.fast-rewind.com/making_littlemermaid.htm|work=The 80s Movies Rewind|publisher=Fast-Rewind.com|year=2009|access-date=June 20, 2013}}</ref> Clements discovered the Hans Christian Andersen fairy tale while browsing through a [[bookstore]].<ref name=\"makingofTLM\" /> Believing the story provided an \"ideal basis\" for an animated feature film and keen on creating a film that took place underwater,<ref name=\"80srewindmermaid\" /> Clements wrote and presented a two-page [[Film treatment|treatment]] of ''The Little Mermaid'' [[Walt Disney Studios (division)|Walt Disney Studios]] to chief [[Jeffrey Katzenberg]] at a \"gong show\" idea suggestion meeting. Katzenberg passed the project over, because at that time the studio was in development on a sequel to their live-action mermaid comedy ''[[Splash (film)|Splash]]'' (1984) and felt ''The Little Mermaid'' would be too similar a project.<ref name=\"makingofTLM\" /> The next day, however, Katzenberg approved of the idea for possible development, along with ''[[Oliver & Company]]''. While in production in the 1980s, the staff found, by chance, original story and visual development work done by [[Kay Nielsen]] for Disney's proposed 1930s Andersen feature.<ref name=\"commentaryTLM\" /> Many of the changes made by the staff in the 1930s to Hans Christian Andersen's original story was coincidentally the same as the changes made by Disney writers in the 1980s.<ref name=\"makingofTLM\">(2006) ''Treasures Untold: The Making of Disney's 'The Little Mermaid'' [Documentary featurette]. Bonus material from ''The Little Mermaid: Platinum Edition'' DVD. Walt Disney Home Entertainment.</ref>\n\nThat year Clements and Musker expanded the two-page idea into a 20-page rough script, eliminating the role of the mermaid's grandmother and expanding the roles of the Merman King and the sea witch. However, the film's plans were momentarily shelved as Disney focused its attention on ''[[Who Framed Roger Rabbit]]'' and ''Oliver & Company'' as more immediate releases.<ref name=\"makingofTLM\" /> In 1987, songwriter [[Howard Ashman]] became involved with the writing and development of ''The Little Mermaid'' after he was asked to contribute a song to ''Oliver & Company''. He proposed changing the minor character Clarence, the English-butler crab, to a Jamaican crab and shifting the music style throughout the film to reflect this. At the same time, Katzenberg, Clements, Musker, and Ashman revised the story format to make ''The Little Mermaid'' a musical with a Broadway-style story structure, with the song sequences serving as the tentpoles of the film.<ref name=\"commentaryTLM\" /> Ashman and composer [[Alan Menken]], both noted for their work as the writers of the successful [[Off-Broadway]] stage musical ''[[Little Shop of Horrors (musical)|Little Shop of Horrors]]'', teamed up to compose the entire song score. In 1988, with ''Oliver & Company'' out of the way, ''The Little Mermaid'' was slated as the next major Disney release.<ref name=\"wakingsleepingbeauty\">{{cite video|people=[[Don Hahn|Hahn, Don]]|title=[[Waking Sleeping Beauty]]|medium=Documentary film|publisher=Stone Circle Pictures/Walt Disney Studios Motion Pictures|location=Burbank, California|year=2009}}</ref>\n\n===Animation===\nMore money and resources were dedicated to ''The Little Mermaid'' than any other Disney animated film in decades.<ref name=\"commentaryTLM\" /> Aside from its main animation facility in [[Glendale, California]], Disney opened a satellite feature animation facility during the production of ''The Little Mermaid'' in [[Lake Buena Vista, Florida]] (near [[Orlando, Florida]]), within [[Disney-MGM Studios]] Theme Park at [[Walt Disney World]].<ref name=\"WDFAtimeline\" /> Opening in 1989, the Disney-MGM facility's first projects were to produce an entire [[Roger Rabbit]] cartoon short, ''[[Roller Coaster Rabbit]]'', and to contribute ink and paint support to ''The Little Mermaid''.<ref name=\"WDFAtimeline\" /> Another first for recent years was the filming of live actors and actresses for motion reference material for the animators, a practice used frequently for many of the Disney animated features produced under Walt Disney's supervision. [[Sherri Stoner|Sherri Lynn Stoner]], a former member of Los Angeles' [[Groundlings]] improvisation comedy group, and Joshua Finkel, a Broadway actor, performed key scenes as Ariel and Eric respectively.<ref name=\"makingofTLM\" /><ref name=\"liveactionref\">(2013) ''The Real Little Mermaid: Live Action Reference Model'' [Documentary featurette]. Bonus material from ''The Little Mermaid: Diamond Edition'' Blu-Ray. Walt Disney Home Entertainment.</ref> [[Jodi Benson]] had already been cast as Ariel's voice actor by this time, and her recorded dialogue was used as playback to guide these live-action references.<ref name=\"liveactionref\" /> Before Benson was cast, [[Melissa Fahn]] was considered for the part.<ref>{{cite web|first=Martin|last=Navarez|title=[RECAP] Anime Expo 2018: Day 2|url=https://www.kawaiikakkoiisugoi.com/2018/07/07/recap-anime-expo-2018-day-2/|access-date=November 9, 2018}}</ref>\n\n''The Little Mermaid''{{'s}} supervising animators included [[Glen Keane]] and [[Mark Henn]] on Ariel, Duncan Marjoribanks on Sebastian, [[Andreas Deja]] on King Triton, and Ruben Aquino on Ursula.<ref name=\"commentaryTLM\" /> Originally, Keane had been asked to work on Ursula, as he had established a reputation for drawing large, powerful figures, such as the bear in ''[[The Fox and the Hound]]'' (1981) and Professor Ratigan in ''[[The Great Mouse Detective]]'' (1986). Keane, however, was assigned as one of the two lead artists on the petite Ariel and oversaw the \"Part of Your World\" musical number. He jokingly stated that his wife looks exactly like Ariel \"without the fins.\"<ref>(2004) Interview with Glen Keane. Bonus material from ''[[Pocahontas (1995 film)|Pocahontas: 10th Anniversary Edition]]'' [DVD]. Walt Disney Home Entertainment.</ref> The character's body type and personality were based upon that of [[Alyssa Milano]], then starring on TV's ''[[Who's the Boss?]]'' and the effect of her hair underwater was based on both footage of [[Sally Ride]] when she was in space,<ref name=\"commentaryTLM\" /> and scenes of Stoner in a pool for guidance in animating Ariel's swimming.<ref>{{cite video|title=Under The Scene|location=''The Little Mermaid'' Blu-Ray|publisher=[[Walt Disney Studios Home Entertainment]]|date=2013}}</ref>\n\nThe design of the villainous [[Ursula (The Little Mermaid)|Ursula]] was based upon drag performer [[Divine (performer)|Divine]].<ref name=\"commentaryTLM\" /> An additional early inspiration before Divine was [[Joan Collins]] in her role as [[Alexis Carrington]] in the television show ''[[Dynasty (1981 TV series)|Dynasty]]'', due to a suggestion from Howard Ashman, who was a fan of the series.<ref name=\"HCWIntv\">{{cite AV media|title=''Harry Clayton-Wright interviews the directors of The Little Mermaid''|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=HbnNNx-iV8A|publisher=YouTube|medium=Digital video|people=Clayton-Wright, Harry|format=Web video content|date=September 2, 2013|access-date=September 6, 2013}}</ref> [[Pat Carroll (actress)|Pat Carroll]] was not Clements and Musker's first choice to voice Ursula; the original script had been written with [[Bea Arthur]] of the Disney-owned TV series ''[[The Golden Girls]]'' in mind. After Arthur turned the part down, actresses such as [[Nancy Marchand]], [[Nancy Wilson (rock musician)|Nancy Wilson]], [[Roseanne Barr|Roseanne]], [[Charlotte Rae]], and [[Elaine Stritch]] were considered for the part.<ref name=\"Ursula\" /> Stritch was eventually cast as Ursula, but clashed with Howard Ashman's style of music production and was replaced by Carroll.<ref name=\"Ursula\">{{cite book|title=Makin' Toons: Inside the Most Popular Animated TV Shows and Movies|first=Allan|last=Neuwirth|publisher=Allworth Communications, Inc.|year=2003|pages=[https://archive.org/details/makintoonsinside0000neuw/page/46 46\u201347]|isbn=1-58115-269-8|url=https://archive.org/details/makintoonsinside0000neuw/page/46}}</ref> Various actors auditioned for additional roles in the film, including [[Jim Carrey]] for the role of Prince Eric, and comedians [[Bill Maher]] and [[Michael Richards]] for the role of Scuttle.<ref name=\"HCWIntv\" />\n\nThe underwater setting required the most special effects animation for a Disney animated feature since ''[[Fantasia (1940 film)|Fantasia]]'' in 1940. Effects animation supervisor [[Mark Dindal]] estimated that over a million bubbles were drawn for this film, in addition to the use of other processes such as [[airbrush]]ing, backlighting, superimposition, and some [[computer animation]]. The artistic manpower needed for ''The Little Mermaid'' required Disney to farm out most of the underwater bubble effects animation in the film to Pacific Rim Productions, a China-based firm with production facilities in Beijing.<ref name=\"commentaryTLM\" /> An attempt to use Disney's famed [[multiplane camera]] for the first time in years for quality \"depth\" shots failed because the machine was reputedly in dilapidated condition. The multiplane shots were instead photographed at an outside animation camera facility.<ref name=\"commentaryTLM\">(2006) Audio Commentary by John Musker, Ron Clements, and Alan Menken Bonus material from ''The Little Mermaid: Platinum Edition'' [DVD]. Walt Disney Home Entertainment.</ref>\n\n''The Little Mermaid'' was the last Disney feature film to use the traditional hand-painted cel method of animation. Disney's next film, ''[[The Rescuers Down Under]]'', used a digital method of coloring and combining scanned drawings developed for Disney by [[Pixar]] called CAPS/ink & paint ([[Computer Animation Production System]]), which would eliminate the need for cels, the multiplane camera, and many of the optical effects used for the last time in ''The Little Mermaid''. A CAPS/ink & paint prototype was used experimentally on a few scenes in ''The Little Mermaid'', and one-shot produced using CAPS/ink & paint\u2014the penultimate shot in the film, of Ariel and Eric's wedding ship sailing away under a rainbow\u2014appears in the finished film. [[Computer-generated imagery]] was used to create some of the wrecked ships in the final battle, a staircase behind a shot of Ariel in Eric's castle, and the carriage Eric and Ariel are riding in when she bounces it over a ravine. These objects were animated using 3D wireframe models, which were [[plotter|plotted]] as line art to cels and painted traditionally.<ref name=\"commentaryTLM\" /> The film being both the first film of the [[Disney Renaissance]] and the last to use the [[xerography]] technology used since the late 1950s with ''[[Sleeping Beauty (1959 film)|Sleeping Beauty]]'' made it somewhat of a transitional film between the two Disney eras.<ref>https://www.tor.com/2015/07/23/the-advent-of-xerography-disneys-one-hundred-and-one-dalmatians/</ref><ref>https://ohmy.disney.com/insider/2016/01/11/why-does-101-dalmatians-look-like-that/</ref>\n\n===Music===\n{{Main|The Little Mermaid (soundtrack)}}\n''The Little Mermaid'' was considered by some as \"the film that brought Broadway into cartoons\".<ref>''Aladdin'' Platinum Edition, Disc 2: ''Alan Menken: Musical''</ref> [[Alan Menken]] wrote the [[Academy Awards|Oscar]]-winning score, and collaborated with [[Howard Ashman]] on the songs. One of the film's most prominent songs, \"[[Part of Your World]]\", was nearly cut from the film when it seemingly tested poorly with an audience of school children, who became rowdy during the scene. This caused Jeffrey Katzenberg to feel that the song needed to be cut, an idea that was resisted by Musker, Clements, and Keane. Both Musker and Clements cited the similar situation of the popular song \"[[Over the Rainbow]]\" nearly being cut from 1939's ''[[The Wizard of Oz (1939 film)|The Wizard of Oz]]'' when it was appealing to Katzenberg. Keane pushed for the song to remain until the film was in a more finalized state. During a second test screening, the scene, now colorized and further developed, tested well with a separate child audience, and the musical number was kept.<ref name=\"HCWIntv\" />\n\n==Release==\nThe film was originally released on November 17, 1989, followed by a re-release on November 14, 1997. After the success of the 3D re-release of ''[[The Lion King]]'', Disney announced a 3D re-release of ''The Little Mermaid'' scheduled for September 13, 2013,<ref>{{cite journal|title='Beauty and the Beast,' 'The Little Mermaid,' 'Finding Nemo,' 'Monsters, Inc.' get 3-D re-releases|url=https://www.ew.com/article/2011/10/04/disney-3d-beauty-beast-mermaid|magazine=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|first=Grady|last=Smith|date=October 4, 2011|access-date=October 27, 2011}}</ref> but this was cancelled on January 14, 2013, due to the under-performances of other Disney 3D re-releases until further notice.<ref>{{cite news|title=Disney cancels 'Little Mermaid 3-D,' dates 'Pirates 5' for 2015|url=https://articles.latimes.com/2013/jan/14/entertainment/la-et-ct-disney-cancels-little-mermaid-3d-pirates-5-2015-20130114|first=Ben|last=Fritz|newspaper=The Los Angeles Times|date=January 14, 2013|access-date=January 14, 2013}}</ref> The 3D version was released on [[Blu-ray]] instead,<ref name=\"3D Blu-Ray\">{{cite web|title=Mermaid fall Blu 3D; no Disneynature|url=https://hollywoodinhidef.com/2013/02/little-mermaid-3d-fall-blu-ray-no-disneynature/|author=Scott Hettrick|date=February 9, 2013|access-date=February 11, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=More Details On October's Little Mermaid Blu-ray Set|url=https://www.cinemablend.com/new/Little-Mermaid-Still-Get-3D-Diamond-Edition-37085.html|author=Jessica Rawden|access-date=April 22, 2013}}</ref> but it did play a limited engagement at the [[El Capitan Theatre]] from September to October 2013.<ref>{{cite web|title=Hollywood's El Capitan Will Be the Only Theatre in the World to Screen THE LITTLE MERMAID 3D, 9/13-10/13|url=https://www.broadwayworld.com/bwwmovies/article/Hollywoods-El-Capitan-Will-Be-Only-Theatre-in-the-World-to-Screen-THE-LITTLE-MERMAID-3D-913-1013-20130827|author=Oliver Oliveros|date=August 27, 2013|access-date=November 3, 2013}}</ref> On September 20, 2013, ''The Little Mermaid'' began playing in select theaters where audiences could bring [[iPad]]s and use an app called Second Screen Live.<ref>{{cite journal|url=https://www.ew.com/article/2013/09/10/little-mermaid-second-screen-app|title='The Little Mermaid' returns to theaters with a new-millennium twist: iPads allowed|first=Jennifer|last=Arellano|magazine=Entertainment Weekly|date=September 10, 2013|access-date=September 10, 2013}}</ref> [[AMC Theatres]] screened the movie from September 6-12, 2019.<ref>{{cite journal|url=https://insidethemagic.net/2019/09/disney-princesses-return-to-the-big-screen-kc1/|title=Disney Princesses return to the big screen|first=Kelly|last=Coffey|magazine=Inside the Magic|date=September 5, 2019|access-date=September 6, 2019}}</ref> The film was also screened out of competition at the [[1990 Cannes Film Festival]].<ref name=\"festival-cannes.com\">{{cite web|title=The Little Mermaid|url=https://www.festival-cannes.com/en/films/the-little-mermaid|website=Festival de Cannes|access-date=April 30, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Home media===\nIn a then-atypical and controversial move for a new Disney animated film, ''The Little Mermaid'' was released as part of the [[Walt Disney Classics]] line of VHS, [[Laserdisc]], Betamax, and Video 8 home video releases in May 1990, six months after the release of the film.<ref name=\"wakingsleepingbeauty\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/dp/6302212529|title=<nowiki>The Little Mermaid (A Walt Disney Classic) [VHS</nowiki>&#93;: Ron Clements, John Musker, Ren\u00e9 Auberjonois, Christopher Daniel Barnes, Jodi Benson, Pat Carroll, Paddi Edwards, Buddy Hackett, Jason Marin, Kenneth Mars, Edie McClurg, Will Ryan, Ben Wright, Samuel E. Wright: Movies & TV|publisher=Amazon.com|access-date=November 2, 2011}}</ref> Before ''The Little Mermaid'', only a select number of Disney's catalog animated films had been released to home video, as the company was afraid of upsetting its profitable practice of theatrically reissuing each film every few years.<ref name=\"wakingsleepingbeauty\" /> ''The Little Mermaid'' became that year's top-selling title on home video, with over 10 million units sold (including 7 million in its first month).<ref>{{cite news|title=THE NEW SEASON: HOME ENTERTAINMENT; 'Beauty' Was Big, but Make Way for 'Aladdin'\u2014New York Times|url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9F0CEEDC1039F931A2575AC0A965958260&n=Top%2fReference%2fTimes%20Topics%2fSubjects%2fR%2fRecords%20and%20Achievements|first=Peter M.|last=Nichols|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|date=September 12, 1993|access-date=July 15, 2009}}</ref> The home video release, along with box office and merchandise sales, contributed to ''The Little Mermaid'' generating a total revenue of {{US$|1 billion|long=no}}.<ref>{{cite news|last=Hofmeister|first=Sallie|title=In the Realm of Marketing, 'The Lion King' Rules|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1994/07/12/business/in-the-realm-of-marketing-the-lion-king-rules.html|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=July 12, 1994|access-date=September 26, 2018|language=English}}</ref> This success led to future Disney films being released on home video soon after the end of their theatrical runs, rather than delayed for several years.<ref name=\"wakingsleepingbeauty\" />\n\nFollowing ''The Little Mermaid''{{'}}s 1997 re-release in theaters, a new VHS version was released in March 1998 as part of the Masterpiece Collection and included a bonus music video of [[Jodi Benson]] singing \"Part of Your World\" during the end credits, replacing \"Under the Sea\" as the end credits song.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/dp/0788812408|title=<nowiki>The Little Mermaid (Fully Restored Special Edition) [VHS</nowiki>&#93;: Jodi Benson, Samuel E. Wright, Ren\u00e9 Auberjonois, Christopher Daniel Barnes, Pat Carroll, Paddi Edwards, Buddy Hackett, Jason Marin, Kenneth Mars, Edie McClurg, Will Ryan, Ben Wright, John Musker, Ron Clements, Chris Hubbell, Gerrit Graham, Hans Christian Andersen, Howard Ashman: Movies & TV|publisher=Amazon.com|access-date=November 2, 2011}}</ref> The VHS sold 13 million units and ranked as the third best-selling video of the year.<ref>{{cite web|title=Press Release Page|url=https://www.mickey-mouse.com/pressreleases.htm#TBC|publisher=Mickey-mouse.com|access-date=July 15, 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=VidNews Archives|url=https://www.onvideo.org/oldnews.htm|publisher=OnVideo|access-date=July 15, 2009}}</ref>\n\n''The Little Mermaid'' was released in a \"bare-bones\" limited issue [[DVD]] in 1999, with a standard video transfer.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/dp/B00001QEE7|title=The Little Mermaid (Limited Issue): Jodi Benson, Samuel E. Wright, Ren\u00e9 Auberjonois, Christopher Daniel Barnes, Pat Carroll, Paddi Edwards, Buddy Hackett, Jason Marin, Kenneth Mars, Edie McClurg, Will Ryan, Ben Wright, John Musker, Ron Clements, Chris Hubbell, Gerrit Graham, Hans Christian Andersen, Howard Ashman: Movies & TV|publisher=Amazon.com|access-date=November 2, 2011}}</ref> The film was re-released on DVD on October 3, 2006, as part of the Walt Disney Platinum Editions line of classic Walt Disney animated features, including the song \"Kiss the Girl\" performed by [[Ashley Tisdale]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/dp/B000F8O35U|title=The Little Mermaid (Two-Disc Platinum Edition): Ren\u00e9 Auberjonois, Christopher Daniel Barnes, Jodi Benson, Pat Carroll, Paddi Edwards, Buddy Hackett, Jason Marin, Kenneth Mars, Edie McClurg, Will Ryan, Ben Wright, Samuel E. Wright, Hamilton Camp, Kimmy Robertson, Mickie McGowan, Jim Cummings, Tim Curry, Jennifer Darling, Gerrit Graham, Malachi Pearson: Movies & TV|publisher=Amazon.com|access-date=November 2, 2011}}</ref> Deleted scenes and several in-depth documentaries were included, as well as an Academy Award-nominated short film intended for the shelved ''Fantasia 2006'', ''[[The Little Matchgirl (2006 film)|The Little Matchgirl]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dvdizzy.com/littlemermaid-platinumedition-pressrelease.html|title=The Little Mermaid: Platinum Edition\u2014DVD Press Release|publisher=UltimateDisney|access-date=July 15, 2009}}</ref> The DVD sold 1.6 million units on its first day of release,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.comingsoon.net/news/dvdnews.php?id=16821|title=Record Starts for X-Men and Mermaid\u2014ComingSoon.net|publisher=ComingSoon|access-date=July 15, 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071012130631/http://comingsoon.net/news/dvdnews.php?id=16821|archive-date=October 12, 2007}}</ref> and over 4 million units during its first week, making it the biggest animated DVD debut for October. By the year's end, the DVD had sold about 7 million units and was one of the year's top 10 selling DVDs.<ref>{{cite web|title=Weekly Breakdown Sales For The Little Mermaid DVD|url=https://www.the-numbers.com/movie/Little-Mermaid-The#tab=video-sales|publisher=The-numbers.com|access-date=July 15, 2009}}</ref> The Platinum Edition DVD was released as part of a \"''Little Mermaid'' Trilogy\" boxed set on December 16, 2008.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Little Mermaid Trilogy: The Little Mermaid: Ariel's Beginning, The Little Mermaid, The Little Mermaid II: Return To The Sea Special Edition, .: Movies & TV|url=https://www.amazon.com/dp/B001G2S3XC|publisher=Amazon.com|access-date=November 2, 2011}}</ref> The Platinum Edition of the film, along with its sequels, went on moratorium in January 2009. The film was re-released on a 3-disc [[Blu-ray]]/DVD/Digital Copy combo, a 2-disc Blu-ray/DVD combo and [[3D Blu-ray]] on October 1, 2013, as part of the Walt Disney Diamond Editions line.<ref name=\"3D Blu-Ray\" /><ref>[https://www.cinemablend.com/new/Check-Out-Little-Mermaid-First-Blu-ray-Trailer-35466.html Check Out The Little Mermaid's First Blu-ray Trailer] Retrieved February 13, 2013</ref> ''The Little Mermaid'' was re-released on HD and [[4K resolution|4K]] digital download on February 12, 2019, with a physical media re-release on Blu-ray and [[Ultra HD Blu-ray]] on February 26, 2019, as part of the ''Walt Disney Signature Collection'' in honor of the film's 30th anniversary.\n\n===Live presentations===\nIn June 2016, Disney held special presentations of the film at the [[Hollywood Bowl]] in Los Angeles, titled ''The Little Mermaid in Concert''. The performances combined a screening of ''The Little Mermaid'' with live accompaniment by guest musicians and celebrities, including [[Sara Bareilles]] (who performed as Ariel), [[Tituss Burgess]] (who performed as Sebastian as a reprisal of his role in the stage adaptation), [[Darren Criss]] (who performed as Prince Eric), [[Rebel Wilson]] (who performed as Ursula), Joshua Colley (who performed as Flounder), [[John Stamos]] (who performed as Chef Louis) and [[Norm Lewis]] (who performed as King Triton as a reprisal of his role in the stage adaptation). The four additional songs written for the [[The Little Mermaid (musical)|stage adaptation]] were also incorporated into the presentation, accompanied by scenes of the film's original concept art. During the third and final performance, [[Jodi Benson]] replaced Bareilles to reprise her original role as Ariel, while [[Brad Kane]] (the singing voice of the title character of ''[[Aladdin (1992 Disney film)|Aladdin]]'') and [[Susan Egan]] (who played Belle in the stage adaptation of ''[[Beauty and the Beast (1991 film)|Beauty and the Beast]]'') also made special appearances, singing songs from their respective films, and a duet of \"[[A Whole New World]]\".<ref name=\"playbill-hwb\">{{cite web|title=Sara Bareilles and Tituss Burgess Headline Little Mermaid at the Hollywood Bowl Tonight|url=https://www.playbill.com/article/sara-bareilles-and-tituss-burgess-headline-little-mermaid-at-the-hollywood-bowl-tonight|website=Playbill|accessdate=25 May 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"billboard-inconcert\">{{cite web|title=Disney's 'Little Mermaid in Concert' Caps Hollywood Bowl Run With Original Ariel, Jodi Benson|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/7400184/disney-little-mermaid-concert-hollywood-bowl-original-ariel|website=Billboard|access-date=25 May 2017}}</ref>\n\nFrom May 17\u201318, 2019, the Hollywood Bowl hosted another live presentation, titled ''The Little Mermaid:  An Immersive Live-to Film Concert Experience''. These performances once again combined a screening of the film with live renditions of the film's songs, this time starring [[Lea Michele]] as Ariel, [[Harvey Fierstein]] as Ursula, [[Cheech Marin]] as Chef Louis, [[Ken Page]] as Sebastian, [[Peter Gallagher]] as King Triton, Leo Gallo as Prince Eric, and an uncredited actor as Scuttle. This presentation utilized the same four songs written for the stage adaptation.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodbowl.com/events/performances/843/2019-05-18/the-little-mermaid-an-immersive-live-to-film-concert-experience/|title=The Little Mermaid: An Immersive Live-to-Film Concert Experience|accessdate=22 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n===Box office===\nEarly in the production of ''The Little Mermaid'', [[Jeffrey Katzenberg]] cautioned Clements, Musker, and their staff, telling them that since ''The Little Mermaid'' was a \"girl's film\", it would make less money at the box office than ''Oliver & Company'', which had been Disney's biggest animated box office success in a decade.<ref name=\"makingofTLM\" /><ref name=\"wakingsleepingbeauty\" /> However, by the time the film was closer to completion, Katzenberg was convinced ''The Little Mermaid'' would be a hit and the first animated feature to earn more than $100 million in its initial run and become a \"[[Blockbuster (entertainment)|blockbuster]]\" film.<ref name=\"makingofTLM\" /><ref name=\"wakingsleepingbeauty\" />\n\nDuring its original 1989 theatrical release, ''The Little Mermaid'' earned $84.4 million at the North American box office,<ref name=\"boxoffice\">{{cite web|url=https://boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=littlemermaid.htm|title=The Little Mermaid|website=Box Office Mojo|access-date=November 22, 2008}}</ref> falling short of Katzenberg's expectations but earning 64% more than ''Oliver & Company''<ref name=\"wakingsleepingbeauty\" /> and becoming the animated film with the highest gross from its initial run.<ref>{{cite news|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=March 14, 1990|last=Stewart|first=Al|page=29|title='Mermaid' to Sink or Swim in Sell-through}}</ref> The film was theatrically reissued on November 14, 1997, on the same day as ''[[Anastasia (1997 film)|Anastasia]]'', a [[Don Bluth]] animated feature for [[Fox Animation Studios]]. The reissue brought $27.2 million in additional gross.<ref name=\"boxoffice\" /> The film also drew {{US$|123 million|long=no}} in box office earnings outside the United States and Canada between both releases, resulting in a total international box office figure of {{US$|233 million|long=no}}.<ref name=\"DisneyWW\">{{cite magazine |last=D'Alessandro |first=Anthony |magazine=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |title=Cartoon Coffers - Top-Grossing Disney Animated Features at the Worldwide B.O. |date=October 27, 2003 |page=6 |url=https://www.thefreelibrary.com/Tooned+in%3A+Disney%27s+ani+classics+set+the+bar+and+lit+the+way+for...-a0110473946 |accessdate=22 June 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Critical reception===\nReview aggregation site [[Rotten Tomatoes]] reported that the film has a 93% approval score based on 69 reviews and an average rating of 8.2/10. The site's consensus reads \"''The Little Mermaid'' ushered in a new golden era for Disney animation with warm and charming hand-drawn characters and catchy musical sequences\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/the_little_mermaid_1989/|title=The Little Mermaid|website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|access-date=April 7, 2019}}</ref> On Metacritic, the film has a weighted average score of 88 out of 100 based on 24 critics, indicating \"universal acclaim\".\n\n[[Roger Ebert]], film critic for the ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]'', was enthusiastic about the film and wrote that, \"''The Little Mermaid'' is a jolly and inventive animated fantasy\u2014a movie that's so creative and so much fun it deserves comparison with the best Disney work of the past.\" Ebert also commented positively on the character of [[Ariel (The Little Mermaid)|Ariel]], stating, \"... Ariel is a fully realized female character who thinks and acts independently, even rebelliously, instead of hanging around passively while the fates decide her destiny.\"<ref name=\"tlmebertreview\">{{cite news|title=''The Little Mermaid'' review|url=https://www.rogerebert.com/reviews/the-little-mermaid-1989|authorlink=Roger Ebert|first=Roger|last=Ebert|newspaper=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|date=November 17, 1989|access-date=December 23, 2009}}</ref> The staff of ''[[TV Guide]]'' wrote a positive review, praising the film's return to the traditional Disney musical as well as the film's animation. Yet they also wrote that the film is detracted from by the juvenile humor and the human characters' eyes. While still giving a positive review, they stated that the film \"can't compare to the real Disney classics (which appealed equally to both kids and adults).\"<ref>{{cite magazine|title=''The Little Mermaid'' movie review|url=https://www.tvguide.com/movies/little-mermaid/review/127524/|magazine=[[TV Guide]]|access-date=December 23, 2009}}</ref> The staff of ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' praised the film for its cast of characters, [[Ursula (The Little Mermaid)|Ursula]] in particular, as well as its animation, stating that the animation \"proves lush and fluid, augmented by the use of shadow and light as elements like fire, sun and water illuminate the characters.\" They also praised the musical collaboration between [[Howard Ashman]] and [[Alan Menken]] \"whose songs frequently begin slowly but build in cleverness and intensity.\"<ref>{{cite journal|title=''The Little Mermaid'' movie review|url=https://variety.com/1988/film/reviews/the-little-mermaid-1200427784/|magazine=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=January 1, 1989|access-date=December 23, 2009}}</ref>\n\nTodd Gilchrist of [[IGN]] wrote a positive review of the film, stating that the film is \"an almost perfect achievement.\" Gilchrist also praised how the film revived interest in animation as it was released at a time when interest in animation was at a lull.<ref>{{cite web|title=Double Dip Digest: ''The Little Mermaid''|url=https://dvd.ign.com/articles/737/737058p1.html|website=IGN|date=October 3, 2006|access-date=December 23, 2009}}</ref> Hal Hinson of ''[[The Washington Post]]'' wrote a mixed review of the film, referring to it as a \"likably unspectacular adaptation of the Hans Christian Andersen classic.\" Hinson went on to write that the film is average even at its highest points. He wrote that while there is nothing wrong with the film, it would be difficult for children to identify with Ariel and that the characters seemed bland. Hinson concluded his review saying that the film is \"accomplished but uninspiring, ''The Little Mermaid'' has enough to please any kid. All that's missing is the magic.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=''The Little Mermaid'' review|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/style/longterm/movies/review97/littlemermaidhin.htm|newspaper=The Washington Post|date=November 17, 1997|access-date=December 24, 2009}}</ref> ''[[Empire (magazine)|Empire]]'' gave a positive review of the film, stating that \"[''The Little Mermaid'' is] a charmer of a movie, boasting all the ingredients that make a Disney experience something to treasure yet free of all the politically correct, formulaic elements that have bogged down the more recent productions.\"<ref>{{cite magazine|title=The Little Mermaid|url=https://www.empireonline.com/reviews/reviewcomplete.asp?DVDID=5779|magazine=Empire|access-date=July 22, 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121020183802/http://www.empireonline.com/reviews/reviewcomplete.asp?DVDID=5779|archive-date=October 20, 2012|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2008 \u2013 almost 20 years after the film's initial release in 1989 \u2013 [[Yahoo!]] users voted \"''The Little Mermaid''\" as No. 14 on the top 30 animated films of all time. Later, when Yahoo! updated the list in June of the same year, the film remained on the list but dropped six slots to end at #20. (Only three other traditionally animated Disney animated films - ''[[Aladdin (1992 Disney film)|Aladdin]]'', ''[[Beauty and the Beast (1991 film)|Beauty and the Beast]]'', and ''[[The Lion King]]'', respectively - scored above it in the poll even after the update.)<ref>{{cite web|title=Making the Grade: Yahoo Users' Top Rated Animated Films photos on Yahoo! Summer Movie Guide (June 25, 2008)|url=https://movies.yahoo.com/summer-movies/Kung-Fu-Panda/1809826133/photos/358/9268/|publisher=[[Yahoo! Movies]]|access-date=July 15, 2009|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080606233938/http://movies.yahoo.com/summer-movies/Kung-Fu-Panda/1809826133/photos/358/9268/|archive-date=June 6, 2008}}</ref> In 2011, Richard Corliss of [[Time (magazine)|''TIME'']] Magazine named it one of \"The 25 All-TIME Best Animated Films\".<ref>{{cite news|title=The 25 All-TIME Best Animated Films \u2013 The Little Mermaid|url=https://entertainment.time.com/2011/06/23/the-25-all-time-best-animated-films/slide/the-little-mermaid-1989|author=Richard Corliss|work=TIME|date=June 23, 2011|access-date=August 19, 2011}}</ref>\n\n''The Little Mermaid'', Disney's first animated fairy tale since ''[[Sleeping Beauty (1959 film)|Sleeping Beauty]]'' (1959),<ref name=\"makingofTLM\" /> is an important film in animation history for many reasons. Chief among these are its re-establishment of animation as a profitable venture for The Walt Disney Company, as the company's theme parks, television productions, and live-action features had overshadowed the animated output since the 1950s.<ref name=\"wakingsleepingbeauty\" /> ''The Little Mermaid'' was the second film, following ''Oliver & Company'', produced after Disney began expanding its animated output following its successful live action/animated film ''[[Who Framed Roger Rabbit]]'', and became Disney's first animated major box office and critical hit since ''[[The Rescuers]]'' in 1977.<ref name=\"wakingsleepingbeauty\" /> Walt Disney Feature Animation was further expanded as a result of ''The Little Mermaid'' and increasingly successful follow-ups \u2014 ''Beauty and the Beast'' (1991), ''Aladdin'' (1992), and ''The Lion King'' (1994). The staff increased from 300 members in 1988 to 2,200 in 1999 spread across three studios in [[Burbank, California]], Lake Buena Vista, Florida, and [[Montreuil, Seine-Saint-Denis]], France.<ref name=\"WDFAtimeline\">{{Citation|title=After the Magic; Scores of Former Disney Animators and Their Colleagues Have Dispersed to Launch Their Own Studios, Seek New Careers and Discover New Identities \u2013 Determined to Land on Their Feet|url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/orlandosentinel/access/653286501.html?FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&date=Jun+20%2C+2004&author=Roger+Moore%2C+Sentinel+Movie+Critic&pub=Orlando+Sentinel&edition=&startpage=F.1&desc=AFTER+THE+MAGIC+%3B+SCORES+OF+FORMER+DISNEY+ANIMATORS+AND+THEIR+COLLEAGUES+HAVE+DISPERSED+TO+LAUNCH+THEIR+OWN+STUDIOS%2C+SEEK+NEW+CAREERS+AND+DISCOVER+NEW+IDENTITIES+--+DETERMINED+TO+LAND+ON+THEIR+FEET.|first=Roger|last=Moore|newspaper=[[Orlando Sentinel]]|pages=F1|date=June 20, 2004|access-date=May 8, 2010}}</ref>\n\nIn addition, ''The Little Mermaid'' signaled the re-establishment of the musical film format as a standard for Disney animated films. The majority of Disney's most popular animated films from the 1930s on had been musicals, though by the 1970s and 1980s the role of music had been de-emphasized in the films.<ref name=\"makingofTLM\" /> 1988's ''Oliver & Company'' had served as a test of sorts to the success of the musical format before Disney committed to the Broadway-style structure of ''The Little Mermaid''.<ref name=\"makingofTLM\" />\n\n===Accolades===\nIn January 1990, ''The Little Mermaid'' earned three Academy Award nominations, making it the first Disney animated film to earn an Academy Award nomination since ''[[The Rescuers]]'' in 1977. The film won two of the awards, for [[Academy Award for Best Original Score|Best Original Score]] and [[Academy Award for Best Original Song|Best Original Song]] (\"[[Under the Sea]]\"). The film also earned four [[Golden Globe]] nominations, including [[Golden Globe Award for Best Motion Picture \u2013 Musical or Comedy|Best Picture\u2014Comedy or Musical]], and won the awards for [[Golden Globe Award for Best Original Song|Best Original Song]] (\"[[Under the Sea]]\") and [[Golden Globe Award for Best Original Score|Best Original Score]].<ref name=\"nonoms89\">{{cite web|title=The 47th Annual Golden Globe Awards (1952)|url=https://www.goldenglobes.org/browse/year/1989|publisher=Hollywood Foreign Press Association|access-date=May 9, 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110527014121/http://www.goldenglobes.org/browse/year/1989|archive-date=May 27, 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn addition to the box office and critical success of the film itself, the film's soundtrack album earned two awards at the [[33rd Grammy Awards]] in 1991: the [[Grammy Award for Best Album for Children]] and the [[Grammy Award for Best Song Written for Visual Media|Best Song Written Specifically for a Motion Picture or Television]] (\"[[Under the Sea]]\").<ref>{{cite web|title=33rd Annual GRAMMY Awards (1990)|url=https://www.grammy.com/grammys/awards/33rd-annual-grammy-awards|publisher=Grammy.com|access-date=August 27, 2018}}</ref> Bolstered by the film's success and the soundtrack's Oscars, Golden Globes and Grammy Awards, was certified double platinum by the [[Recording Industry Association of America]] in September 1990 for shipments of two million copies of the soundtrack album, an unheard of feat for an animated film at the time.<ref name=\"RIAA\">{{cite web|title=\"Gold and Platinum\" search for \"Little Mermaid\"|url=https://www.riaa.com/gold-platinum/?tab_active=default-award&se=the+little+mermaid|publisher=RIAA.com|access-date=July 28, 2016}}</ref> To date, the soundtrack has been certified six times platinum.<ref name=\"RIAA\" />\n\n''The Little Mermaid'' won two [[Academy Awards]] for [[Academy Award for Best Original Score|Best Original Score]] as well as [[Academy Award for Best Original Song|Best Original Song]] for [[Alan Menken]] and [[Howard Ashman]]'s \"[[Under the Sea]]\", sung by [[Samuel E. Wright]] in a memorable scene.<ref name=\"boxofficemojo1989\">{{cite web|title=1989 Academy Awards Nominations and Winners by Category|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/oscar/chart/?view=allcategories&yr=1989&p=.htm|website=Box Office Mojo|access-date=May 16, 2014}}</ref> Another song from the film, \"[[Kiss the Girl]]\", was nominated but lost to \"[[Under the Sea]]\".<ref name=\"boxofficemojo1989\"/> The film also won two [[Golden Globe]]s for [[Golden Globe Award for Best Original Score|Best Original Score]] as well [[Golden Globe Award for Best Original Song|Best Original Song]] for \"[[Under the Sea]]\". It was also nominated in two other categories, [[Golden Globe Award for Best Motion Picture \u2013 Musical or Comedy|Best Picture\u2014Comedy or Musical]] and another [[Golden Globe Award for Best Original Song|Best Original Song]]. Menken and Ashman also won a [[Grammy Award]] in 1991 for [[Grammy Award for Best Song Written for Visual Media|Best Song Written Specifically for a Motion Picture or Television]] for \"[[Under the Sea]].\"<ref>{{cite news|title=4 Golden Globe Awards To 'Born on 4th of July'|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1990/01/22/movies/4-golden-globe-awards-to-born-on-4th-of-july.html|newspaper=The New York Times|agency=Associated Press|date=January 22, 1990|access-date=May 16, 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe film is recognized by [[American Film Institute]] in these lists:\n* 2002: [[AFI's 100 Years...100 Passions]] \u2013 Nominated<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.afi.com/Docs/100Years/passions400.pdf|title=AFI's 100 Years...100 Passions Nominees|format=PDF|accessdate=August 19, 2016}}</ref>\n* 2003: [[AFI's 100 Years...100 Heroes & Villains]]:\n** [[Ursula (The Little Mermaid)|Ursula]] \u2013 Nominated Villain<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.afi.com/Docs/100Years/handv400.pdf|title=AFI's 100 Years...100 Heroes & Villains Nominees|format=PDF|access-date=August 19, 2016}}</ref>\n* 2004: [[AFI's 100 Years...100 Songs]]:\n** \"[[Under the Sea]]\" \u2013 Nominated<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.afi.com/Docs/100Years/songs400.pdf|title=AFI's 100 Years...100 Songs Nominees|format=PDF|access-date=August 19, 2016}}</ref>\n* 2006: [[AFI's Greatest Movie Musicals]] \u2013 Nominated<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.afi.com/Docs/100Years/musicals_ballot.pdf|title=AFI's Greatest Movie Musicals Nominees|format=PDF|access-date=August 19, 2016}}</ref>\n* 2008: [[AFI's 10 Top 10]]:\n** Nominated Animation Film<ref>{{cite web|url=https://connect.afi.com/site/DocServer/10top10.pdf?docID=381&AddInterest=1781|title=AFI's 10 Top 10 Nominees|format=PDF|accessdate=August 19, 2016|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110716071937/http://connect.afi.com/site/DocServer/10top10.pdf?docID=381&AddInterest=1781|archive-date=July 16, 2011}}</ref>\n\n===Controversy===\nControversy arose regarding the artwork for the film's original VHS release when consumers noticed an oddly shaped structure on the castle, closely resembling a human penis.<ref name=\"Snopes1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.snopes.com/disney/films/mermaid.asp|title=Little Mermaid Phallus|publisher=snopes.com|access-date=July 15, 2009}}</ref><ref name=\"Everyday\">{{cite news|title=Mermaid's Tower is Kettle of Fish|first=Elaine|last=Viets|publisher=Everyday Magazine (St. Louis Post-Dispatch)|date=November 24, 1992}}</ref> Disney and the cover designer insist it was an accident, resulting from a late night rush job to finish the cover artwork. The object does not appear on the cover of the second release of the movie.<ref name=\"Snopes1\"/>\n\nAnother allegation is that the clergyman presiding over the wedding between Eric and Ursula (the latter disguised as Vanessa) is seen to have an [[erection]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Sex Seen (by Some) in Films by Disney|first=Russell W.|last=Smith|date=September 8, 1995|newspaper=Austin American-Statesman|pages=d1}}</ref><ref name=\"Recorder2\" /> The object in question is actually the short, stubby-legged man's knee.<ref name=\"Snopes2\">{{cite web|title=Little Mermaid Minister|url=https://www.snopes.com/disney/films/minister.asp|publisher=snopes.com|access-date=July 15, 2009}}</ref>\n\nThe combined incidents led an Arkansas woman to file suit against The Walt Disney Company in 1995, though she dropped the suit two months later.<ref name=\"Recorder2\">{{cite news|title=Help the Needy; Help Yourself|first=Susan|last=Beck|publisher=[[The Recorder (Massachusetts newspaper)|The Recorder]]|page=2|date=January 5, 1996}}</ref><ref name=\"Snopes2\"/><ref name=\"March 1996\">{{cite news|title=When the Media Miss Real Messages in Subliminal Stories|first=C. Eugene|last=Emery Jr.|publisher=Skeptical Inquirer|page=16|date=March 1996}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Disney Catches Hell|work=Entertainment Weekly}}</ref><ref>Omaha World-Herald \"Filth' Found in Disney Movies Is a Stretch of the Imagination.\"</ref>\n\n==Sequels and spin-offs==\n* An [[The Little Mermaid (TV series)|animated series]] prequel based on the film premiered in late 1992 on the [[Columbia Broadcasting System|CBS]] television network, following Ariel's adventures before the events of the film. The show ran for 31 episodes.\n* A series of shorts starring Sebastian were aired as part of the Disney animated series ''[[Raw Toonage]]'' and ''[[Marsupilami (1993 TV series)|Marsupilami]]''.\n* A [[direct-to-video]] [[sequel]] titled ''[[The Little Mermaid II: Return to the Sea]]'' was released on September 19, 2000. The plot focuses on Ariel's daughter Melody who longs to be a part of the ocean world. \n* A direct-to-video prequel, titled ''[[The Little Mermaid: Ariel's Beginning]]'', was released on August 26, 2008. The story is set before the events of the original film, in which King Triton has banned music from Atlantica.\n* Ariel, Sebastian, Flounder, King Triton, Ursula, Prince Eric, Scuttle, Grimsby and Chef Louie are \"guests\" in ''[[House of Mouse]]''. Ursula appears as one of the leading villains in ''[[Mickey's House of Villains]]''. Ariel, Prince Eric and Ursula also appear in ''[[Mickey's Magical Christmas: Snowed in at the House of Mouse]]''.\n* ''The Little Mermaid'' is featured as a playable world in the ''[[Kingdom Hearts]]'' series known as Atlantica. Characters from the film include, Ariel, Sebastian, Flounder, King Triton, Ursula, Flotsam and Jetsam, Prince Eric, and Glut the shark. Ariel's sisters, Attina and Andrina, also make a small appearance in a ''[[Kingdom Hearts II]]'' mini-game. Ursula is featured as a tutorial boss in ''[[Kingdom Hearts 3D: Dream_Drop_Distance|Dream Drop Distance]]'' and Ariel returns as a Summon in ''[[Kingdom Hearts III]]''.\n* Ariel and the other [[Disney Princess]]es all made [[guest appearance]]s in the 2018 film ''[[Ralph Breaks the Internet]]''.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://ew.com/movies/2017/07/14/wreck-it-ralph-sequel-star-wars-disney-princesses/|title=Wreck-It Ralph sequel will unite the Disney princesses \u2013 and Star Wars!|last=Breznican|first=Anthony|magazine=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|date=July 14, 2017|accessdate=January 2, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Live-action==\n===Live-action film adaptation===\nIn May 2016, ''[[Deadline Hollywood]]'' reported that Disney was in early development for a [[List of Disney live-action reimaginings of animated films|live-action adaptation]] of the film.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2016/05/disney-mulling-the-little-mermaid-live-action-version-1201762354/|title=Disney Mulling Live-Action Version Of 'The Little Mermaid'|last=Jaafer|first=Ali|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|date=May 25, 2016|access-date=March 4, 2017}}</ref> \n\nIn August, it was announced that [[Alan Menken]] would return as the film's composer and write new songs alongside [[Lin-Manuel Miranda]], who will also co-produce the movie with [[Marc Platt (producer)|Marc Platt]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ew.com/article/2016/08/16/little-mermaid-lin-manuel-miranda-alan-menken|title=Lin-Manuel Miranda, Alan Menken team up for live-action Little Mermaid|last=Snetiker|first=Marc|work=Entertainment Weekly|date=August 16, 2016|access-date=March 4, 2017}}</ref> \n\nStudio veterans [[Lindsay Lohan]] and [[Chris Evans (actor)|Chris Evans]] expressed interest in starring in the adaptation.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cnn.com/2017/02/20/entertainment/lindsay-lohan-little-mermaid/|title=Lindsay Lohan really wants a 'Little Mermaid' gig|last=Respers France|first=Lisa|work=CNN|date=February 20, 2017|access-date=May 24, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://ew.com/movies/2017/02/19/lindsay-lohan-wants-bill-condon-direct-her-little-mermaid-musical/|title=Lindsay Lohan wants Bill Condon to direct her in The Little Mermaid musical|last=Nolfi|first=Joey|work=Entertainment Weekly|date=February 19, 2017|access-date=May 24, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://comicbook.com/marvel/2016/06/06/chris-evans-teases-interest-in-prince-eric-west-side-story-remak/|title=Chris Evans Teases Interest In Prince Eric, West Side Story Remake|last=Davis|first=Brandon|work=Comicbook.com|date=June 6, 2016|access-date=April 5, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2017, [[Rob Marshall]] was being courted by the Walt Disney Company to direct the film, while [[Jane Goldman]] would serve as screenwriter.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2017/12/the-little-mermaid-rob-marshall-top-choice-disney-mary-poppins-returns-1202220650/|title=Rob Marshall Top Choice To Helm Disney\u2019s Live Action \u2018The Little Mermaid\u2019|last=Fleming Jr|first=Mike|website=Deadline Hollywood|date=December 6, 2017|access-date=December 6, 2017}}</ref> One year later, Marshall said that he, along with [[John DeLuca]] and Marc Platt were hired to begin developing the project for a film adaptation.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.syfy.com/syfywire/for-director-rob-marshall-mary-poppins-returns-is-a-very-personal-project|title=FOR DIRECTOR ROB MARSHALL, MARY POPPINS RETURNS IS A VERY PERSONAL PROJECT|last=Jaafer|first=Ali|website=[[SyFy Wire]]|date=December 5, 2018|access-date=December 6, 2018}}</ref> In December 2018, Marshall was officially hired as director for the film.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://collider.com/rob-marshall-interview-mary-poppins-returns/#images|title=Rob Marshall on Why He Signed an Overall Deal at Walt Disney Studios|first=Steve|last=Weintraub|work=[[Collider]]|date=December 21, 2018|accessdate=July 3, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.etonline.com/media/videos/little-mermaid-live-action-director-rob-marshall-shares-production-update-exclusive|title='Little Mermaid' Live-Action Director Rob Marshall Shares Production Update (Exclusive)|work=[[Entertainment Tonight]]|date=January 3, 2018|accessdate=July 3, 2019}}</ref> [[David Magee]] will co-write the script with Goldman.\n\nIn May 2019, Menken stated that ''The Little Mermaid'' would be his next project, following the release of the [[Aladdin (2019 film)|live-action adaptation]] of ''[[Aladdin (1992 Disney film)|Aladdin]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.digitalspy.com/movies/a27527282/disney-remakes-aladdin-alan-menken-changes/|title=Disney legend Alan Menken talks about updating Aladdin and the movie he thinks won't get remade|last=April May |first=Rebecca |date=May 20, 2019 |work=[[Digital Spy]] |access-date=June 12, 2019}}</ref> In the following month, [[Melissa McCarthy]], [[Jacob Tremblay]], and [[Awkwafina]] entered early negotiations to portray [[Ursula (The Little Mermaid)|Ursula]], [[List of The Little Mermaid characters|Flounder]], and a gender-swapped [[List of The Little Mermaid characters|Scuttle]], respectively.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2019/film/news/melissa-mccarthy-little-mermaid-ursula-1203217481/|title=Melissa McCarthy in Talks to Play Ursula in Live-Action \u2018Little Mermaid\u2019 (EXCLUSIVE)|last=Kroll|first=Justin|website=Variety|date=June 28, 2019|access-date=June 28, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/disneys-live-action-little-mermaid-eyes-jacob-tremblay-awkwafina-1221947|title=Jacob Tremblay, Awkwafina in Talks for Disney's Live-Action 'Little Mermaid'|last=Kit|first=Borys|website=The Hollywood Reporter|date=July 1, 2019|access-date=July 1, 2019}}</ref> \n\nBy July, [[Halle Bailey]] was cast in the starring role as [[Ariel (The Little Mermaid)|Ariel]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://variety.com/2019/film/news/little-mermaid-halle-bailey-chloe-x-halle-1203234294/ |title=Disney\u2019s Live-Action \u2018Little Mermaid\u2019 Casts Halle Bailey as Ariel |last=Kroll |first=Justin |date=July 3, 2019 |work=Variety|language=en|access-date=July 3, 2019}}</ref> It was also announced that same month that [[Harry Styles]] and [[Javier Bardem]] were in talks to play [[List of The Little Mermaid characters|Prince Eric]] and [[List of The Little Mermaid characters|King Triton]], respectively.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/harry-styles-talks-play-prince-eric-disneys-little-mermaid-1224669 |title=Harry Styles in Talks to Play Prince Eric in Disney's Live-Action 'Little Mermaid' |last=Kit |first=Borys |date=July 16, 2019 |work=The Hollywood Reporter|language=en|access-date=July 16, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://deadline.com/2019/07/javier-bardem-disney-the-little-mermaid-1202648060/|title=Javier Bardem In Talks For Disney\u2019s \u2018The Little Mermaid\u2019 Remake|last=N'Duka|first=Amanda|date=July 17, 2019 |work=Deadline|language=en|access-date=July 17, 2019}}</ref> However, by August, it was revealed that Styles had turned down the role due to focusing on his music career.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://variety.com/2019/film/news/harry-styles-prince-eric-passes-little-mermaid-1203301582/|title=Harry Styles Passes on Prince Eric Role in Live-Action \u2018Little Mermaid\u2019|last=Kroll|first=Justin|date=August 13, 2019|work=Variety|language=en|access-date=August 13, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/harry-styles-explains-turning-down-little-mermaid-prince-eric-role-1237336|title=Harry Styles Explains Passing on 'Little Mermaid' Prince Eric Role|last=Schaffstall|first=Katherine|date=September 6, 2019|work=The Hollywood Reporter|language=en|access-date=September 7, 2019}}</ref> \n\nLater, in September, it was reported that [[Cameron Cuffe]] and [[Jonah Hauer-King]] were two of the finalists to play Prince Eric.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://deadline.com/2019/09/the-little-mermaid-prince-eric-cameron-cuffe-jonah-hauer-king-testing-role-1202743642/|title='The Little Mermaid': 'Krypton's Cameron Cuffe, Jonah Hauer-King Testing for Prince Eric Role|last=Patrick Hipes|first=Anthony D'Alessandro|date=September 24, 2019|work=Deadline Hollywood|language=en|access-date=September 24, 2019}}</ref> In November 2019, Hauer-King was officially cast in the role.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://deadline.com/2019/11/little-mermaid-jonah-hauer-king-wins-roles-of-prince-eric-1202784503/|title=\u2018Little Mermaid\u2019: Jonah Hauer-King Wins Role Of Prince Eric|last=D'Alessandro|first=Anthony D'Alessandro|date=November 12, 2019|work=Deadline Hollywood|language=en|access-date=November 13, 2019}}</ref> \n\nIn October, [[Daveed Diggs]] was also revealed to be in talks to voice [[List of The Little Mermaid characters|Sebastian]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://variety.com/2019/film/news/daveed-diggs-little-mermaid-sebastian-1203293889/|title=Daveed Diggs in Talks to Play Sebastian in Disney's 'Little Mermaid' (EXCLUSIVE)|last=Kroll|first=Justin|date=October 8, 2019|work=Variety|language=en|access-date=October 8, 2019}}</ref> In March 2020 it was confirmed that other characters like Vanessa, Grimsby, Max, Chef Louis, and the rest of Ariel's family, including her mother and sisters, will also appear in the film.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://thedisinsider.com/2020/03/23/alan-menken-confirms-all-the-music-for-the-live-action-adaptation-of-the-little-mermaid-have-been-recorded/|title=Alan Menken Confirms All The Music For The Live-Action Adaptation of \u2018The Little Mermaid\u2019 Have Been Recorded |last=Shuler|first=Skyler|date=March 23, 2020 |work=TheDisInsider|language=en|access-date=March 23, 2020}}</ref>\n\nPrincipal photography was originally scheduled to begin in April 2020 at [[Pinewood Studios]], [[London]], [[United Kingdom]] and in [[Cornwall]], [[South West England]], but production on the film was temporarily halted in March 2020 due to the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Geisinger |first1=Gabriella |title=The Little Mermaid cast: These stars in talks for the Disney remake - who will be in it? |url=https://www.express.co.uk/entertainment/films/1147939/The-Little-Mermaid-cast-Melissa-McCarthy-Awkwafina-Lin-Manuel-Miranda-disney-movie |accessdate=July 3, 2019 |work=Express.co.uk |date=July 2, 2019 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=D'Alessandro|first=Anthony|url=https://deadline.com/2020/03/disney-pausing-production-movies-little-mermaid-home-alone-nightmare-alley-coronavirus-1202882556/|title=Disney Pausing Production On Features \u2018Little Mermaid\u2019, \u2018Home Alone\u2019, \u2018Nightmare Alley\u2019 & More Until Coronavirus Calms Down|work=Deadline Hollywood|date=March 13, 2020|accessdate=March 13, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Kay|first=Jeremy|url=https://www.screendaily.com/news/london-shoot-on-the-little-mermaid-other-disney-live-action-productions-on-hold/5148126.article|title=London shoot on \u2019The Little Mermaid\u2019, other Disney live-action productions on hold|work=Screen International|date=March 13, 2020|accessdate=March 13, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===''The Little Mermaid Live!''===\n{{Main|The Little Mermaid Live!}}\nOn May 16, 2017, [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] announced that it planned to air ''[[The Wonderful World of Disney]]: The Little Mermaid Live'', on October 3, 2017, which would have featured a broadcast of the film with a similar format to the aforementioned Hollywood Bowl concerts. The special aimed to appeal to the recent trend of live made-for-TV productions of Broadway musicals on network television, such as those of [[NBC]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/abc-little-mermaid-rolling-stone-live-musicals-1004221|title=ABC Slates 'Little Mermaid' and Rolling Stone Live Musicals|last=Stanhope|first=Kate|work=The Hollywood Reporter|date=May 16, 2017|access-date=May 16, 2017}}</ref> However, on August 3, 2017, it was announced that the special had been dropped due to budget issues.<ref>{{cite news|last=Levin|first=Gary|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/tv/2017/08/03/abc-drops-plans-little-mermaid-musical/535299001/|title=ABC drops plans for 'Little Mermaid' musical|newspaper=[[USA Today]]|date=August 3, 2017|access-date=August 4, 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn August 5, 2019, it was announced that the project had been revived to mark the 30th anniversary of the film's original release, and would be aired on November 5, 2019. [[Auli'i Cravalho]], [[Queen Latifah]] and [[Shaggy (musician)|Shaggy]] starred as Ariel, Ursula and Sebastian, respectively.<ref name=\"THR\">{{cite news|last=Bentley|first=Jean|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/little-mermaid-live-starring-aulii-cravalho-set-at-abc-1229130|title=Little Mermaid' Live Starring Auli'i Cravalho Set at ABC|newspaper=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|date=August 5, 2019|access-date=August 5, 2019}}</ref> Other cast members included [[John Stamos]] as Chef Louis and [[Graham Phillips (actor)|Graham Phillips]] as Prince Eric.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Petski |first1=Denise |title=John Stamos & Graham Phillips Join \u2018The Little Mermaid Live!\u2019 On ABC |url=https://deadline.com/2019/09/john-stamos-reprise-chef-louis-role-the-little-mermaid-live-abc-graham-phillips-cast-1202744462/ |accessdate=September 26, 2019 |work=Deadline Hollywood |date=September 25, 2019 |language=en}}</ref> The special featured performances of songs from the film and its Broadway adaptations in a themed \"dive-in theater\" setting at the [[Walt Disney Studios (Burbank)|Disney lot]], accompanied by the film itself.<ref name=\"THR\" /><ref>{{cite news |last1=White |first1=Peter |title=\u2018Little Mermaid\u2019 Live Musical: Auli\u2019i Cravalho, Shaggy & Hamish Hamilton Go Under The Sea To Describe ABC\u2019s \u201cInteresting Hybrid\u201d \u2013 TCA |url=https://deadline.com/2019/08/little-mermaid-interesting-hybrid-abc-1202662158/ |accessdate=August 6, 2019 |work=Deadline Hollywood |date=August 5, 2019 |language=en}}</ref> It was produced by [[Done and Dusted]], with director-executive producer [[Hamish Hamilton (director)|Hamish Hamilton]] and executive producer Richard Kraft (who had also worked on the aforementioned concerts).<ref>{{cite news |last1=Otterson |first1=Joe |title=\u2018Little Mermaid\u2019 Set as ABC Live Musical, Auli\u2019i Cravalho to Star |url=https://variety.com/2019/tv/news/little-mermaid-live-abc-aulii-cravalho-1203292102/ |accessdate=August 6, 2019 |work=Variety |date=August 5, 2019 |language=en}}</ref> [[Amber Riley]] portrayed Emcee, the lead singer of the song \"Daughters of Triton\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2019/10/the-little-mermaid-live-amber-riley-emcee-abc-1202756407/|title=\u2018The Little Mermaid Live!\u2019: Amber Riley To Emcee ABC Musical|last=Pedersen|first=Erik|date=2019-10-10|website=Deadline|language=en|access-date=2019-10-10}}</ref> Jodi Benson introduced the special.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://insidethemagic.net/2019/11/jodi-benson-the-little-mermaid-live-kc1/ |title=Jodi Benson, original voice of Ariel, to appear in ABC\u2019s \u201cThe Little Mermaid Live!\u201d |last=Coffey |first=Kelly |date=November 2, 2019 |website=Inside the Magic |access-date=November 22, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn addition to marking the film's anniversary, the special was also used as a pre-launch promotional push for the new [[Disney+]] streaming service, which was launched on November 12, 2019.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Low |first1=Elaine |title=ABC Chief: \u2018Little Mermaid\u2019 Live Musical Will Be Disney Plus Launchpad |url=https://variety.com/2019/tv/news/litte-mermaid-live-musical-abc-disney-plus-1203292569/ |accessdate=August 6, 2019 |work=Variety |date=August 6, 2019 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Andreeva |first1=Nellie |title=\u2018The Little Mermaid\u2019 Live Event A Go On ABC With Auli\u2019i Cravalho As Ariel, Queen Latifah & Shaggy Co-Starring |url=https://deadline.com/2019/08/little-mermaid-live-event-special-abc-with-aulii-cravalho-stars-ariel-queen-latifah-ursula-shaggy-sebastian-1202660483/ |accessdate=August 6, 2019 |work=Deadline Hollywood |date=August 5, 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal bar|Disney|Film|1980s|Animation|Cartoon|United States}}\n* [[Mermaids in popular culture]]\n* [[List of Disney theatrical animated features]]\n* [[List of Disney animated films based on fairy tales]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikiquote}}\n* {{Official website|https://movies.disney.com/the-little-mermaid}}\n* {{IMDb title|0097757}}\n* {{BCDB title|11}}\n* {{Mojo title|littlemermaid}}\n* {{Rotten Tomatoes|the_little_mermaid_1989}}\n\n{{The Little Mermaid (Andersen)}}\n{{Ron Clements and John Musker}}\n{{Howard Ashman}}\n{{Alan Menken}}\n{{Disney Princess}}\n{{Disney theatrical animated features}}\n{{Walt Disney Animation Studios}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Little Mermaid, The}}\n[[Category:The Little Mermaid (franchise)]]\n[[Category:1989 animated films]]\n[[Category:1989 films]]\n[[Category:1980s American animated films]]\n[[Category:American children's animated fantasy films]]\n[[Category:American coming-of-age films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American romantic fantasy films]]\n[[Category:American romantic musical films]]\n[[Category:Animated coming-of-age films]]\n[[Category:Animated films about fish]]\n[[Category:Animated films about friendship]]\n[[Category:Animated films featuring female antagonists]]\n[[Category:Animated musical films]]\n[[Category:Cartoon controversies]]\n[[Category:Disney Renaissance]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Alan Menken]]\n[[Category:Films about prejudice]]\n[[Category:Films about princesses]]\n[[Category:Films about shapeshifting]]\n[[Category:Films about wish fulfillment]]\n[[Category:Films about witchcraft]]\n[[Category:Films based on The Little Mermaid]]\n[[Category:Films directed by John Musker]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Ron Clements]]\n[[Category:Films featuring anthropomorphic characters]]\n[[Category:Films featuring hypnosis]]\n[[Category:Films set in the 19th century]]\n[[Category:Films that won the Best Original Score Academy Award]]\n[[Category:Films that won the Best Original Song Academy Award]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by Howard Ashman]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by John Musker]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by Ron Clements]]\n[[Category:Walt Disney Animation Studios films]]\n[[Category:Walt Disney Pictures films]]\n[[Category:1980s children's animated films]]\n[[Category:3D re-releases]]\n[[Category:Films adapted into comics]]\n[[Category:Films adapted into television programs]]\n[[Category:Films adapted into video games]]\n", "text_old": "{{good article}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2015}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name                  = The Little Mermaid\n| image                 = The Little Mermaid (Official 1989 Film Poster).png\n| alt                   = \n| caption               = Original theatrical release poster by [[John Alvin]]\n| director              = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Ron Clements]]\n* [[John Musker]]\n}}\n| producer              = {{Plainlist|\n* John Musker\n* [[Howard Ashman]]\n}}\n| writer                = {{Plainlist|\n* Ron Clements\n* John Musker\n}}\n| based on              = {{Based on|''[[The Little Mermaid]]''|[[Hans Christian Andersen]]}}\n| starring              = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Ren\u00e9 Auberjonois]]\n* [[Christopher Daniel Barnes]]\n* [[Jodi Benson]]\n* [[Pat Carroll (actress)|Pat Carroll]]\n* [[Paddi Edwards]]\n* [[Buddy Hackett]]\n* Jason Marin\n* [[Kenneth Mars]]\n* [[Edie McClurg]]\n* [[Will Ryan]]\n* [[Ben Wright (English actor)|Ben Wright]]\n* [[Samuel E. Wright]]\n}}\n| music                 = [[Alan Menken]]\n| editing               = Mark Hester\n| production companies  = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Walt Disney Pictures]]\n* [[Walt Disney Animation Studios|Walt Disney Feature Animation]]\n* [[Silver Screen Partners|Silver Screen Partners IV]]\n}}\n| distributor           = [[Walt Disney Studios Motion Pictures|Buena Vista Pictures]]\n| released              = {{Film date|1989|11|17}}\n| runtime               = 83 minutes<!--Theatrical runtime: 82:32--><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbfc.co.uk/releases/little-mermaid-film|title=''THE LITTLE MERMAID'' (U)|work=[[British Board of Film Classification]]|date=December 28, 1989|access-date=April 2, 2016}}</ref>\n| country               = United States\n| language              = English\n| budget                = $40 million<ref name=disneywar>Stewart, James B. (2005). ''[[DisneyWar]]'', p. 104. {{ISBN|0-684-80993-1}}. [[Simon & Schuster]]. Retrieved June 4, 2007.</ref>\n| gross                 = {{US$|233 million|long=no}}<ref name=\"DisneyWW\"/>\n}}\n'''''The Little Mermaid''''' is a 1989 American [[animation|animated]] [[musical film|musical]] [[romantic fantasy film]] produced by [[Walt Disney Animation Studios|Walt Disney Feature Animation]] and [[Walt Disney Pictures]]. The 28th [[List of Walt Disney Animation Studios films|Disney animated feature film]] and the first film in [[The Little Mermaid (franchise)|''The Little Mermaid'' franchise]], it is loosely based on the Danish [[fairy tale]] [[The Little Mermaid|of the same name]] by [[Hans Christian Andersen]]. The film tells the story of a [[mermaid]] Princess named [[Ariel (The Little Mermaid)|Ariel]] who dreams of becoming human and falls in love with a human prince named [[List of Disney's The Little Mermaid characters#Prince Eric|Eric]]. Written and directed by [[Ron Clements]] and [[John Musker]], with music by [[Alan Menken]] and [[Howard Ashman]] (who also served as co-producer alongside John Musker), and art direction by [[Michael Peraza|Michael Peraza Jr.]] and Donald A. Towns, the film features the voices of [[Jodi Benson]], [[Christopher Daniel Barnes]], [[Pat Carroll (actress)|Pat Carroll]], [[Samuel E. Wright]], Jason Marin, [[Kenneth Mars]], [[Buddy Hackett]], and [[Ren\u00e9 Auberjonois]].\n\n''The Little Mermaid'' was released to theaters on November 17, 1989 to critical acclaim, earning praise for the animation, music, and plot. It was also a commercial success, garnering $84 million at the domestic box office during its initial release,<ref>{{cite web|title=The Little Mermaid (1989) \u2013 Box Office Summary|url=https://boxofficemojo.com/movies/?page=releases&id=littlemermaid.htm|website=[[Box Office Mojo]]}}</ref> and {{US$|233 million|long=no}} in total lifetime gross worldwide.<ref name=\"DisneyWW\"/> After the success of the 1986 [[Walt Disney Pictures|Disney]] animated film ''[[The Great Mouse Detective]]''<ref>https://www.mouseplanet.com/9534/How_Basil_Saved_Disney_Feature_Animation_Part_One</ref><ref>https://www.mouseplanet.com/9549/How_Basil_Saved_Disney_Feature_Animation_Part_Two</ref> and the 1988 Disney/[[Amblin Entertainment|Amblin]] live-action/animated film ''[[Who Framed Roger Rabbit]]'', ''The Little Mermaid'' is given credit for breathing life back into the art of Disney animated feature films after a string of critical or commercial failures produced by Disney that dated back to the early 1970s. It also marked the start of the era known as the [[Disney Renaissance]].<ref name=\"Pallant1\">{{cite book|last1=Pallant|first1=Chris|title=Demystifying Disney: A History of Disney Feature Animation|date=2011|publisher=Continuum Publishing|location=New York|isbn=9781441150462|page=89|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=zOCoAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA89|access-date=January 13, 2017}}</ref> The film won two Academy Awards for [[Academy Award for Best Original Score|Best Original Score]] and [[Academy Award for Best Original Song|Best Original Song]] (\"[[Under the Sea]]\").\n\nThe film's success lead to a [[The Little Mermaid (musical)|stage adaptation]] with a book by [[Doug Wright]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Q&A With Grey Gardens Playwright Doug Wright\u2014New York Magazine|url=https://nymag.com/arts/theater/profiles/16075|publisher=Newyorkmetro.com|first=Boris|last=Kachka|date=February 26, 2006|access-date=July 15, 2009}}</ref> and additional songs by [[Alan Menken]] and new lyricist [[Glenn Slater]] opened in Denver in July 2007 and began performances on [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] January 10, 2008<ref>{{cite web|title=Playbill Features: STAGE TO SCREENS: Chatting with Grey Gardens and Little Mermaid Librettist Doug Wright|url=https://www.playbill.com/features/article/stage-to-screens-chatting-with-grey-gardens-and-little-mermaid-librettist-d-130245|work=Playbill|date=January 6, 2006|access-date=July 15, 2009|author=Michael Buckley}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=The Little Mermaid to Celebrate First Broadway Anniversary January 10|url=https://www.playbill.com/news/article/the-little-mermaid-to-celebrate-first-broadway-anniversary-jan.-10-156713|date=January 8, 2009|author=Andrew Gans|work=Playbill|access-date=October 22, 2010}}</ref> starring [[Sierra Boggess]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.playbill.com/article/from-little-mermaid-to-phantom-of-the-opera-sierra-boggess-6-most-memorable-nights-onstage|title=From Little Mermaid to Phantom of the Opera, Sierra Boggess\u2019 6 Most Memorable Nights Onstage|first=Andrew|last=Gans|date=November 3, 2017|publisher=Playbill.com|location=New York City}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.broadway.com/buzz/96308/sierra-boggess-cast-as-ariel-in-disneys-the-little-mermaid/|title=Sierra Boggess Cast as Ariel in Disney's The Little Mermaid|publisher=Broadway.com|location=New York City}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ibdb.com/broadway-production/the-little-mermaid-456222|title=The Little Mermaid on Internet Broadway Database|publisher=The Broadway League|location=New York City}}</ref> Other derived works and material inspired by the movie, include a live-action film adaptation, directed by [[Rob Marshall]], currently in development, and a 2019 [[The Little Mermaid Live!|live musical presentation]] of the film airing on [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] as part of ''[[The Wonderful World of Disney]]''.\n\n==Plot==\n<!-- Per WP:FILMPLOT, plot summaries for feature film articles should be between 400 and 700 words in length. -->\n[[Ariel (The Little Mermaid)|Ariel]] is a 16-year-old mermaid Princess in the kingdom of Atlantica, in the Atlantic Ocean. She is fascinated by the human world above. She ventures out with her best friend [[List of Disney's The Little Mermaid characters#Flounder|Flounder]] to collect human artifacts in her [[grotto]] and often goes to the surface of the ocean to visit [[List of Disney's The Little Mermaid characters#Scuttle|Scuttle]], a seagull who offers inaccurate knowledge of human culture. She swims back to Atlantica and is watched by two eels named [[List of Disney's The Little Mermaid characters#Flotsam and Jetsam|Flotsam and Jetsam]] under orders from [[Ursula (The Little Mermaid)|Ursula]] the sea witch. Ariel ignores the warnings of her father [[List of Disney's The Little Mermaid characters#King Triton|King Triton]], the ruler of Atlantica, and [[List of The Little Mermaid characters#Sebastian|Sebastian]], a crab who serves as Triton's adviser and court composer, that contact with humans is forbidden.\n\nOne night, Ariel, Flounder, and an unwilling Sebastian travel to the surface to watch a celebration for [[List of Disney's The Little Mermaid characters#Prince Eric|Prince Eric]]'s birthday on a ship. Ariel instantly falls in love with Eric. Shortly afterward, a violent storm arrives, which wrecks the ship and tosses Eric overboard. Ariel rescues him and brings him to shore. She sings to him but leaves just as he regains consciousness to avoid being discovered. Fascinated by the memory of her voice, Eric vows to find the girl who saved and sang to him; Ariel vows to find a way to join him in his world. Noticing a change in Ariel's behavior, Triton questions Sebastian and learns of her love for Eric. Triton confronts Ariel in her grotto and destroys the artifacts she collected with his trident. After Triton leaves, Ariel begins weeping. Flotsam and Jetsam convince her to visit Ursula.\n\nUrsula makes a deal with Ariel to transform her into a human for three days in exchange for Ariel's voice, which Ursula puts in a nautilus shell. Within these three days, Ariel must receive the \"kiss of true love\" from Eric to remain a human permanently. Otherwise, she will transform back into a mermaid and belong to Ursula. Ariel accepts and is given human legs and taken to the surface by Flounder and Sebastian. Unbeknownst to Ariel, Ursula, who harbors a secret vendetta against King Triton, plans to use her as a bargaining chip and take over the kingdom. Eric finds Ariel on the beach and takes her to his castle, unaware that she is the one who had rescued him earlier. Ariel spends time with Eric, and at the end of the second day, they almost kiss but are thwarted by Flotsam and Jetsam. Angered at Ariel's near success, Ursula disguises herself as a beautiful young woman named Vanessa and appears onshore singing with Ariel's voice. Eric recognizes the song and, in her disguise, Ursula casts a hypnotic enchantment on Eric to make him forget about Ariel and marry Vanessa instead.\n\nThe next day, Ariel discovers that Eric will be married to Vanessa. Scuttle discovers Vanessa's true identity and informs Ariel, who immediately pursues the wedding barge. While Sebastian informs Triton, Scuttle disrupts the wedding with the help of various sea animals. Through all of the commotion the nautilus shell around Ursula's neck breaks, which restores Ariel's voice back to her and breaks Ursula's enchantment over Eric. Realizing that Ariel is the girl who saved his life, Eric rushes to kiss her, but the sun sets and Ariel transforms back into a mermaid. Ursula then reveals herself and kidnaps Ariel. Triton confronts Ursula and demands Ariel's release. However, the deal is inviolable; Triton makes a new deal to take Ariel's place as Ursula's servant by giving up his trident in order to save his daughter. Ariel is released as Triton transforms into a [[Polyp (zoology)|polyp]] and loses his authority over Atlantica. Ursula declares herself the new ruler, but before she can use the trident, Ariel confronts Ursula and attacks her, and Eric intervenes with a harpoon and hurts Ursula. Ursula attempts to kill Eric, but Ariel intervenes and causes Ursula to inadvertently kill Flotsam and Jetsam. As Ariel hurries to join Eric, the enraged Ursula uses the trident to grow to a monstrous size.\n\nAriel and Eric reunite on the surface just before Ursula grows past and towers over them. She then gains full control of the entire ocean, creating a storm and bringing sunken ships to the surface. As Ursula is about to destroy Ariel with the trident, Eric steers a wrecked ship and kills Ursula by impaling her with its splintered [[bowsprit]]. With Ursula dead, Triton and the other polyps in Ursula's garden revert to their original forms. Realizing that Ariel loves Eric, Triton changes her from a mermaid into a human permanently and approves her marriage to Eric. At the wedding, Ariel and Eric marry on a ship and depart.\n\n==Voice cast==\n{{Main|List of The Little Mermaid characters}}\n* [[Jodi Benson]] as [[Ariel (The Little Mermaid)|Princess Ariel]], the 16-year-old mermaid princess of Atlantica who is fascinated with humans, especially Prince Eric.<ref name=\"DisneyChar\">{{cite book|last=Grant|first=John|title=Encyclopedia of Walt Disney's Animated Characters (Third Edition)|publisher=Hyperion|year=1998|pages=344\u2013345|isbn=0-7868-6336-6}}</ref>\n:* Benson also voices Vanessa, Ursula's human alter ego\n* [[Christopher Daniel Barnes]] as [[List of The Little Mermaid characters#Prince Eric|Prince Eric]], a human prince saved by Ariel and is determined to find and marry her.<ref name=\"nytimes1\">{{cite news|last=|first=|date=July 14, 2014|title=The-Little-Mermaid \u2013 Cast, Crew, Director and Awards|url=https://www.nytimes.com/movies/movie/29563/The-Little-Mermaid/cast/|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|access-date=July 1, 2018|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140715022533/https://www.nytimes.com/movies/movie/29563/The-Little-Mermaid/cast|archive-date=July 15, 2014}}</ref>\n* [[Pat Carroll (actress)|Pat Carroll]] as [[Ursula (The Little Mermaid)|Ursula]], a sea witch who stole Ariel's voice and is determined to ruin her attempts to get Eric to love her.<ref name=\"nytimes1\" />\n* [[Samuel E. Wright]] as [[List of The Little Mermaid characters#Sebastian|Sebastian]], a worrisome Jamaican [[crab]] who serves as King Triton's advisor and court composer.<ref name=\"nytimes1\" />\n* Jason Marin as [[List of The Little Mermaid characters#Flounder|Flounder]], Ariel's [[fish]] best friend.<ref name=\"nytimes1\" />\n* [[Kenneth Mars]] as [[List of The Little Mermaid characters#King Triton|King Triton]], Ariel's father and the ruler of Atlantica who despises humans.<ref name=\"nytimes1\" />\n* [[Buddy Hackett]] as Scuttle, a dimwitted [[seagull]] who shares Ariel's fascination with humans and teaches her about \"human stuff\".<ref name=\"nytimes1\" />\n* [[Paddi Edwards]] as Flotsam and Jetsam, Ursula's symbiotic and insidious pet [[eel]]s.<ref name=\"nytimes1\" />\n* [[Ben Wright (English actor)|Ben Wright]] as Grimsby, Eric's loyal [[valet]].<ref name=\"nytimes1\" />\n* [[Edie McClurg]] as Carlotta, Eric's maid.<ref name=\"nytimes1\" />\n* [[Kimmy Robertson]] as Andrina, Arista, Adella and Alana, four of Ariel's sisters.<ref name=\"nytimes1\" />\n* [[Caroline Vasicek]] as Aquata and Attina, two more of Ariel's sisters.<ref name=\"nytimes1\" />\n* [[Will Ryan]] as Harold, a [[seahorse]] and Triton's herald.<ref name=\"nytimes1\" />\n* [[Ren\u00e9 Auberjonois]] as Chef Louis, Eric's mad chef who attempts to cook Sebastian, but fails.<ref name=\"nytimes1\" />\n\n==Production==\n===Story development===\n[[File:Georges de La Tour - Magdalen of Night Light - WGA12337.jpg|thumb|[[Georges de La Tour]]'s painting ''[[Magdalene with the Smoking Flame]]'' (1640) is shown in the film.]]\n''The Little Mermaid'' was originally planned as part of one of [[Walt Disney]]'s earliest feature films, a proposed [[Anthology film|package film]] featuring vignettes of [[Hans Christian Andersen]] tales.<ref name=\"commentaryTLM\" /> Development started soon after ''[[Snow White and the Seven Dwarfs (1937 film)|Snow White and the Seven Dwarfs]]'' in the late 1930s, but was delayed due to various circumstances.<ref>{{cite web|title=Disney's animated zombies: How classic stories are lost in reinvention|url=http://www.salon.com/2014/05/02/disneys_animated_zombies_how_classic_stories_are_lost_in_reinvention/|work=salon.com}}</ref>\n\nIn 1985, [[Ron Clements]] became interested in a film adaptation of ''The Little Mermaid'' while he was serving as a director on ''[[The Great Mouse Detective]]'' (1986) alongside [[John Musker]].<ref name=\"80srewindmermaid\">{{cite web|title=Making Of... The Little Mermaid Behind The Scenes|url=https://www.fast-rewind.com/making_littlemermaid.htm|work=The 80s Movies Rewind|publisher=Fast-Rewind.com|year=2009|access-date=June 20, 2013}}</ref> Clements discovered the Hans Christian Andersen fairy tale while browsing through a [[bookstore]].<ref name=\"makingofTLM\" /> Believing the story provided an \"ideal basis\" for an animated feature film and keen on creating a film that took place underwater,<ref name=\"80srewindmermaid\" /> Clements wrote and presented a two-page [[Film treatment|treatment]] of ''The Little Mermaid'' [[Walt Disney Studios (division)|Walt Disney Studios]] to chief [[Jeffrey Katzenberg]] at a \"gong show\" idea suggestion meeting. Katzenberg passed the project over, because at that time the studio was in development on a sequel to their live-action mermaid comedy ''[[Splash (film)|Splash]]'' (1984) and felt ''The Little Mermaid'' would be too similar a project.<ref name=\"makingofTLM\" /> The next day, however, Katzenberg approved of the idea for possible development, along with ''[[Oliver & Company]]''. While in production in the 1980s, the staff found, by chance, original story and visual development work done by [[Kay Nielsen]] for Disney's proposed 1930s Andersen feature.<ref name=\"commentaryTLM\" /> Many of the changes made by the staff in the 1930s to Hans Christian Andersen's original story was coincidentally the same as the changes made by Disney writers in the 1980s.<ref name=\"makingofTLM\">(2006) ''Treasures Untold: The Making of Disney's 'The Little Mermaid'' [Documentary featurette]. Bonus material from ''The Little Mermaid: Platinum Edition'' DVD. Walt Disney Home Entertainment.</ref>\n\nThat year Clements and Musker expanded the two-page idea into a 20-page rough script, eliminating the role of the mermaid's grandmother and expanding the roles of the Merman King and the sea witch. However, the film's plans were momentarily shelved as Disney focused its attention on ''[[Who Framed Roger Rabbit]]'' and ''Oliver & Company'' as more immediate releases.<ref name=\"makingofTLM\" /> In 1987, songwriter [[Howard Ashman]] became involved with the writing and development of ''The Little Mermaid'' after he was asked to contribute a song to ''Oliver & Company''. He proposed changing the minor character Clarence, the English-butler crab, to a Jamaican crab and shifting the music style throughout the film to reflect this. At the same time, Katzenberg, Clements, Musker, and Ashman revised the story format to make ''The Little Mermaid'' a musical with a Broadway-style story structure, with the song sequences serving as the tentpoles of the film.<ref name=\"commentaryTLM\" /> Ashman and composer [[Alan Menken]], both noted for their work as the writers of the successful [[Off-Broadway]] stage musical ''[[Little Shop of Horrors (musical)|Little Shop of Horrors]]'', teamed up to compose the entire song score. In 1988, with ''Oliver & Company'' out of the way, ''The Little Mermaid'' was slated as the next major Disney release.<ref name=\"wakingsleepingbeauty\">{{cite video|people=[[Don Hahn|Hahn, Don]]|title=[[Waking Sleeping Beauty]]|medium=Documentary film|publisher=Stone Circle Pictures/Walt Disney Studios Motion Pictures|location=Burbank, California|year=2009}}</ref>\n\n===Animation===\nMore money and resources were dedicated to ''The Little Mermaid'' than any other Disney animated film in decades.<ref name=\"commentaryTLM\" /> Aside from its main animation facility in [[Glendale, California]], Disney opened a satellite feature animation facility during the production of ''The Little Mermaid'' in [[Lake Buena Vista, Florida]] (near [[Orlando, Florida]]), within [[Disney-MGM Studios]] Theme Park at [[Walt Disney World]].<ref name=\"WDFAtimeline\" /> Opening in 1989, the Disney-MGM facility's first projects were to produce an entire [[Roger Rabbit]] cartoon short, ''[[Roller Coaster Rabbit]]'', and to contribute ink and paint support to ''The Little Mermaid''.<ref name=\"WDFAtimeline\" /> Another first for recent years was the filming of live actors and actresses for motion reference material for the animators, a practice used frequently for many of the Disney animated features produced under Walt Disney's supervision. [[Sherri Stoner|Sherri Lynn Stoner]], a former member of Los Angeles' [[Groundlings]] improvisation comedy group, and Joshua Finkel, a Broadway actor, performed key scenes as Ariel and Eric respectively.<ref name=\"makingofTLM\" /><ref name=\"liveactionref\">(2013) ''The Real Little Mermaid: Live Action Reference Model'' [Documentary featurette]. Bonus material from ''The Little Mermaid: Diamond Edition'' Blu-Ray. Walt Disney Home Entertainment.</ref> [[Jodi Benson]] had already been cast as Ariel's voice actor by this time, and her recorded dialogue was used as playback to guide these live-action references.<ref name=\"liveactionref\" /> Before Benson was cast, [[Melissa Fahn]] was considered for the part.<ref>{{cite web|first=Martin|last=Navarez|title=[RECAP] Anime Expo 2018: Day 2|url=https://www.kawaiikakkoiisugoi.com/2018/07/07/recap-anime-expo-2018-day-2/|access-date=November 9, 2018}}</ref>\n\n''The Little Mermaid''{{'s}} supervising animators included [[Glen Keane]] and [[Mark Henn]] on Ariel, Duncan Marjoribanks on Sebastian, [[Andreas Deja]] on King Triton, and Ruben Aquino on Ursula.<ref name=\"commentaryTLM\" /> Originally, Keane had been asked to work on Ursula, as he had established a reputation for drawing large, powerful figures, such as the bear in ''[[The Fox and the Hound]]'' (1981) and Professor Ratigan in ''[[The Great Mouse Detective]]'' (1986). Keane, however, was assigned as one of the two lead artists on the petite Ariel and oversaw the \"Part of Your World\" musical number. He jokingly stated that his wife looks exactly like Ariel \"without the fins.\"<ref>(2004) Interview with Glen Keane. Bonus material from ''[[Pocahontas (1995 film)|Pocahontas: 10th Anniversary Edition]]'' [DVD]. Walt Disney Home Entertainment.</ref> The character's body type and personality were based upon that of [[Alyssa Milano]], then starring on TV's ''[[Who's the Boss?]]'' and the effect of her hair underwater was based on both footage of [[Sally Ride]] when she was in space,<ref name=\"commentaryTLM\" /> and scenes of Stoner in a pool for guidance in animating Ariel's swimming.<ref>{{cite video|title=Under The Scene|location=''The Little Mermaid'' Blu-Ray|publisher=[[Walt Disney Studios Home Entertainment]]|date=2013}}</ref>\n\nThe design of the villainous [[Ursula (The Little Mermaid)|Ursula]] was based upon drag performer [[Divine (performer)|Divine]].<ref name=\"commentaryTLM\" /> An additional early inspiration before Divine was [[Joan Collins]] in her role as [[Alexis Carrington]] in the television show ''[[Dynasty (1981 TV series)|Dynasty]]'', due to a suggestion from Howard Ashman, who was a fan of the series.<ref name=\"HCWIntv\">{{cite AV media|title=''Harry Clayton-Wright interviews the directors of The Little Mermaid''|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=HbnNNx-iV8A|publisher=YouTube|medium=Digital video|people=Clayton-Wright, Harry|format=Web video content|date=September 2, 2013|access-date=September 6, 2013}}</ref> [[Pat Carroll (actress)|Pat Carroll]] was not Clements and Musker's first choice to voice Ursula; the original script had been written with [[Bea Arthur]] of the Disney-owned TV series ''[[The Golden Girls]]'' in mind. After Arthur turned the part down, actresses such as [[Nancy Marchand]], [[Nancy Wilson (rock musician)|Nancy Wilson]], [[Roseanne Barr|Roseanne]], [[Charlotte Rae]], and [[Elaine Stritch]] were considered for the part.<ref name=\"Ursula\" /> Stritch was eventually cast as Ursula, but clashed with Howard Ashman's style of music production and was replaced by Carroll.<ref name=\"Ursula\">{{cite book|title=Makin' Toons: Inside the Most Popular Animated TV Shows and Movies|first=Allan|last=Neuwirth|publisher=Allworth Communications, Inc.|year=2003|pages=[https://archive.org/details/makintoonsinside0000neuw/page/46 46\u201347]|isbn=1-58115-269-8|url=https://archive.org/details/makintoonsinside0000neuw/page/46}}</ref> Various actors auditioned for additional roles in the film, including [[Jim Carrey]] for the role of Prince Eric, and comedians [[Bill Maher]] and [[Michael Richards]] for the role of Scuttle.<ref name=\"HCWIntv\" />\n\nThe underwater setting required the most special effects animation for a Disney animated feature since ''[[Fantasia (1940 film)|Fantasia]]'' in 1940. Effects animation supervisor [[Mark Dindal]] estimated that over a million bubbles were drawn for this film, in addition to the use of other processes such as [[airbrush]]ing, backlighting, superimposition, and some [[computer animation]]. The artistic manpower needed for ''The Little Mermaid'' required Disney to farm out most of the underwater bubble effects animation in the film to Pacific Rim Productions, a China-based firm with production facilities in Beijing.<ref name=\"commentaryTLM\" /> An attempt to use Disney's famed [[multiplane camera]] for the first time in years for quality \"depth\" shots failed because the machine was reputedly in dilapidated condition. The multiplane shots were instead photographed at an outside animation camera facility.<ref name=\"commentaryTLM\">(2006) Audio Commentary by John Musker, Ron Clements, and Alan Menken Bonus material from ''The Little Mermaid: Platinum Edition'' [DVD]. Walt Disney Home Entertainment.</ref>\n\n''The Little Mermaid'' was the last Disney feature film to use the traditional hand-painted cel method of animation. Disney's next film, ''[[The Rescuers Down Under]]'', used a digital method of coloring and combining scanned drawings developed for Disney by [[Pixar]] called CAPS/ink & paint ([[Computer Animation Production System]]), which would eliminate the need for cels, the multiplane camera, and many of the optical effects used for the last time in ''The Little Mermaid''. A CAPS/ink & paint prototype was used experimentally on a few scenes in ''The Little Mermaid'', and one-shot produced using CAPS/ink & paint\u2014the penultimate shot in the film, of Ariel and Eric's wedding ship sailing away under a rainbow\u2014appears in the finished film. [[Computer-generated imagery]] was used to create some of the wrecked ships in the final battle, a staircase behind a shot of Ariel in Eric's castle, and the carriage Eric and Ariel are riding in when she bounces it over a ravine. These objects were animated using 3D wireframe models, which were [[plotter|plotted]] as line art to cels and painted traditionally.<ref name=\"commentaryTLM\" /> The film being both the first film of the [[Disney Renaissance]] and the last to use the [[xerography]] technology used since the late 1950s with ''[[Sleeping Beauty (1959 film)|Sleeping Beauty]]'' made it somewhat of a transitional film between the two Disney eras.<ref>https://www.tor.com/2015/07/23/the-advent-of-xerography-disneys-one-hundred-and-one-dalmatians/</ref><ref>https://ohmy.disney.com/insider/2016/01/11/why-does-101-dalmatians-look-like-that/</ref>\n\n===Music===\n{{Main|The Little Mermaid (soundtrack)}}\n''The Little Mermaid'' was considered by some as \"the film that brought Broadway into cartoons\".<ref>''Aladdin'' Platinum Edition, Disc 2: ''Alan Menken: Musical''</ref> [[Alan Menken]] wrote the [[Academy Awards|Oscar]]-winning score, and collaborated with [[Howard Ashman]] on the songs. One of the film's most prominent songs, \"[[Part of Your World]]\", was nearly cut from the film when it seemingly tested poorly with an audience of school children, who became rowdy during the scene. This caused Jeffrey Katzenberg to feel that the song needed to be cut, an idea that was resisted by Musker, Clements, and Keane. Both Musker and Clements cited the similar situation of the popular song \"[[Over the Rainbow]]\" nearly being cut from 1939's ''[[The Wizard of Oz (1939 film)|The Wizard of Oz]]'' when it was appealing to Katzenberg. Keane pushed for the song to remain until the film was in a more finalized state. During a second test screening, the scene, now colorized and further developed, tested well with a separate child audience, and the musical number was kept.<ref name=\"HCWIntv\" />\n\n==Release==\nThe film was originally released on November 17, 1989, followed by a re-release on November 14, 1997. After the success of the 3D re-release of ''[[The Lion King]]'', Disney announced a 3D re-release of ''The Little Mermaid'' scheduled for September 13, 2013,<ref>{{cite journal|title='Beauty and the Beast,' 'The Little Mermaid,' 'Finding Nemo,' 'Monsters, Inc.' get 3-D re-releases|url=https://www.ew.com/article/2011/10/04/disney-3d-beauty-beast-mermaid|magazine=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|first=Grady|last=Smith|date=October 4, 2011|access-date=October 27, 2011}}</ref> but this was cancelled on January 14, 2013, due to the under-performances of other Disney 3D re-releases until further notice.<ref>{{cite news|title=Disney cancels 'Little Mermaid 3-D,' dates 'Pirates 5' for 2015|url=https://articles.latimes.com/2013/jan/14/entertainment/la-et-ct-disney-cancels-little-mermaid-3d-pirates-5-2015-20130114|first=Ben|last=Fritz|newspaper=The Los Angeles Times|date=January 14, 2013|access-date=January 14, 2013}}</ref> The 3D version was released on [[Blu-ray]] instead,<ref name=\"3D Blu-Ray\">{{cite web|title=Mermaid fall Blu 3D; no Disneynature|url=https://hollywoodinhidef.com/2013/02/little-mermaid-3d-fall-blu-ray-no-disneynature/|author=Scott Hettrick|date=February 9, 2013|access-date=February 11, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=More Details On October's Little Mermaid Blu-ray Set|url=https://www.cinemablend.com/new/Little-Mermaid-Still-Get-3D-Diamond-Edition-37085.html|author=Jessica Rawden|access-date=April 22, 2013}}</ref> but it did play a limited engagement at the [[El Capitan Theatre]] from September to October 2013.<ref>{{cite web|title=Hollywood's El Capitan Will Be the Only Theatre in the World to Screen THE LITTLE MERMAID 3D, 9/13-10/13|url=https://www.broadwayworld.com/bwwmovies/article/Hollywoods-El-Capitan-Will-Be-Only-Theatre-in-the-World-to-Screen-THE-LITTLE-MERMAID-3D-913-1013-20130827|author=Oliver Oliveros|date=August 27, 2013|access-date=November 3, 2013}}</ref> On September 20, 2013, ''The Little Mermaid'' began playing in select theaters where audiences could bring [[iPad]]s and use an app called Second Screen Live.<ref>{{cite journal|url=https://www.ew.com/article/2013/09/10/little-mermaid-second-screen-app|title='The Little Mermaid' returns to theaters with a new-millennium twist: iPads allowed|first=Jennifer|last=Arellano|magazine=Entertainment Weekly|date=September 10, 2013|access-date=September 10, 2013}}</ref> [[AMC Theatres]] screened the movie from September 6-12, 2019.<ref>{{cite journal|url=https://insidethemagic.net/2019/09/disney-princesses-return-to-the-big-screen-kc1/|title=Disney Princesses return to the big screen|first=Kelly|last=Coffey|magazine=Inside the Magic|date=September 5, 2019|access-date=September 6, 2019}}</ref> The film was also screened out of competition at the [[1990 Cannes Film Festival]].<ref name=\"festival-cannes.com\">{{cite web|title=The Little Mermaid|url=https://www.festival-cannes.com/en/films/the-little-mermaid|website=Festival de Cannes|access-date=April 30, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Home media===\nIn a then-atypical and controversial move for a new Disney animated film, ''The Little Mermaid'' was released as part of the [[Walt Disney Classics]] line of VHS, [[Laserdisc]], Betamax, and Video 8 home video releases in May 1990, six months after the release of the film.<ref name=\"wakingsleepingbeauty\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/dp/6302212529|title=<nowiki>The Little Mermaid (A Walt Disney Classic) [VHS</nowiki>&#93;: Ron Clements, John Musker, Ren\u00e9 Auberjonois, Christopher Daniel Barnes, Jodi Benson, Pat Carroll, Paddi Edwards, Buddy Hackett, Jason Marin, Kenneth Mars, Edie McClurg, Will Ryan, Ben Wright, Samuel E. Wright: Movies & TV|publisher=Amazon.com|access-date=November 2, 2011}}</ref> Before ''The Little Mermaid'', only a select number of Disney's catalog animated films had been released to home video, as the company was afraid of upsetting its profitable practice of theatrically reissuing each film every few years.<ref name=\"wakingsleepingbeauty\" /> ''The Little Mermaid'' became that year's top-selling title on home video, with over 10 million units sold (including 7 million in its first month).<ref>{{cite news|title=THE NEW SEASON: HOME ENTERTAINMENT; 'Beauty' Was Big, but Make Way for 'Aladdin'\u2014New York Times|url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9F0CEEDC1039F931A2575AC0A965958260&n=Top%2fReference%2fTimes%20Topics%2fSubjects%2fR%2fRecords%20and%20Achievements|first=Peter M.|last=Nichols|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|date=September 12, 1993|access-date=July 15, 2009}}</ref> The home video release, along with box office and merchandise sales, contributed to ''The Little Mermaid'' generating a total revenue of {{US$|1 billion|long=no}}.<ref>{{cite news|last=Hofmeister|first=Sallie|title=In the Realm of Marketing, 'The Lion King' Rules|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1994/07/12/business/in-the-realm-of-marketing-the-lion-king-rules.html|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=July 12, 1994|access-date=September 26, 2018|language=English}}</ref> This success led to future Disney films being released on home video soon after the end of their theatrical runs, rather than delayed for several years.<ref name=\"wakingsleepingbeauty\" />\n\nFollowing ''The Little Mermaid''{{'}}s 1997 re-release in theaters, a new VHS version was released in March 1998 as part of the Masterpiece Collection and included a bonus music video of [[Jodi Benson]] singing \"Part of Your World\" during the end credits, replacing \"Under the Sea\" as the end credits song.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/dp/0788812408|title=<nowiki>The Little Mermaid (Fully Restored Special Edition) [VHS</nowiki>&#93;: Jodi Benson, Samuel E. Wright, Ren\u00e9 Auberjonois, Christopher Daniel Barnes, Pat Carroll, Paddi Edwards, Buddy Hackett, Jason Marin, Kenneth Mars, Edie McClurg, Will Ryan, Ben Wright, John Musker, Ron Clements, Chris Hubbell, Gerrit Graham, Hans Christian Andersen, Howard Ashman: Movies & TV|publisher=Amazon.com|access-date=November 2, 2011}}</ref> The VHS sold 13 million units and ranked as the third best-selling video of the year.<ref>{{cite web|title=Press Release Page|url=https://www.mickey-mouse.com/pressreleases.htm#TBC|publisher=Mickey-mouse.com|access-date=July 15, 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=VidNews Archives|url=https://www.onvideo.org/oldnews.htm|publisher=OnVideo|access-date=July 15, 2009}}</ref>\n\n''The Little Mermaid'' was released in a \"bare-bones\" limited issue [[DVD]] in 1999, with a standard video transfer.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/dp/B00001QEE7|title=The Little Mermaid (Limited Issue): Jodi Benson, Samuel E. Wright, Ren\u00e9 Auberjonois, Christopher Daniel Barnes, Pat Carroll, Paddi Edwards, Buddy Hackett, Jason Marin, Kenneth Mars, Edie McClurg, Will Ryan, Ben Wright, John Musker, Ron Clements, Chris Hubbell, Gerrit Graham, Hans Christian Andersen, Howard Ashman: Movies & TV|publisher=Amazon.com|access-date=November 2, 2011}}</ref> The film was re-released on DVD on October 3, 2006, as part of the Walt Disney Platinum Editions line of classic Walt Disney animated features, including the song \"Kiss the Girl\" performed by [[Ashley Tisdale]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/dp/B000F8O35U|title=The Little Mermaid (Two-Disc Platinum Edition): Ren\u00e9 Auberjonois, Christopher Daniel Barnes, Jodi Benson, Pat Carroll, Paddi Edwards, Buddy Hackett, Jason Marin, Kenneth Mars, Edie McClurg, Will Ryan, Ben Wright, Samuel E. Wright, Hamilton Camp, Kimmy Robertson, Mickie McGowan, Jim Cummings, Tim Curry, Jennifer Darling, Gerrit Graham, Malachi Pearson: Movies & TV|publisher=Amazon.com|access-date=November 2, 2011}}</ref> Deleted scenes and several in-depth documentaries were included, as well as an Academy Award-nominated short film intended for the shelved ''Fantasia 2006'', ''[[The Little Matchgirl (2006 film)|The Little Matchgirl]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dvdizzy.com/littlemermaid-platinumedition-pressrelease.html|title=The Little Mermaid: Platinum Edition\u2014DVD Press Release|publisher=UltimateDisney|access-date=July 15, 2009}}</ref> The DVD sold 1.6 million units on its first day of release,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.comingsoon.net/news/dvdnews.php?id=16821|title=Record Starts for X-Men and Mermaid\u2014ComingSoon.net|publisher=ComingSoon|access-date=July 15, 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071012130631/http://comingsoon.net/news/dvdnews.php?id=16821|archive-date=October 12, 2007}}</ref> and over 4 million units during its first week, making it the biggest animated DVD debut for October. By the year's end, the DVD had sold about 7 million units and was one of the year's top 10 selling DVDs.<ref>{{cite web|title=Weekly Breakdown Sales For The Little Mermaid DVD|url=https://www.the-numbers.com/movie/Little-Mermaid-The#tab=video-sales|publisher=The-numbers.com|access-date=July 15, 2009}}</ref> The Platinum Edition DVD was released as part of a \"''Little Mermaid'' Trilogy\" boxed set on December 16, 2008.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Little Mermaid Trilogy: The Little Mermaid: Ariel's Beginning, The Little Mermaid, The Little Mermaid II: Return To The Sea Special Edition, .: Movies & TV|url=https://www.amazon.com/dp/B001G2S3XC|publisher=Amazon.com|access-date=November 2, 2011}}</ref> The Platinum Edition of the film, along with its sequels, went on moratorium in January 2009. The film was re-released on a 3-disc [[Blu-ray]]/DVD/Digital Copy combo, a 2-disc Blu-ray/DVD combo and [[3D Blu-ray]] on October 1, 2013, as part of the Walt Disney Diamond Editions line.<ref name=\"3D Blu-Ray\" /><ref>[https://www.cinemablend.com/new/Check-Out-Little-Mermaid-First-Blu-ray-Trailer-35466.html Check Out The Little Mermaid's First Blu-ray Trailer] Retrieved February 13, 2013</ref> ''The Little Mermaid'' was re-released on HD and [[4K resolution|4K]] digital download on February 12, 2019, with a physical media re-release on Blu-ray and [[Ultra HD Blu-ray]] on February 26, 2019, as part of the ''Walt Disney Signature Collection'' in honor of the film's 30th anniversary.\n\n===Live presentations===\nIn June 2016, Disney held special presentations of the film at the [[Hollywood Bowl]] in Los Angeles, titled ''The Little Mermaid in Concert''. The performances combined a screening of ''The Little Mermaid'' with live accompaniment by guest musicians and celebrities, including [[Sara Bareilles]] (who performed as Ariel), [[Tituss Burgess]] (who performed as Sebastian as a reprisal of his role in the stage adaptation), [[Darren Criss]] (who performed as Prince Eric), [[Rebel Wilson]] (who performed as Ursula), Joshua Colley (who performed as Flounder), [[John Stamos]] (who performed as Chef Louis) and [[Norm Lewis]] (who performed as King Triton as a reprisal of his role in the stage adaptation). The four additional songs written for the [[The Little Mermaid (musical)|stage adaptation]] were also incorporated into the presentation, accompanied by scenes of the film's original concept art. During the third and final performance, [[Jodi Benson]] replaced Bareilles to reprise her original role as Ariel, while [[Brad Kane]] (the singing voice of the title character of ''[[Aladdin (1992 Disney film)|Aladdin]]'') and [[Susan Egan]] (who played Belle in the stage adaptation of ''[[Beauty and the Beast (1991 film)|Beauty and the Beast]]'') also made special appearances, singing songs from their respective films, and a duet of \"[[A Whole New World]]\".<ref name=\"playbill-hwb\">{{cite web|title=Sara Bareilles and Tituss Burgess Headline Little Mermaid at the Hollywood Bowl Tonight|url=https://www.playbill.com/article/sara-bareilles-and-tituss-burgess-headline-little-mermaid-at-the-hollywood-bowl-tonight|website=Playbill|accessdate=25 May 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"billboard-inconcert\">{{cite web|title=Disney's 'Little Mermaid in Concert' Caps Hollywood Bowl Run With Original Ariel, Jodi Benson|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/7400184/disney-little-mermaid-concert-hollywood-bowl-original-ariel|website=Billboard|access-date=25 May 2017}}</ref>\n\nFrom May 17\u201318, 2019, the Hollywood Bowl hosted another live presentation, titled ''The Little Mermaid:  An Immersive Live-to Film Concert Experience''. These performances once again combined a screening of the film with live renditions of the film's songs, this time starring [[Lea Michele]] as Ariel, [[Harvey Fierstein]] as Ursula, [[Cheech Marin]] as Chef Louis, [[Ken Page]] as Sebastian, [[Peter Gallagher]] as King Triton, Leo Gallo as Prince Eric, and an uncredited actor as Scuttle. This presentation utilized the same four songs written for the stage adaptation.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodbowl.com/events/performances/843/2019-05-18/the-little-mermaid-an-immersive-live-to-film-concert-experience/|title=The Little Mermaid: An Immersive Live-to-Film Concert Experience|accessdate=22 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n===Box office===\nEarly in the production of ''The Little Mermaid'', [[Jeffrey Katzenberg]] cautioned Clements, Musker, and their staff, telling them that since ''The Little Mermaid'' was a \"girl's film\", it would make less money at the box office than ''Oliver & Company'', which had been Disney's biggest animated box office success in a decade.<ref name=\"makingofTLM\" /><ref name=\"wakingsleepingbeauty\" /> However, by the time the film was closer to completion, Katzenberg was convinced ''The Little Mermaid'' would be a hit and the first animated feature to earn more than $100 million in its initial run and become a \"[[Blockbuster (entertainment)|blockbuster]]\" film.<ref name=\"makingofTLM\" /><ref name=\"wakingsleepingbeauty\" />\n\nDuring its original 1989 theatrical release, ''The Little Mermaid'' earned $84.4 million at the North American box office,<ref name=\"boxoffice\">{{cite web|url=https://boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=littlemermaid.htm|title=The Little Mermaid|website=Box Office Mojo|access-date=November 22, 2008}}</ref> falling short of Katzenberg's expectations but earning 64% more than ''Oliver & Company''<ref name=\"wakingsleepingbeauty\" /> and becoming the animated film with the highest gross from its initial run.<ref>{{cite news|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=March 14, 1990|last=Stewart|first=Al|page=29|title='Mermaid' to Sink or Swim in Sell-through}}</ref> The film was theatrically reissued on November 14, 1997, on the same day as ''[[Anastasia (1997 film)|Anastasia]]'', a [[Don Bluth]] animated feature for [[Fox Animation Studios]]. The reissue brought $27.2 million in additional gross.<ref name=\"boxoffice\" /> The film also drew {{US$|123 million|long=no}} in box office earnings outside the United States and Canada between both releases, resulting in a total international box office figure of {{US$|233 million|long=no}}.<ref name=\"DisneyWW\">{{cite magazine |last=D'Alessandro |first=Anthony |magazine=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |title=Cartoon Coffers - Top-Grossing Disney Animated Features at the Worldwide B.O. |date=October 27, 2003 |page=6 |url=https://www.thefreelibrary.com/Tooned+in%3A+Disney%27s+ani+classics+set+the+bar+and+lit+the+way+for...-a0110473946 |accessdate=22 June 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Critical reception===\nReview aggregation site [[Rotten Tomatoes]] reported that the film has a 93% approval score based on 69 reviews and an average rating of 8.2/10. The site's consensus reads \"''The Little Mermaid'' ushered in a new golden era for Disney animation with warm and charming hand-drawn characters and catchy musical sequences\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/the_little_mermaid_1989/|title=The Little Mermaid|website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|access-date=April 7, 2019}}</ref> On Metacritic, the film has a weighted average score of 88 out of 100 based on 24 critics, indicating \"universal acclaim\".\n\n[[Roger Ebert]], film critic for the ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]'', was enthusiastic about the film and wrote that, \"''The Little Mermaid'' is a jolly and inventive animated fantasy\u2014a movie that's so creative and so much fun it deserves comparison with the best Disney work of the past.\" Ebert also commented positively on the character of [[Ariel (The Little Mermaid)|Ariel]], stating, \"... Ariel is a fully realized female character who thinks and acts independently, even rebelliously, instead of hanging around passively while the fates decide her destiny.\"<ref name=\"tlmebertreview\">{{cite news|title=''The Little Mermaid'' review|url=https://www.rogerebert.com/reviews/the-little-mermaid-1989|authorlink=Roger Ebert|first=Roger|last=Ebert|newspaper=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|date=November 17, 1989|access-date=December 23, 2009}}</ref> The staff of ''[[TV Guide]]'' wrote a positive review, praising the film's return to the traditional Disney musical as well as the film's animation. Yet they also wrote that the film is detracted from by the juvenile humor and the human characters' eyes. While still giving a positive review, they stated that the film \"can't compare to the real Disney classics (which appealed equally to both kids and adults).\"<ref>{{cite magazine|title=''The Little Mermaid'' movie review|url=https://www.tvguide.com/movies/little-mermaid/review/127524/|magazine=[[TV Guide]]|access-date=December 23, 2009}}</ref> The staff of ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' praised the film for its cast of characters, [[Ursula (The Little Mermaid)|Ursula]] in particular, as well as its animation, stating that the animation \"proves lush and fluid, augmented by the use of shadow and light as elements like fire, sun and water illuminate the characters.\" They also praised the musical collaboration between [[Howard Ashman]] and [[Alan Menken]] \"whose songs frequently begin slowly but build in cleverness and intensity.\"<ref>{{cite journal|title=''The Little Mermaid'' movie review|url=https://variety.com/1988/film/reviews/the-little-mermaid-1200427784/|magazine=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=January 1, 1989|access-date=December 23, 2009}}</ref>\n\nTodd Gilchrist of [[IGN]] wrote a positive review of the film, stating that the film is \"an almost perfect achievement.\" Gilchrist also praised how the film revived interest in animation as it was released at a time when interest in animation was at a lull.<ref>{{cite web|title=Double Dip Digest: ''The Little Mermaid''|url=https://dvd.ign.com/articles/737/737058p1.html|website=IGN|date=October 3, 2006|access-date=December 23, 2009}}</ref> Hal Hinson of ''[[The Washington Post]]'' wrote a mixed review of the film, referring to it as a \"likably unspectacular adaptation of the Hans Christian Andersen classic.\" Hinson went on to write that the film is average even at its highest points. He wrote that while there is nothing wrong with the film, it would be difficult for children to identify with Ariel and that the characters seemed bland. Hinson concluded his review saying that the film is \"accomplished but uninspiring, ''The Little Mermaid'' has enough to please any kid. All that's missing is the magic.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=''The Little Mermaid'' review|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/style/longterm/movies/review97/littlemermaidhin.htm|newspaper=The Washington Post|date=November 17, 1997|access-date=December 24, 2009}}</ref> ''[[Empire (magazine)|Empire]]'' gave a positive review of the film, stating that \"[''The Little Mermaid'' is] a charmer of a movie, boasting all the ingredients that make a Disney experience something to treasure yet free of all the politically correct, formulaic elements that have bogged down the more recent productions.\"<ref>{{cite magazine|title=The Little Mermaid|url=https://www.empireonline.com/reviews/reviewcomplete.asp?DVDID=5779|magazine=Empire|access-date=July 22, 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121020183802/http://www.empireonline.com/reviews/reviewcomplete.asp?DVDID=5779|archive-date=October 20, 2012|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2008 \u2013 almost 20 years after the film's initial release in 1989 \u2013 [[Yahoo!]] users voted \"''The Little Mermaid''\" as No. 14 on the top 30 animated films of all time. Later, when Yahoo! updated the list in June of the same year, the film remained on the list but dropped six slots to end at #20. (Only three other traditionally animated Disney animated films - ''[[Aladdin (1992 Disney film)|Aladdin]]'', ''[[Beauty and the Beast (1991 film)|Beauty and the Beast]]'', and ''[[The Lion King]]'', respectively - scored above it in the poll even after the update.)<ref>{{cite web|title=Making the Grade: Yahoo Users' Top Rated Animated Films photos on Yahoo! Summer Movie Guide (June 25, 2008)|url=https://movies.yahoo.com/summer-movies/Kung-Fu-Panda/1809826133/photos/358/9268/|publisher=[[Yahoo! Movies]]|access-date=July 15, 2009|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080606233938/http://movies.yahoo.com/summer-movies/Kung-Fu-Panda/1809826133/photos/358/9268/|archive-date=June 6, 2008}}</ref> In 2011, Richard Corliss of [[Time (magazine)|''TIME'']] Magazine named it one of \"The 25 All-TIME Best Animated Films\".<ref>{{cite news|title=The 25 All-TIME Best Animated Films \u2013 The Little Mermaid|url=https://entertainment.time.com/2011/06/23/the-25-all-time-best-animated-films/slide/the-little-mermaid-1989|author=Richard Corliss|work=TIME|date=June 23, 2011|access-date=August 19, 2011}}</ref>\n\n''The Little Mermaid'', Disney's first animated fairy tale since ''[[Sleeping Beauty (1959 film)|Sleeping Beauty]]'' (1959),<ref name=\"makingofTLM\" /> is an important film in animation history for many reasons. Chief among these are its re-establishment of animation as a profitable venture for The Walt Disney Company, as the company's theme parks, television productions, and live-action features had overshadowed the animated output since the 1950s.<ref name=\"wakingsleepingbeauty\" /> ''The Little Mermaid'' was the second film, following ''Oliver & Company'', produced after Disney began expanding its animated output following its successful live action/animated film ''[[Who Framed Roger Rabbit]]'', and became Disney's first animated major box office and critical hit since ''[[The Rescuers]]'' in 1977.<ref name=\"wakingsleepingbeauty\" /> Walt Disney Feature Animation was further expanded as a result of ''The Little Mermaid'' and increasingly successful follow-ups \u2014 ''Beauty and the Beast'' (1991), ''Aladdin'' (1992), and ''The Lion King'' (1994). The staff increased from 300 members in 1988 to 2,200 in 1999 spread across three studios in [[Burbank, California]], Lake Buena Vista, Florida, and [[Montreuil, Seine-Saint-Denis]], France.<ref name=\"WDFAtimeline\">{{Citation|title=After the Magic; Scores of Former Disney Animators and Their Colleagues Have Dispersed to Launch Their Own Studios, Seek New Careers and Discover New Identities \u2013 Determined to Land on Their Feet|url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/orlandosentinel/access/653286501.html?FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&date=Jun+20%2C+2004&author=Roger+Moore%2C+Sentinel+Movie+Critic&pub=Orlando+Sentinel&edition=&startpage=F.1&desc=AFTER+THE+MAGIC+%3B+SCORES+OF+FORMER+DISNEY+ANIMATORS+AND+THEIR+COLLEAGUES+HAVE+DISPERSED+TO+LAUNCH+THEIR+OWN+STUDIOS%2C+SEEK+NEW+CAREERS+AND+DISCOVER+NEW+IDENTITIES+--+DETERMINED+TO+LAND+ON+THEIR+FEET.|first=Roger|last=Moore|newspaper=[[Orlando Sentinel]]|pages=F1|date=June 20, 2004|access-date=May 8, 2010}}</ref>\n\nIn addition, ''The Little Mermaid'' signaled the re-establishment of the musical film format as a standard for Disney animated films. The majority of Disney's most popular animated films from the 1930s on had been musicals, though by the 1970s and 1980s the role of music had been de-emphasized in the films.<ref name=\"makingofTLM\" /> 1988's ''Oliver & Company'' had served as a test of sorts to the success of the musical format before Disney committed to the Broadway-style structure of ''The Little Mermaid''.<ref name=\"makingofTLM\" />\n\n===Accolades===\nIn January 1990, ''The Little Mermaid'' earned three Academy Award nominations, making it the first Disney animated film to earn an Academy Award nomination since ''[[The Rescuers]]'' in 1977. The film won two of the awards, for [[Academy Award for Best Original Score|Best Original Score]] and [[Academy Award for Best Original Song|Best Original Song]] (\"[[Under the Sea]]\"). The film also earned four [[Golden Globe]] nominations, including [[Golden Globe Award for Best Motion Picture \u2013 Musical or Comedy|Best Picture\u2014Comedy or Musical]], and won the awards for [[Golden Globe Award for Best Original Song|Best Original Song]] (\"[[Under the Sea]]\") and [[Golden Globe Award for Best Original Score|Best Original Score]].<ref name=\"nonoms89\">{{cite web|title=The 47th Annual Golden Globe Awards (1952)|url=https://www.goldenglobes.org/browse/year/1989|publisher=Hollywood Foreign Press Association|access-date=May 9, 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110527014121/http://www.goldenglobes.org/browse/year/1989|archive-date=May 27, 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn addition to the box office and critical success of the film itself, the film's soundtrack album earned two awards at the [[33rd Grammy Awards]] in 1991: the [[Grammy Award for Best Album for Children]] and the [[Grammy Award for Best Song Written for Visual Media|Best Song Written Specifically for a Motion Picture or Television]] (\"[[Under the Sea]]\").<ref>{{cite web|title=33rd Annual GRAMMY Awards (1990)|url=https://www.grammy.com/grammys/awards/33rd-annual-grammy-awards|publisher=Grammy.com|access-date=August 27, 2018}}</ref> Bolstered by the film's success and the soundtrack's Oscars, Golden Globes and Grammy Awards, was certified double platinum by the [[Recording Industry Association of America]] in September 1990 for shipments of two million copies of the soundtrack album, an unheard of feat for an animated film at the time.<ref name=\"RIAA\">{{cite web|title=\"Gold and Platinum\" search for \"Little Mermaid\"|url=https://www.riaa.com/gold-platinum/?tab_active=default-award&se=the+little+mermaid|publisher=RIAA.com|access-date=July 28, 2016}}</ref> To date, the soundtrack has been certified six times platinum.<ref name=\"RIAA\" />\n\n''The Little Mermaid'' won two [[Academy Awards]] for [[Academy Award for Best Original Score|Best Original Score]] as well as [[Academy Award for Best Original Song|Best Original Song]] for [[Alan Menken]] and [[Howard Ashman]]'s \"[[Under the Sea]]\", sung by [[Samuel E. Wright]] in a memorable scene.<ref name=\"boxofficemojo1989\">{{cite web|title=1989 Academy Awards Nominations and Winners by Category|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/oscar/chart/?view=allcategories&yr=1989&p=.htm|website=Box Office Mojo|access-date=May 16, 2014}}</ref> Another song from the film, \"[[Kiss the Girl]]\", was nominated but lost to \"[[Under the Sea]]\".<ref name=\"boxofficemojo1989\"/> The film also won two [[Golden Globe]]s for [[Golden Globe Award for Best Original Score|Best Original Score]] as well [[Golden Globe Award for Best Original Song|Best Original Song]] for \"[[Under the Sea]]\". It was also nominated in two other categories, [[Golden Globe Award for Best Motion Picture \u2013 Musical or Comedy|Best Picture\u2014Comedy or Musical]] and another [[Golden Globe Award for Best Original Song|Best Original Song]]. Menken and Ashman also won a [[Grammy Award]] in 1991 for [[Grammy Award for Best Song Written for Visual Media|Best Song Written Specifically for a Motion Picture or Television]] for \"[[Under the Sea]].\"<ref>{{cite news|title=4 Golden Globe Awards To 'Born on 4th of July'|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1990/01/22/movies/4-golden-globe-awards-to-born-on-4th-of-july.html|newspaper=The New York Times|agency=Associated Press|date=January 22, 1990|access-date=May 16, 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe film is recognized by [[American Film Institute]] in these lists:\n* 2002: [[AFI's 100 Years...100 Passions]] \u2013 Nominated<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.afi.com/Docs/100Years/passions400.pdf|title=AFI's 100 Years...100 Passions Nominees|format=PDF|accessdate=August 19, 2016}}</ref>\n* 2003: [[AFI's 100 Years...100 Heroes & Villains]]:\n** [[Ursula (The Little Mermaid)|Ursula]] \u2013 Nominated Villain<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.afi.com/Docs/100Years/handv400.pdf|title=AFI's 100 Years...100 Heroes & Villains Nominees|format=PDF|access-date=August 19, 2016}}</ref>\n* 2004: [[AFI's 100 Years...100 Songs]]:\n** \"[[Under the Sea]]\" \u2013 Nominated<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.afi.com/Docs/100Years/songs400.pdf|title=AFI's 100 Years...100 Songs Nominees|format=PDF|access-date=August 19, 2016}}</ref>\n* 2006: [[AFI's Greatest Movie Musicals]] \u2013 Nominated<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.afi.com/Docs/100Years/musicals_ballot.pdf|title=AFI's Greatest Movie Musicals Nominees|format=PDF|access-date=August 19, 2016}}</ref>\n* 2008: [[AFI's 10 Top 10]]:\n** Nominated Animation Film<ref>{{cite web|url=https://connect.afi.com/site/DocServer/10top10.pdf?docID=381&AddInterest=1781|title=AFI's 10 Top 10 Nominees|format=PDF|accessdate=August 19, 2016|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110716071937/http://connect.afi.com/site/DocServer/10top10.pdf?docID=381&AddInterest=1781|archive-date=July 16, 2011}}</ref>\n\n===Controversy===\nControversy arose regarding the artwork for the film's original VHS release when consumers noticed an oddly shaped structure on the castle, closely resembling a human penis.<ref name=\"Snopes1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.snopes.com/disney/films/mermaid.asp|title=Little Mermaid Phallus|publisher=snopes.com|access-date=July 15, 2009}}</ref><ref name=\"Everyday\">{{cite news|title=Mermaid's Tower is Kettle of Fish|first=Elaine|last=Viets|publisher=Everyday Magazine (St. Louis Post-Dispatch)|date=November 24, 1992}}</ref> Disney and the cover designer insist it was an accident, resulting from a late night rush job to finish the cover artwork. The object does not appear on the cover of the second release of the movie.<ref name=\"Snopes1\"/>\n\nAnother allegation is that the clergyman presiding over the wedding between Eric and Ursula (the latter disguised as Vanessa) is seen to have an [[erection]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Sex Seen (by Some) in Films by Disney|first=Russell W.|last=Smith|date=September 8, 1995|newspaper=Austin American-Statesman|pages=d1}}</ref><ref name=\"Recorder2\" /> The object in question is actually the short, stubby-legged man's knee.<ref name=\"Snopes2\">{{cite web|title=Little Mermaid Minister|url=https://www.snopes.com/disney/films/minister.asp|publisher=snopes.com|access-date=July 15, 2009}}</ref>\n\nThe combined incidents led an Arkansas woman to file suit against The Walt Disney Company in 1995, though she dropped the suit two months later.<ref name=\"Recorder2\">{{cite news|title=Help the Needy; Help Yourself|first=Susan|last=Beck|publisher=[[The Recorder (Massachusetts newspaper)|The Recorder]]|page=2|date=January 5, 1996}}</ref><ref name=\"Snopes2\"/><ref name=\"March 1996\">{{cite news|title=When the Media Miss Real Messages in Subliminal Stories|first=C. Eugene|last=Emery Jr.|publisher=Skeptical Inquirer|page=16|date=March 1996}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Disney Catches Hell|work=Entertainment Weekly}}</ref><ref>Omaha World-Herald \"Filth' Found in Disney Movies Is a Stretch of the Imagination.\"</ref>\n\n==Sequels and spin-offs==\n* An [[The Little Mermaid (TV series)|animated series]] prequel based on the film premiered in late 1992 on the [[Columbia Broadcasting System|CBS]] television network, following Ariel's adventures before the events of the film. The show ran for 31 episodes.\n* A series of shorts starring Sebastian were aired as part of the Disney animated series ''[[Raw Toonage]]'' and ''[[Marsupilami (1993 TV series)|Marsupilami]]''.\n* A [[direct-to-video]] [[sequel]] titled ''[[The Little Mermaid II: Return to the Sea]]'' was released on September 19, 2000. The plot focuses on Ariel's daughter Melody who longs to be a part of the ocean world. \n* A direct-to-video prequel, titled ''[[The Little Mermaid: Ariel's Beginning]]'', was released on August 26, 2008. The story is set before the events of the original film, in which King Triton has banned music from Atlantica.\n* Ariel, Sebastian, Flounder, King Triton, Ursula, Prince Eric, Scuttle, Grimsby and Chef Louie are \"guests\" in ''[[House of Mouse]]''. Ursula appears as one of the leading villains in ''[[Mickey's House of Villains]]''. Ariel, Prince Eric and Ursula also appear in ''[[Mickey's Magical Christmas: Snowed in at the House of Mouse]]''.\n* ''The Little Mermaid'' is featured as a playable world in the ''[[Kingdom Hearts]]'' series known as Atlantica. Characters from the film include, Ariel, Sebastian, Flounder, King Triton, Ursula, Flotsam and Jetsam, Prince Eric, and Glut the shark. Ariel's sisters, Attina and Andrina, also make a small appearance in a ''[[Kingdom Hearts II]]'' mini-game. Ursula is featured as a tutorial boss in ''[[Kingdom Hearts 3D: Dream_Drop_Distance|Dream Drop Distance]]'' and Ariel returns as a Summon in ''[[Kingdom Hearts III]]''.\n* Ariel and the other [[Disney Princess]]es all made [[guest appearance]]s in the 2018 film ''[[Ralph Breaks the Internet]]''.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://ew.com/movies/2017/07/14/wreck-it-ralph-sequel-star-wars-disney-princesses/|title=Wreck-It Ralph sequel will unite the Disney princesses \u2013 and Star Wars!|last=Breznican|first=Anthony|magazine=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|date=July 14, 2017|accessdate=January 2, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Live-action==\n===Live-action film adaptation===\nIn May 2016, ''[[Deadline Hollywood]]'' reported that Disney was in early development for a [[List of Disney live-action reimaginings of animated films|live-action adaptation]] of the film.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2016/05/disney-mulling-the-little-mermaid-live-action-version-1201762354/|title=Disney Mulling Live-Action Version Of 'The Little Mermaid'|last=Jaafer|first=Ali|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|date=May 25, 2016|access-date=March 4, 2017}}</ref> \n\nIn August, it was announced that [[Alan Menken]] would return as the film's composer and write new songs alongside [[Lin-Manuel Miranda]], who will also co-produce the movie with [[Marc Platt (producer)|Marc Platt]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ew.com/article/2016/08/16/little-mermaid-lin-manuel-miranda-alan-menken|title=Lin-Manuel Miranda, Alan Menken team up for live-action Little Mermaid|last=Snetiker|first=Marc|work=Entertainment Weekly|date=August 16, 2016|access-date=March 4, 2017}}</ref> \n\nStudio veterans [[Lindsay Lohan]] and [[Chris Evans (actor)|Chris Evans]] expressed interest in starring in the adaptation.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cnn.com/2017/02/20/entertainment/lindsay-lohan-little-mermaid/|title=Lindsay Lohan really wants a 'Little Mermaid' gig|last=Respers France|first=Lisa|work=CNN|date=February 20, 2017|access-date=May 24, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://ew.com/movies/2017/02/19/lindsay-lohan-wants-bill-condon-direct-her-little-mermaid-musical/|title=Lindsay Lohan wants Bill Condon to direct her in The Little Mermaid musical|last=Nolfi|first=Joey|work=Entertainment Weekly|date=February 19, 2017|access-date=May 24, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://comicbook.com/marvel/2016/06/06/chris-evans-teases-interest-in-prince-eric-west-side-story-remak/|title=Chris Evans Teases Interest In Prince Eric, West Side Story Remake|last=Davis|first=Brandon|work=Comicbook.com|date=June 6, 2016|access-date=April 5, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2017, [[Rob Marshall]] was being courted by the Walt Disney Company to direct the film, while [[Jane Goldman]] would serve as screenwriter.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2017/12/the-little-mermaid-rob-marshall-top-choice-disney-mary-poppins-returns-1202220650/|title=Rob Marshall Top Choice To Helm Disney\u2019s Live Action \u2018The Little Mermaid\u2019|last=Fleming Jr|first=Mike|website=Deadline Hollywood|date=December 6, 2017|access-date=December 6, 2017}}</ref> One year later, Marshall said that he, along with [[John DeLuca]] and Marc Platt were hired to begin developing the project for a film adaptation.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.syfy.com/syfywire/for-director-rob-marshall-mary-poppins-returns-is-a-very-personal-project|title=FOR DIRECTOR ROB MARSHALL, MARY POPPINS RETURNS IS A VERY PERSONAL PROJECT|last=Jaafer|first=Ali|website=[[SyFy Wire]]|date=December 5, 2018|access-date=December 6, 2018}}</ref> In December 2018, Marshall was officially hired as director for the film.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://collider.com/rob-marshall-interview-mary-poppins-returns/#images|title=Rob Marshall on Why He Signed an Overall Deal at Walt Disney Studios|first=Steve|last=Weintraub|work=[[Collider]]|date=December 21, 2018|accessdate=July 3, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.etonline.com/media/videos/little-mermaid-live-action-director-rob-marshall-shares-production-update-exclusive|title='Little Mermaid' Live-Action Director Rob Marshall Shares Production Update (Exclusive)|work=[[Entertainment Tonight]]|date=January 3, 2018|accessdate=July 3, 2019}}</ref> [[David Magee]] will co-write the script with Goldman.\n\nIn May 2019, Menken stated that ''The Little Mermaid'' would be his next project, following the release of the [[Aladdin (2019 film)|live-action adaptation]] of ''[[Aladdin (1992 Disney film)|Aladdin]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.digitalspy.com/movies/a27527282/disney-remakes-aladdin-alan-menken-changes/|title=Disney legend Alan Menken talks about updating Aladdin and the movie he thinks won't get remade|last=April May |first=Rebecca |date=May 20, 2019 |work=[[Digital Spy]] |access-date=June 12, 2019}}</ref> In the following month, [[Melissa McCarthy]], [[Jacob Tremblay]], and [[Awkwafina]] entered early negotiations to portray [[Ursula (The Little Mermaid)|Ursula]], [[List of The Little Mermaid characters|Flounder]], and a gender-swapped [[List of The Little Mermaid characters|Scuttle]], respectively.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2019/film/news/melissa-mccarthy-little-mermaid-ursula-1203217481/|title=Melissa McCarthy in Talks to Play Ursula in Live-Action \u2018Little Mermaid\u2019 (EXCLUSIVE)|last=Kroll|first=Justin|website=Variety|date=June 28, 2019|access-date=June 28, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/disneys-live-action-little-mermaid-eyes-jacob-tremblay-awkwafina-1221947|title=Jacob Tremblay, Awkwafina in Talks for Disney's Live-Action 'Little Mermaid'|last=Kit|first=Borys|website=The Hollywood Reporter|date=July 1, 2019|access-date=July 1, 2019}}</ref> \n\nBy July, [[Halle Bailey]] was cast in the starring role as [[Ariel (The Little Mermaid)|Ariel]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://variety.com/2019/film/news/little-mermaid-halle-bailey-chloe-x-halle-1203234294/ |title=Disney\u2019s Live-Action \u2018Little Mermaid\u2019 Casts Halle Bailey as Ariel |last=Kroll |first=Justin |date=July 3, 2019 |work=Variety|language=en|access-date=July 3, 2019}}</ref> It was also announced that same month that [[Harry Styles]] and [[Javier Bardem]] were in talks to play [[List of The Little Mermaid characters|Prince Eric]] and [[List of The Little Mermaid characters|King Triton]], respectively.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/harry-styles-talks-play-prince-eric-disneys-little-mermaid-1224669 |title=Harry Styles in Talks to Play Prince Eric in Disney's Live-Action 'Little Mermaid' |last=Kit |first=Borys |date=July 16, 2019 |work=The Hollywood Reporter|language=en|access-date=July 16, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://deadline.com/2019/07/javier-bardem-disney-the-little-mermaid-1202648060/|title=Javier Bardem In Talks For Disney\u2019s \u2018The Little Mermaid\u2019 Remake|last=N'Duka|first=Amanda|date=July 17, 2019 |work=Deadline|language=en|access-date=July 17, 2019}}</ref> However, by August, it was revealed that Styles had turned down the role due to focusing on his music career.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://variety.com/2019/film/news/harry-styles-prince-eric-passes-little-mermaid-1203301582/|title=Harry Styles Passes on Prince Eric Role in Live-Action \u2018Little Mermaid\u2019|last=Kroll|first=Justin|date=August 13, 2019|work=Variety|language=en|access-date=August 13, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/harry-styles-explains-turning-down-little-mermaid-prince-eric-role-1237336|title=Harry Styles Explains Passing on 'Little Mermaid' Prince Eric Role|last=Schaffstall|first=Katherine|date=September 6, 2019|work=The Hollywood Reporter|language=en|access-date=September 7, 2019}}</ref> \n\nLater, in September, it was reported that [[Cameron Cuffe]] and [[Jonah Hauer-King]] were two of the finalists to play Prince Eric.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://deadline.com/2019/09/the-little-mermaid-prince-eric-cameron-cuffe-jonah-hauer-king-testing-role-1202743642/|title='The Little Mermaid': 'Krypton's Cameron Cuffe, Jonah Hauer-King Testing for Prince Eric Role|last=Patrick Hipes|first=Anthony D'Alessandro|date=September 24, 2019|work=Deadline Hollywood|language=en|access-date=September 24, 2019}}</ref> In November 2019, Hauer-King was officially cast in the role.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://deadline.com/2019/11/little-mermaid-jonah-hauer-king-wins-roles-of-prince-eric-1202784503/|title=\u2018Little Mermaid\u2019: Jonah Hauer-King Wins Role Of Prince Eric|last=D'Alessandro|first=Anthony D'Alessandro|date=November 12, 2019|work=Deadline Hollywood|language=en|access-date=November 13, 2019}}</ref> \n\nIn October, [[Daveed Diggs]] was also revealed to be in talks to voice [[List of The Little Mermaid characters|Sebastian]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://variety.com/2019/film/news/daveed-diggs-little-mermaid-sebastian-1203293889/|title=Daveed Diggs in Talks to Play Sebastian in Disney's 'Little Mermaid' (EXCLUSIVE)|last=Kroll|first=Justin|date=October 8, 2019|work=Variety|language=en|access-date=October 8, 2019}}</ref> In March 2020 it was confirmed that other characters like Vanessa, Grimsby, Max, Chef Louis, and the rest of Ariel's family, including her mother and sisters, will also appear in the film.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://thedisinsider.com/2020/03/23/alan-menken-confirms-all-the-music-for-the-live-action-adaptation-of-the-little-mermaid-have-been-recorded/|title=Alan Menken Confirms All The Music For The Live-Action Adaptation of \u2018The Little Mermaid\u2019 Have Been Recorded |last=Shuler|first=Skyler|date=March 23, 2020 |work=TheDisInsider|language=en|access-date=March 23, 2020}}</ref>\n\nPrincipal photography was originally scheduled to begin in April 2020 at [[Pinewood Studios]], [[London]], [[United Kingdom]] and in [[Cornwall]], [[South West England]], but production on the film was temporarily halted in March 2020 due to the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Geisinger |first1=Gabriella |title=The Little Mermaid cast: These stars in talks for the Disney remake - who will be in it? |url=https://www.express.co.uk/entertainment/films/1147939/The-Little-Mermaid-cast-Melissa-McCarthy-Awkwafina-Lin-Manuel-Miranda-disney-movie |accessdate=July 3, 2019 |work=Express.co.uk |date=July 2, 2019 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=D'Alessandro|first=Anthony|url=https://deadline.com/2020/03/disney-pausing-production-movies-little-mermaid-home-alone-nightmare-alley-coronavirus-1202882556/|title=Disney Pausing Production On Features \u2018Little Mermaid\u2019, \u2018Home Alone\u2019, \u2018Nightmare Alley\u2019 & More Until Coronavirus Calms Down|work=Deadline Hollywood|date=March 13, 2020|accessdate=March 13, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Kay|first=Jeremy|url=https://www.screendaily.com/news/london-shoot-on-the-little-mermaid-other-disney-live-action-productions-on-hold/5148126.article|title=London shoot on \u2019The Little Mermaid\u2019, other Disney live-action productions on hold|work=Screen International|date=March 13, 2020|accessdate=March 13, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===''The Little Mermaid Live!''===\n{{Main|The Little Mermaid Live!}}\nOn May 16, 2017, [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] announced that it planned to air ''[[The Wonderful World of Disney]]: The Little Mermaid Live'', on October 3, 2017, which would have featured a broadcast of the film with a similar format to the aforementioned Hollywood Bowl concerts. The special aimed to appeal to the recent trend of live made-for-TV productions of Broadway musicals on network television, such as those of [[NBC]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/abc-little-mermaid-rolling-stone-live-musicals-1004221|title=ABC Slates 'Little Mermaid' and Rolling Stone Live Musicals|last=Stanhope|first=Kate|work=The Hollywood Reporter|date=May 16, 2017|access-date=May 16, 2017}}</ref> However, on August 3, 2017, it was announced that the special had been dropped due to budget issues.<ref>{{cite news|last=Levin|first=Gary|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/tv/2017/08/03/abc-drops-plans-little-mermaid-musical/535299001/|title=ABC drops plans for 'Little Mermaid' musical|newspaper=[[USA Today]]|date=August 3, 2017|access-date=August 4, 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn August 5, 2019, it was announced that the project had been revived to mark the 30th anniversary of the film's original release, and would be aired on November 5, 2019. [[Auli'i Cravalho]], [[Queen Latifah]] and [[Shaggy (musician)|Shaggy]] starred as Ariel, Ursula and Sebastian, respectively.<ref name=\"THR\">{{cite news|last=Bentley|first=Jean|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/little-mermaid-live-starring-aulii-cravalho-set-at-abc-1229130|title=Little Mermaid' Live Starring Auli'i Cravalho Set at ABC|newspaper=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|date=August 5, 2019|access-date=August 5, 2019}}</ref> Other cast members included [[John Stamos]] as Chef Louis and [[Graham Phillips (actor)|Graham Phillips]] as Prince Eric.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Petski |first1=Denise |title=John Stamos & Graham Phillips Join \u2018The Little Mermaid Live!\u2019 On ABC |url=https://deadline.com/2019/09/john-stamos-reprise-chef-louis-role-the-little-mermaid-live-abc-graham-phillips-cast-1202744462/ |accessdate=September 26, 2019 |work=Deadline Hollywood |date=September 25, 2019 |language=en}}</ref> The special featured performances of songs from the film and its Broadway adaptations in a themed \"dive-in theater\" setting at the [[Walt Disney Studios (Burbank)|Disney lot]], accompanied by the film itself.<ref name=\"THR\" /><ref>{{cite news |last1=White |first1=Peter |title=\u2018Little Mermaid\u2019 Live Musical: Auli\u2019i Cravalho, Shaggy & Hamish Hamilton Go Under The Sea To Describe ABC\u2019s \u201cInteresting Hybrid\u201d \u2013 TCA |url=https://deadline.com/2019/08/little-mermaid-interesting-hybrid-abc-1202662158/ |accessdate=August 6, 2019 |work=Deadline Hollywood |date=August 5, 2019 |language=en}}</ref> It was produced by [[Done and Dusted]], with director-executive producer [[Hamish Hamilton (director)|Hamish Hamilton]] and executive producer Richard Kraft (who had also worked on the aforementioned concerts).<ref>{{cite news |last1=Otterson |first1=Joe |title=\u2018Little Mermaid\u2019 Set as ABC Live Musical, Auli\u2019i Cravalho to Star |url=https://variety.com/2019/tv/news/little-mermaid-live-abc-aulii-cravalho-1203292102/ |accessdate=August 6, 2019 |work=Variety |date=August 5, 2019 |language=en}}</ref> [[Amber Riley]] portrayed Emcee, the lead singer of the song \"Daughters of Triton\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2019/10/the-little-mermaid-live-amber-riley-emcee-abc-1202756407/|title=\u2018The Little Mermaid Live!\u2019: Amber Riley To Emcee ABC Musical|last=Pedersen|first=Erik|date=2019-10-10|website=Deadline|language=en|access-date=2019-10-10}}</ref> Jodi Benson introduced the special.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://insidethemagic.net/2019/11/jodi-benson-the-little-mermaid-live-kc1/ |title=Jodi Benson, original voice of Ariel, to appear in ABC\u2019s \u201cThe Little Mermaid Live!\u201d |last=Coffey |first=Kelly |date=November 2, 2019 |website=Inside the Magic |access-date=November 22, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn addition to marking the film's anniversary, the special was also used as a pre-launch promotional push for the new [[Disney+]] streaming service, which was launched on November 12, 2019.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Low |first1=Elaine |title=ABC Chief: \u2018Little Mermaid\u2019 Live Musical Will Be Disney Plus Launchpad |url=https://variety.com/2019/tv/news/litte-mermaid-live-musical-abc-disney-plus-1203292569/ |accessdate=August 6, 2019 |work=Variety |date=August 6, 2019 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Andreeva |first1=Nellie |title=\u2018The Little Mermaid\u2019 Live Event A Go On ABC With Auli\u2019i Cravalho As Ariel, Queen Latifah & Shaggy Co-Starring |url=https://deadline.com/2019/08/little-mermaid-live-event-special-abc-with-aulii-cravalho-stars-ariel-queen-latifah-ursula-shaggy-sebastian-1202660483/ |accessdate=August 6, 2019 |work=Deadline Hollywood |date=August 5, 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal bar|Disney|Film|1980s|Animation|Cartoon|United States}}\n* [[Mermaids in popular culture]]\n* [[List of Disney theatrical animated features]]\n* [[List of Disney animated films based on fairy tales]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikiquote}}\n* {{Official website|https://movies.disney.com/the-little-mermaid}}\n* {{IMDb title|0097757}}\n* {{BCDB title|11}}\n* {{Mojo title|littlemermaid}}\n* {{Rotten Tomatoes|the_little_mermaid_1989}}\n\n{{The Little Mermaid (Andersen)}}\n{{Ron Clements and John Musker}}\n{{Howard Ashman}}\n{{Alan Menken}}\n{{Disney Princess}}\n{{Disney theatrical animated features}}\n{{Walt Disney Animation Studios}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Little Mermaid, The}}\n[[Category:The Little Mermaid (franchise)]]\n[[Category:1989 animated films]]\n[[Category:1989 films]]\n[[Category:1980s American animated films]]\n[[Category:American children's animated fantasy films]]\n[[Category:American coming-of-age films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American romantic fantasy films]]\n[[Category:American romantic musical films]]\n[[Category:Animated coming-of-age films]]\n[[Category:Animated films about fish]]\n[[Category:Animated films about friendship]]\n[[Category:Animated films featuring female antagonists]]\n[[Category:Animated musical films]]\n[[Category:Cartoon controversies]]\n[[Category:Disney Renaissance]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Alan Menken]]\n[[Category:Films about prejudice]]\n[[Category:Films about princesses]]\n[[Category:Films about shapeshifting]]\n[[Category:Films about wish fulfillment]]\n[[Category:Films about witchcraft]]\n[[Category:Films based on The Little Mermaid]]\n[[Category:Films directed by John Musker]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Ron Clements]]\n[[Category:Films featuring anthropomorphic characters]]\n[[Category:Films featuring hypnosis]]\n[[Category:Films set in the 19th century]]\n[[Category:Films that won the Best Original Score Academy Award]]\n[[Category:Films that won the Best Original Song Academy Award]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by Howard Ashman]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by John Musker]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by Ron Clements]]\n[[Category:Walt Disney Animation Studios films]]\n[[Category:Walt Disney Pictures films]]\n[[Category:1980s children's animated films]]\n[[Category:3D re-releases]]\n[[Category:Films adapted into comics]]\n[[Category:Films adapted into television programs]]\n[[Category:Films adapted into video games]]\n", "name_user": "Moe1810", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Little_Mermaid_(1989_film)"}
{"title_page": "Opulence (EP)", "text_new": "{{about|a musical work||Opulence (disambiguation)}}\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = Opulence\n| type       = EP\n| artist     = [[Brooke Candy]]\n| cover      = Brooke candy opulence.png\n| alt        =\n| released   = {{Start date|2014|05|06|df=y}}\n| recorded   = 2013\u201314\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Electropop]], [[Trap music|trap]]\n| length     = 14:58\n| label      = [[RCA Records|RCA]]\n| producer   = {{hlist|A.C.|Cory Enemy|[[Diplo]]|[[Kool Kojak]]|[[Jesse Shatkin]]|[[Shea Taylor]]|[[Sia Furler|Sia]] <small>([[Executive producer|exec.]])</small>|Swizzymack}}\n| prev_title = The Mixtape\n| prev_year  = 2013\n| next_title = [[Sexorcism (Brooke Candy album)|Sexorcism]]\n| next_year  = 2019\n| misc       = {{Singles\n | name        =\n | type        = EP\n | single1     = Opulence\n | single1date = April 22, 2014\n}}\n}}\n\n'''''Opulence''''' is the debut [[extended play]] (EP) by American rapper [[Brooke Candy]], released as [[Music download|digital download]] by [[RCA Records]] on 6 May 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/opulence-ep/id871225498|title=Opulence EP by Brooke Candy on Apple Music|website=[[Apple Music]]|date=2014-05-06}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rcarecords.com/news/brooke-candy-release-opulence-ep-may-6th |title= Brooke Candy To Release Opulence EP On May 6th|publisher=[[RCA Records]]|date=2014-04-28|accessdate=2014-06-25}}</ref> The EP is preceded by the release of title track and lead single \"Opulence\" and is Candy's first major label release. The EP features production from [[Diplo]], [[Kool Kojak]], [[Jesse Shatkin]] and [[Shea Taylor]] among others, including a feature with producer Cory Enemy and songwriting work from [[Mozella]], [[Jesse Saint John]] and [[Sia Furler|Sia]], this later also serving as the [[executive producer]] of the project.<ref name=\"Fact\">{{cite web|url=http://www.factmag.com/2014/04/28/brooke-candy-preps-debut-ep-does-sex-and-violence-in-opulence-video/|title=Brooke Candy preps debut EP, does sex-and-violence in \u2018Opulence\u2019 video|work=[[Fact (UK magazine)|Fact]]|date=April 28, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Background and promotion==\nCandy caught Sia's attention, and contacted via [[Instagram]] with the purpose of writing one song for her. Sia ended up executive producing Candy's debut record, helping her to get a record contract and to find, in Sia's words: \"[a] decent, nice, honest management, and [to] help [her] make the art [she] want to make from a place of positive mental health and love\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://noisey.vice.com/en_uk/article/why-sia-is-one-of-the-most-important-artists-in-the-world-right-now-by-brooke-candy|title=Brooke Candy: Sia is One of the Most Important Artists In the World Right Now|publisher=[[Noisey]]|author=Brooke Candy|date=March 8, 2016}}</ref> Candy signed with [[RCA Records|RCA]] in February 2014.<ref name=RCAsigning>{{cite web|title=Dynamic Rapper / Singer Brooke Candy Signs with RCA Records |url=http://www.rcarecords.com/news/dynamic-rappersinger-brooke-candy-signs-rca-records|publisher=[[RCA Records]]|accessdate=21 November 2015|date=18 February 2014}}</ref> She later joined [[Columbia Records|Columbia]]'s [[United Kingdom|UK]] roster.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://earmilk.com/2014/07/11/brooke-candy-signs-to-columbia-records-and-drops-this-fire-cory-enemy-remix-of-opulance-premiere/|title=Brooke Candy drops this fire Cory Enemy remix of \"Opulence\" [Premiere]|publisher=EARMILK|date=11 July 2014}}</ref> The first single and title track was performed on April 3, 2014 at [[Nicola Formichetti]]'s debut [[Diesel (brand)|Diesel]] fashion show on [[Venice]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ohnotheydidnt.livejournal.com/87338967.html|title=Brooke Candy debuts \"Opulence\" at Formichetti's debut Diesel fashion show in Venice|work=[[Oh No They Didn't]]|author=FUCKFROSTI|date=April 15, 2014}}</ref> It was later released on April 22, 2014 as [[Music download|digital download]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/opulence-single/id849829947|title=Opulence - Single by Brooke Candy on Apple Music|website=[[Apple Music]]|date=2014-04-22}}</ref> along the premiere of its official music video directed by [[Steven Klein (photographer)|Steven Klein]] and styled by Formichetti.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://radio.com/2014/06/02/brooke-candy-opulence-video-formichetti-interview/|title=How Brooke Candy's Artful 'Opulence' Video Primes Her for Pop Stardom|work=[[Radio.com|Radio]]|author=Courtney E. Smith|date=June 2, 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"Fact\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.idolator.com/7515899/brooke-candy-opulence-video-watch|title=Brooke Candy\u2019s \"Opulence\" Video Will Give You Nightmares: Watch The Steven Klein-Directed Clip|website=[[Idolator (website)|Idolator]]|author=Robbie Daw|date=April 28, 2014}}</ref> The song is featured in a scene of [[CSI: Crime Scene Investigation (season 15)#Episodes|CSI's fifteen season episode \"Under My Skin\"]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.songspub.com/News/1336/CSI%20(TV)%20Opulence%20(Brooke%20Candy)|title=CSI (TV) // Opulence (Brooke Candy)|work=[[Songs Music Publishing]]|access-date=March 18, 2017}}</ref> and is part of the soundtrack of the basketball video game [[NBA Live 15]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.easports.com/uk/nba-live/news/2014/nba-live-15-soundtrack|title=NBA LIVE 15 Soundtrack - Complete Track Listing|work=[[EA Games]]|date=October 14, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Critical reception==\nThe EP was generally praised by critics. Kevin Apaza from [[Direct Lyrics]] described it as \"five songs featuring hard-hitting [[synthesizer|synths]], fierce and risqu\u00e9 lyrics, and a swagger by Brooke that can\u2019t be duplicated. She\u2019s making us excited about female rappers again. There just have to be more options than [[Nicki Minaj|Nicki]] or [[Iggy Azalea|Iggy]]!\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.directlyrics.com/review-brooke-candy-opulence-ep-news.html|title=Review: Brooke Candy - 'Opulence' EP|work=[[Direct Lyrics]]|author=Kevin Apaza|date=May 12, 2014}}</ref> Ashley Emma NG from Best Fan also praised the project saying \"''Opulence'' brings a fresh sound that is all Brook[e] Candy. Some may not understand her lascivious and unconventional attitude, but you can\u2019t help but respect her hustle. Her confidence is indestructible, and not once does it come off as cocky.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bestfan.com/blog/2014/05/album-review-brooke-candy-opulence-ep/|title=ALBUM REVIEW: Brooke Candy \u2013 \u2018Opulence\u2019 EP|work=Best Fan|author=Ashley Emma NG|date=May 14, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Track listing==\nCredits taken from [[Qobuz]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.qobuz.com/gb-en/album/opulence-ep-brooke-candy/0886444565158|title=Opulence EP - Brooke Candy \u2013 Download and listen to the album|work=[[Qobuz]]|date=May 6, 2014}}</ref>\n{{Track listing\n| collapsed       = no\n| headline        = \n| extra_column    = Producer(s)\n| total_length    = 14:58\n| title1          = Opulence\n| writer1         = {{hlist|[[Xaphoon Jones|Noah Beresin]]|[[Brooke Candy]]|[[Sia Furler]]|[[Diplo|Thomas Pentz]]|Jordan Safford|[[Jesse Saint John]]}}\n| extra1          = {{hlist|[[Diplo]]|Swizzymack{{ref|a|[a]}}}}\n| length1         = 2:19\n| title2          = Pop Rock\n| writer2         = {{hlist|Furler|[[Shea Taylor|Robert Shea Taylor]]}}\n| extra2          = Shea Taylor\n| length2         = 2:56\n| title3          = Bed Squeak\n| writer3         = {{hlist|Candy|Alexander Castillo Vasquez|[[Kool Kojak|Allan P. Grigg]]|Saint John}}\n| extra3          = {{hlist|A.C.|[[Kool Kojak]]}}\n| length3         = 3:40\n| title4          = Feel Yourself (Alcohol)\n| writer4         = {{hlist|Candy|[[Michel Sanchez]]|[[Wes Madiko|Patrice Delacour]]|Cory Nitta|Saint John}}\n| extra4          = Cory Enemy\n| note4           = featuring Cory Enemy\n| length4         = 3:46\n| title5          = Godzillionaire\n| writer5         = {{hlist|Candy|Furler|Jimmy Joliff|[[MoZella]]|Nitta|[[Jesse Shatkin]]|Saint John}}\n| extra5          = Shatkin\n| length5         = 2:55\n}}\n;Notes\n*<sup>{{note|a|[a]}}</sup> signifies a co-[[record producer|producer]]\n;Sampling credits\n* \"Feel Yourself (Alcohol)\" samples the 1997 song entitled \"[[Alane (song)|Alane]]\" recorded by [[Wes Madiko|Wes]].\n\n==Charts==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\"| Chart (2014)\n! scope=\"col\"| Peak<br/>position\n|-\n{{albumchart|BillboardRandBHipHop|48|artist=Brooke Candy|album=Opulence (EP)|rowheader=true|accessdate=May 24, 2014}}\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Brooke Candy}}\n\n[[Category:2014 debut EPs]]\n[[Category:Electronic dance music EPs]]\n[[Category:Hip hop EPs]]\n[[Category:Pop EPs]]\n[[Category:RCA Records EPs]]\n[[Category:Brooke Candy albums]]\n", "text_old": "{{about|a musical work||Opulence (disambiguation)}}\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = Opulence\n| type       = EP\n| artist     = [[Brooke Candy]]\n| cover      = Brooke candy opulence.png\n| alt        =\n| released   = {{Start date|2014|05|06|df=y}}\n| recorded   = 2013\u201314\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Electropop]], [[Trap music|trap]]\n| length     = 14:58\n| label      = [[RCA Records|RCA]]\n| producer   = {{hlist|A.C.|Cory Enemy|[[Diplo]]|[[Kool Kojak]]|[[Jesse Shatkin]]|[[Shea Taylor]]|[[Sia Furler|Sia]] <small>([[Executive producer|exec.]])</small>|Swizzymack}}\n| prev_title = The Mixtape\n| prev_year  = 2013\n| next_title = [[Sexorcism (Brooke Candy album)|Sexorcism]]\n| next_year  = 2019\n| misc       = {{Singles\n | name        =\n | type        = EP\n | single1     = Opulence\n | single1date = April 22, 2014\n}}\n}}\n\n'''''Opulence''''' is the debut [[extended play]] (EP) by American rapper [[Brooke Candy]], released as [[Music download|digital download]] by [[RCA Records]] on 6 May 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/opulence-ep/id871225498|title=Opulence EP by Brooke Candy on Apple Music|website=[[Apple Music]]|date=2014-05-06}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rcarecords.com/news/brooke-candy-release-opulence-ep-may-6th |title= Brooke Candy To Release Opulence EP On May 6th|publisher=[[RCA Records]]|date=2014-04-28|accessdate=2014-06-25}}</ref> The EP is preceded by the release of title track and lead single \"Opulence\" and is Candy's first major label release. The EP features production from [[Diplo]], [[Kool Kojak]], [[Jesse Shatkin]] and [[Shea Taylor]] among others, including a feature with producer Cory Enemy and songwriting work from [[Mozella]], [[Jesse Saint John]] and [[Sia Furler|Sia]], this later also serving as the [[executive producer]] of the project.<ref name=\"Fact\">{{cite web|url=http://www.factmag.com/2014/04/28/brooke-candy-preps-debut-ep-does-sex-and-violence-in-opulence-video/|title=Brooke Candy preps debut EP, does sex-and-violence in \u2018Opulence\u2019 video|work=[[Fact (UK magazine)|Fact]]|date=April 28, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Background and promotion==\nCandy caught Sia's attention, and contacted via [[Instagram]] with the purpose of writing one song for her. Sia ended up executive producing Candy's debut record, helping her to get a record contract and to find, in Sia's words: \"[a] decent, nice, honest management, and [to] help [her] make the art [she] want to make from a place of positive mental health and love\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://noisey.vice.com/en_uk/article/why-sia-is-one-of-the-most-important-artists-in-the-world-right-now-by-brooke-candy|title=Brooke Candy: Sia is One of the Most Important Artists In the World Right Now|publisher=[[Noisey]]|author=Brooke Candy|date=March 8, 2016}}</ref> Candy signed with [[RCA Records|RCA]] on February 2014.<ref name=RCAsigning>{{cite web|title=Dynamic Rapper / Singer Brooke Candy Signs with RCA Records |url=http://www.rcarecords.com/news/dynamic-rappersinger-brooke-candy-signs-rca-records|publisher=[[RCA Records]]|accessdate=21 November 2015|date=18 February 2014}}</ref> She later joined [[Columbia Records|Columbia]]'s [[United Kingdom|UK]] roster.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://earmilk.com/2014/07/11/brooke-candy-signs-to-columbia-records-and-drops-this-fire-cory-enemy-remix-of-opulance-premiere/|title=Brooke Candy drops this fire Cory Enemy remix of \"Opulence\" [Premiere]|publisher=EARMILK|date=11 July 2014}}</ref> The first single and title track was performed on April 3, 2014 at [[Nicola Formichetti]]'s debut [[Diesel (brand)|Diesel]] fashion show on [[Venice]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ohnotheydidnt.livejournal.com/87338967.html|title=Brooke Candy debuts \"Opulence\" at Formichetti's debut Diesel fashion show in Venice|work=[[Oh No They Didn't]]|author=FUCKFROSTI|date=April 15, 2014}}</ref> It was later released on April 22, 2014 as [[Music download|digital download]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/opulence-single/id849829947|title=Opulence - Single by Brooke Candy on Apple Music|website=[[Apple Music]]|date=2014-04-22}}</ref> along the premiere of its official music video directed by [[Steven Klein (photographer)|Steven Klein]] and styled by Formichetti.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://radio.com/2014/06/02/brooke-candy-opulence-video-formichetti-interview/|title=How Brooke Candy's Artful 'Opulence' Video Primes Her for Pop Stardom|work=[[Radio.com|Radio]]|author=Courtney E. Smith|date=June 2, 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"Fact\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.idolator.com/7515899/brooke-candy-opulence-video-watch|title=Brooke Candy\u2019s \"Opulence\" Video Will Give You Nightmares: Watch The Steven Klein-Directed Clip|website=[[Idolator (website)|Idolator]]|author=Robbie Daw|date=April 28, 2014}}</ref> The song is featured in a scene of [[CSI: Crime Scene Investigation (season 15)#Episodes|CSI's fifteen season episode \"Under My Skin\"]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.songspub.com/News/1336/CSI%20(TV)%20Opulence%20(Brooke%20Candy)|title=CSI (TV) // Opulence (Brooke Candy)|work=[[Songs Music Publishing]]|access-date=March 18, 2017}}</ref> and is part of the soundtrack of the basketball video game [[NBA Live 15]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.easports.com/uk/nba-live/news/2014/nba-live-15-soundtrack|title=NBA LIVE 15 Soundtrack - Complete Track Listing|work=[[EA Games]]|date=October 14, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Critical reception==\nThe EP was generally praised by critics. Kevin Apaza from [[Direct Lyrics]] described it as \"five songs featuring hard-hitting [[synthesizer|synths]], fierce and risqu\u00e9 lyrics, and a swagger by Brooke that can\u2019t be duplicated. She\u2019s making us excited about female rappers again. There just have to be more options than [[Nicki Minaj|Nicki]] or [[Iggy Azalea|Iggy]]!\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.directlyrics.com/review-brooke-candy-opulence-ep-news.html|title=Review: Brooke Candy - 'Opulence' EP|work=[[Direct Lyrics]]|author=Kevin Apaza|date=May 12, 2014}}</ref> Ashley Emma NG from Best Fan also praised the proyect saying \"''Opulence'' brings a fresh sound that is all Brook[e] Candy. Some may not understand her lascivious and unconventional attitude, but you can\u2019t help but respect her hustle. Her confidence is indestructible, and not once does it come off as cocky.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bestfan.com/blog/2014/05/album-review-brooke-candy-opulence-ep/|title=ALBUM REVIEW: Brooke Candy \u2013 \u2018Opulence\u2019 EP|work=Best Fan|author=Ashley Emma NG|date=May 14, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Track listing==\nCredits taken from [[Qobuz]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.qobuz.com/gb-en/album/opulence-ep-brooke-candy/0886444565158|title=Opulence EP - Brooke Candy \u2013 Download and listen to the album|work=[[Qobuz]]|date=May 6, 2014}}</ref>\n{{Track listing\n| collapsed       = no\n| headline        = \n| extra_column    = Producer(s)\n| total_length    = 14:58\n| title1          = Opulence\n| writer1         = {{hlist|[[Xaphoon Jones|Noah Beresin]]|[[Brooke Candy]]|[[Sia Furler]]|[[Diplo|