urg, Pennsylvania)|Walnut Street Bridge]]\n|[[Harrisburg, Pennsylvania]]\n|United States\n|{{dts|format=dmy|1996|January}}\n|Truss bridge\n|As a result of rising flood waters and ice floe from the [[North American blizzard of 1996]], when high floodwaters and a large ice floe lifted the spans off their foundations and swept them down the river.\n|0 killed, 0 injured\n|Lost two of its seven western spans, A third span was damaged and later collapsed into the river.\n|[[File:Walnut street br1.jpg|thumb|upright=.80|Western span of the Walnut Street Bridge after it collapsed during the 1996 flood. The eastern span is still in use for pedestrian traffic.]]\n|-\n|[[Koror-Babeldaob Bridge]]\n|[[Koror]] and [[Babeldaob]]\n|Palau\n|{{dts|format=dmy|1996|September|26}}\n|\n|Collapse following strengthening work\n|2 killed, 4 injured\n|\n|\n|-\n|Baikong Railway bridge\n|[[Ruyuan Yao Autonomous County]], [[Guangdong]]\n|People's Republic of China\n|{{dts|format=dmy|1996|December|20}}\n|\n|During construction\n|29 killed\n|\n|\n|-\n|[[Maccabiah bridge collapse]]\n|[[Tel Aviv]]/[[Ramat Gan]] border\n|Israel\n|{{dts|format=dmy|1997|July|14}}\n|Athletes pedestrian bridge\n|Poor design and construction\n|4 killed (2 killed in collapse, 2 others indirectly), 60 injured\n|\n|During opening of the [[1997 Maccabiah Games|15th Maccabiah Games]], a temporary bridge over the [[river pollution|polluted]] [[Yarkon River]] collapsed causing two deaths the same day and infected many with the deadly fungus ''[[Pseudallescheria boydii]]'', from which 2 more died later.\n|-\n|[[Eschede train disaster]]\n|[[Eschede]]\n|Germany\n|{{dts|format=dmy|1998|June|3}}\n|Road bridge\n|Train disaster\n|101 killed, 105 injured\n|&nbsp;\n|After derailing due to metal fatigue in one of its metal tyres, the Hanover-bound [[InterCityExpress]] [[ICE 1|high speed train]] collided with a road bridge, causing it to collapse onto part of the train. 99 people on board the train, as well as two engineers who were working near the track at the time of the accident, were killed.\n|-\n|Injaka Bridge Collapse\n|[[Bushbuckridge, Mpumalanga]]\n|South Africa\n|{{dts|format=dmy|1998|July|6}}\n|300m 7-span continuous pre-stressed concrete road bridge over the [[Injaka Dam]] under construction.\n|Incompetence and negligence; Steel launch nose not structurally stiff enough; Incorrect temporary works slide path; Incorrectly placed temporary bearings; Incorrect feeding of bearing pads; Under-designed deck slab.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.projectpro.co.za/Project_Parade/Injaka_-_Lesson_Learned/body_injaka_-_lesson_learned.html|title=Injaka Bridge Collapse: Lessons Learned|publisher=|accessdate=15 November 2014}}</ref>\n|14 killed, 19 injured\n|Structure destroyed. Rebuilt completed in 2000, now carrying the R533 over the Injaka Dam (Reservoir).\n|Collapsed while being inspected. Victims include design and consulting engineers.\n|}\n\n== 2000\u2013present ==\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"font-size:94%;\"\n|-\n!Bridge\n!Location\n!Country\n!Date\n!Construction type, use of bridge\n!Reason\n!data-sort-type=\"number\" |Casualties\n!Damage\n!Comments\n|-\n|[[Hoan Bridge]]\n|[[Milwaukee, Wisconsin]]\n|United States\n|{{dts|format=dmy|2000|December|13}}\n|Concrete and steel bridge\n|Northbound right lane began to buckle during the morning rush hour and sagged a few feet below normal. Damage was a result of a violent failure of cross bracing members caused by extremely high stress concentrations in triaxial welds.\n|0 killed, 0 injured\n|Partial collapse\n|Damaged section removed by [[demolition|controlled demolition]] and rebuilt. Remainder of bridge extensively repaired and retrofitted.  Triaxial welds were drilled and most cross bracing members were removed.  Many other similar bridges around the world were also modified in this way as a result of this failure.\n|-\n|[[Hintze Ribeiro disaster]]\n|[[Entre-os-Rios, Castelo de Paiva]]\n|Portugal\n|{{dts|format=dmy|2001|March|4}}\n|Masonry 