 bridge]] with small [[Bascule bridge|bascule]] section\n|Poor materials, unbalanced load and vibrations by subjects singing to honour [[Frederick Ferdinand, Duke of Anhalt-K\u00f6then|the duke]]\n|55 drowned or frozen to death\n|Bridge half damaged, other side demolished\n|<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bernd-nebel.de/bruecken/4_desaster/nienburg/nienburg.html|title=Der Einsturz der Nienburger Schr\u00e4gkettenbr\u00fccke|access-date=2 September 2016|publisher=www.bernd-nebel.de}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Broughton Suspension Bridge]]\n|[[Broughton, Greater Manchester]]\n|England\n|{{dts|format=dmy|1831|April|12}}\n|Suspension bridge over [[River Irwell]]\n|Bolt snapped due to [[mechanical resonance]] caused by marching soldiers\n|0 dead, 20 injured\n|Collapsed at one end, bridge quickly rebuilt and strengthened\n|[[File:Broughton-suspension-bridge.jpg|thumb|upright=.80|The rebuilt Broughton Suspension Bridge in 1883. This disaster caused the \"break step\" rule issued to UK soldiers.]]\n|-\n|[[Yarmouth suspension bridge]]\n||[[Great Yarmouth]]\n|England\n|{{dts|format=dmy|1845|May|2}}\n|[[Suspension bridge]]\n|Spectators crowded the bridge over the [[River Bure]] to view a clown travel the river in a barrel. Their position shifted as the barrel passed; the suspension chains snapped and the bridge deck tipped over.\n|79 people drowned, mainly children.\n|Suspension chains snapped due to overload.\n|<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-norfolk-24240357|title=Great Yarmouth suspension bridge disaster memorial unveiled|access-date=2 September 2016|date=28 September 2013|publisher=BBC}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Dee Bridge disaster|Dee Bridge]]\n|Chester\n|England\n|{{dts|format=dmy|1847|May|24}}\n|[[Cast iron]] [[beam bridge]] over the [[River Dee, Wales|River Dee]]\n|Overload by passenger train on faulty structure\n|5 killed\n|Bridge rendered unusable\n|[[File:Dee bridge disaster.jpg|thumb|upright=.80|The Dee bridge after its collapse. The failure was due to faulty design]]\n|-\n|[[Angers Bridge]]\n|[[Angers]]\n|France\n|{{dts|format=dmy|1850|April|16}}\n|Suspension bridge over [[Maine (river)|Maine River]]\n|Wind and possibly [[resonance]] of soldiers led to collapse\n|226 killed, unknown injured\n|Bridge total damage\n|[[File:Pont de la Basse-Cha\u00eene (7).jpg|thumb|upright=.80|The Angers Bridge after its collapse.]]\n|-\n|[[Wheeling Suspension Bridge]]\n|[[Wheeling, West Virginia]] (then Virginia)\n|United States\n|{{dts|format=dmy|1854|May|17}}\n|Suspension bridge carrying the [[National Road]] over the [[Ohio River]]\n|Torsional movement and vertical undulations caused by wind\n|No casualties\n|Deck destroyed; towers left intact and remain in use today\n|\n|-\n|[[Gasconade Bridge train disaster|Gasconade Bridge]]\n|[[Gasconade, Missouri]]\n|United States\n|{{dts|format=dmy|1855|November|1}}\n|Wooden rail bridge\n|Inaugural train run conducted before temporary trestle work was replaced by permanent structure\n|31 killed, hundreds injured\n|Span from anchorage to first pier destroyed\n|\n|-\n|[[Desjardins Canal Bridge]]\n|[[Desjardins Canal]], Ontario\n|Canada\n|{{dts|format=dmy|1857|March|12}}\n|Rail bridge\n|Mechanical force due to broken locomotive front axle\n|59 killed\n|\n|\n|-\n|[[Sauquoit Creek Bridge]]\n|{{convert|3|miles|abbr=out}} from [[Utica, New York]]\n|United States\n|{{dts|format=dmy|1858|May|11}}\n|Railroad trestle\n|Weight (two trains on the same trestle)\n|9 killed, 55 injured\n|\n|\n|-\n|[[South Bend train wreck|Springbrook Bridge]]\n|Between [[Mishawaka, Indiana|Mishawaka]] and [[South Bend, Indiana]]\n|United States\n|{{dts|format=dmy|1859|June|27}}\n|Railroad embankment bridge\n|Washout\n|41 killed (some accounts of 60 to 70)\n|\n|[[File:SouthBendWreck.jpg|thumb|upright=.80|Known as the Great Mishawaka Train Wreck or the South Bend train wreck]]\n|-\n|[[Bull bridge accident|Bull Bridge]]\n|[[Ambergate]]\n|England\n|{{dts|format=dmy|1860|September|26}}\n|[[Cast iron]] rail bridge\n|Cast iron beam cracked and failed under weight of freight train\n|0 killed 0 injured\n|Total collapse of bridge\n|[[File:Bull bridge1.jpg|thumb|upright|Section of broken girder]]\n|-\n|[[Wootton bridge collapse|Wootton Bridge]]\n|[[Leek Wootton|Wootton]]\n|England\n|{{dts|format=dmy|1861|June|11}}\n|[[Cast iron]] rail bridge\n|Cast iron beams cracked and failed\n|2 killed\n|Total damage to floor\n|[[File:Wootton bridge.jpg|thumb|upright=.80|Wootton Bridge crash, caused by a flawed design & unreliable cast iron, failed from a repair]]\n|-\n|[[Platte Bridge Railroad Tragedy|Platte Bridge]]\n|[[St. Joseph, Missouri]]\n|United States\n|{{dts|format=dmy|1861|September|3}}\n|\n|Sabotage by Confederate partisans during US Civil War.\n|17\u201320 killed, 100 injured\n|\n|\n|-\n|[[Chunky Creek Train Wreck of 1863|Chunky Creek Bridge]]\n|near [[Hickory, Mississippi]]\n|United States\n|{{dts|format=dmy|1863}}\n|\n|Winter flood caused a debris build-up which shifted the bridge trestle.\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n|[[Wood River Junction, Rhode Island|Train bridge]]\n|[[Wood River Junction|Wood River Junction, RI]]\n|United States\n|{{dts|format=dmy|1873|April|19}}\n|\n|Washaway\n|7 killed, 20 injured\n|\n|[[File:Railroad Disaster at Meadow Brook, Rhode Island.jpg|thumb|upright=.80|Railroad Disaster at Meadow Brook, Rhode Island]]\n|-\n|[[Dixon Bridge Disaster|Dixon Bridge]] (aka Truesdell Bridge)\n|[[Dixon, Illinois]]\n|United States\n|4 May 1873\n|Iron vehicular bridge (for pedestrians and carriages) over the [[Rock River (Mississippi River)|Rock River]]\n|Large crowd assembled on one side to view baptism ceremony; bridge design flaw\n|46 killed 56 injured\n|Bridge was a total loss\n|[[File:Truesdell Bridge Collapse, view from the southern shore.jpg|thumb|upright=.80|The collapse of the Dixon (Ill.) Truesdell Bridge, May 4, 1873.]]\n|-\n|[[Letchworth State Park#Old Portageville Bridge Fire|Portage Bridge]]\n|[[Portageville, New York]]\n|United States\n|{{dts|format=dmy|1875|May|5}}\n|[[Wooden]] [[beam bridge]] 